\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes, I can! (LAUGHS) Story of my life! Well, I was born into a coloured middle-class Jamaican family. I\rquote ll
 tell you a bit about the background in a minute. But that, in itself, is an important thing, because as you know Jamaica, they\rquote 
re relatively few, but they are the elite. We were 20 years away from Independence, but they were already clearly the coming class \endash  they\rquote re going to be the governing class, the business class, etc. \endash 
 and so my father belonged to this solid middle-class elite. My father had been from a lower middle-class family \endash  his father kept a drug store \endash  but he had been quite well educated, a
nd he got a job, very early on, with the United Fruit Company. He stayed there most, well, the whole of his early working life, and he was the first local Jamaican to hold every post he had, and finally ended up as the Chief Accountant. Before that, peopl
e
 had been sent down from Boston to top the Company, etc.. So he was a rising, he was part of the rising social group (LAUGHS), as it were. My mother, however, came from a very different background. Her mother was a postmistress, and her father was, I thin
k - may have been what I would call \'93Jamaican white\'94 \endash  you\rquote 
ll understand what I mean! You know, close relationship to an English birth, but whether he was actually English or first generation, or whatever - they were much fairer than my father \endash  the whole o
f that family. They were Grossets. And they lived in Port Antonio... My father\rquote s family lived in Old Harbour, which is to the south of the Island, just out of Kingston - Kingston-Spanish Town-Old Harbour. It\rquote 
s the less interesting, less picturesque part of Jamaica. It\rquote s very flat, there are very few beaches for quite a while. It\rquote s not like the north coast. The north coast is another world altogether. So he comes from there and his family\rquote 
s lived there all the time. They\rquote ve only relatively recently sold the 
house they had. My mother, on the other hand, came from this Grosset family, who were a very prominent family in Port Antonio. Port Antonio was then a bustling, thriving town, on the north of the Island, and bustling and thriving because it was the last p
ort of call of the banana boats. They would come to Kingston, load; go to Montego Bay, load; go to Port Antonio, load \endash  and then back to England. So, you know, it\rquote 
s full of life and so on. And her uncles were the leading doctor, and the leading lawyer of the place. And my mother\rquote s mother, who was really quite poor, allowed my mother\rquote s uncles, in effect, to adopt her It wasn\rquote 
t formal, but they brought her up rather than my mother bringing her up. Now, they were definitely part of the Port Antonio elite, much fairer than my father in colour \endash  skin colour \endash  prominent well-known family, and we\rquote 
ve since discovered, through Catherine\rquote s work on slave owners, that John Grosset, in the 19th century, was a plantation owner, active pro-slaver, wrote pamphlets opposing a
bolition, was a Conservative MP for Cheltenham, so they are a classic absentee family - not absentee, I think they must have established a full residence in Jamaica, but they were part of that group that are other English planters, plantation owners, or p
eople who travelled between the two places. Now, they owned a small estate as well as this professional standing that they had, and that\rquote 
s where my mother was brought up. And she was brought as if she were an estate girl. There were cousins, a bit fairer than she was, and there was no formal adoption, but she was brought up alongside them \endash 
 not quite, because they were all sent, at a certain point, to England, to be educated, as was often the common practice then. She didn\rquote t go, and I think she resented the fact that her cousins went and she didn\rquote 
t go. But she was part of that world. She adored and idolised both her aunt and her uncle who brought her up. And they acculturated her to small plantation life. You know, she drove the buggies, and she gave commands
, etc.. (LAUGHS) So my father, coming upwardly mobile, rising from a lower middle-class family, but attached to a foreign firm \endash  which meant that he has prospects \endash 
 and my mother not quite absorbed into the professional elite of Port Antonio, but with very
 good connections and strong links to England and all that, etc., imbibed the habits of a young plantation girl. Well, this is the marriage that produced me! (LAUGHS) He went to Port Antonio to work for United Fruit, she was there, they got married. They 
got married on Armistice Day, First World War. But she brought into my family all those habits, all those expectations, everything. She\rquote 
s very handsome, very strong, very self-willed person. She should have worked, they took her to work in her uncle\rquote s office \endash  law firm \endash 
 she loved it. But the family was her work. That production of the family (LAUGHS) was her labour! And she\rquote d have my father as a good prospect, because he was coming up, and he represented sort of new emerging Jamaica. But, of course, he neve
r quite earned enough money for her, so there was always a feeling that she was slightly disappointed that she had settled for a good marriage, but at a slightly lower standard of living from that to which the estate \endash  the small estate \endash 
 had accustomed her. The estate is still there, it\rquote s called \'93Norwich\'94, it\rquote s above Port Antonio, looks out beautifully on to the sea. I\rquote 
ve filmed in the old house, which is falling apart. Beautiful African palms up the driveway, and it was owned for a long time by Eartha Kitt
. Okay, so this mix is the family I was brought into. My brother, George, was 12 years older than me. Then my sister, Pat, who is six years older than me, so we\rquote re very spaced out. I was the last. And my brother had what was called \'93pigmentosa
\'94, so he had very bad sight, and they brought him to England at one point, to see whether they could do anything about it. They couldn\rquote 
t. He did go to the States to study agricultural chemistry, but he eventually went blind. He was very bright, and very sweet-natured, etc.. So he was the apple of my family\rquote s eye. My sister was a turbulent adolescent, and my mother, my mother didn
\rquote t say to her \endash  in my hearing \endash  \'93Of course, women are not interesting, they don\rquote t have any part \endash  \'93 you know, they had to give up the game as i
t were! So she and my sister, in her adolescence, quarrelled infinitely. Then me. Well, I\rquote ll tell you one apocryphal story, then I\rquote ll stop and you ask me some questions! (LAUGHS) Apocryphal story, which I don\rquote t know whether it\rquote 
s true or not, but in a way, it doesn\rquote t matter whether it\rquote s true, because it\rquote 
s true in another sense, symbolically true. When, finally, I was born, and we were then living in Kingston, my father was working in Kingston at the Head Office, United Fruit Company, we were part of the King
ston middle-class. When my sister looked into the crib and saw me, she said, \'93Where did you get this coolie baby from?\'94
 Because, as you know, within that family, there was every shade! My mother was the fairest, my brother was almost as fair as her. My sister was a bit darker. I was distinctly darker, much closer to my father and my father\rquote 
s family. But I had the sense, from God knows when, that I was a kind of anomaly there. I didn\rquote t quite fit in. I didn\rquote t understand anything about race or colour \endash  you know, I\rquote m talking about very early on. If I showed you 
\endash  I have a picture of myself at about six, sitting on the steps of our house, with an air rifle, and I do look (a) depressed, and (b) murderous! (LAUGHS) I\rquote m about to shoot somebody, I don\rquote t know who, or 
what for! (LAUGHS) I never felt at home in that place. Never felt at home. Their aspirations for me were not my aspirations. They saw me in a way that I didn\rquote 
t see myself. And that was very much because of their attitude to the rest of Jamaica. They were in the struggle to identify us \endash  that middle-class, at that stage \endash  with the Colonial power, with England \endash 
 you know, my mother really thought she was English, some sort of some genetic error had occurred to make her not English! Indeed, her mother\rquote s name was \'93Hopwood\'94
, and she became convinced, at one stage, that this was a derivation from Hapsburg! So, you know, this is the Freudian Colonial family romance. Okay? My father wasn\rquote t quite like that. He was a very quiet person \endash 
 studious, read the papers, neve
r went into debt for anything, careful accountant, smoked stubby cigars in the evening. Go for his walk, have a rum and ginger on the veranda. And he never really stopped my mother from doing anything. She just governed the place. Okay, that\rquote 
s that! (LAUGH) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Well, you say, as a child, you had a sense there was something odd going on, but when did you begin to see that in terms of colour and class? ST: Well, that is hard to tell, Paul. I remember the riots in 1938, which is thought to be - This comes 
at the end of the terrible depression Jamaica suffered in the thirties, lots of unemployment. It\rquote s the beginnings of Trade Unionism in Jamaica, and of political parties, yes? So it\rquote 
s really the opening of modern politics in Jamaica. Huge riots, unemploymen
t riots. And I remember, my family was in, as you can imagine, panic. All of them thought the mobs, the black masses are going to rise up and come up into Upper Kingston and savage us in our beds \endash 
 all sorts of rumours! And I must have been six, and I thought, \'93What is this about? What is going on?\'94 You know, \'93Why are they carrying on like that? Who are they?\'94
 Well, I knew who they were because the veranda talk that I had been exposed to throughout my life, was entirely about that. That\rquote s what it was about,
 it was about class and colour, class differences, colour differences. I mean, we must talk about what that system is like, in a minute, but I don\rquote 
t know when I became conscious of the fact that I lived in a society absolutely riveted by colour, race, class differences. And so in a way, then, my family experience was - well, somehow you\rquote ve got to choose. Why you don\rquote 
t feel at one with them? Well, who are you to feel at one with? Well, ordinary Jamaican people - 95% of the population! Yes, but you don\rquote t know them, you never lived a life like that. You know them, you\rquote 
ve seen them about, you love Jamaica, you identify with the place, you adore the countryside, etc., but you don\rquote t really - you\rquote re not one of them. You aren\rquote t one of them. Between me and them was t
he shield of my family, the screen of my family. So I suppose it\rquote 
s quite a while before I identified this as having to do with class and colour. But I knew we were different, I knew the side was graded, I knew that that was such a riveting topic that the m
iddle-classes could not let it go. My grandmother could pinpoint people\rquote s racial background, you know, to a T. I mean, she would run the combinations of skin colour, education, straightness of the hair, European features, on and on and on, she
\rquote d say, \'93A touch of the tar brush there!\'94 So that\rquote s what they talked about. We used to have rum punch parties on Sunday and some expatriate people would come, some of my father\rquote 
s business people, old family friends from Port Antonio, etc., the grounds would be full of these people drinking my mother\rquote 
s rum punch and chatting. They were chatting about affairs, and about class distinctions. And the class distinctions were always mediated through colour. So the moment I really started to reflect on this thing, I thought, \'93W
ell, that is what this society is about. It\rquote s about these two things\'94. Now, later on I came to think, and you know Jamaica, so you\rquote ll understand what I\rquote 
m saying. I came to think this is one of the most complexly structured societies on earth. Everybody in 
the Island is from somewhere else. The natives were massacred and wiped out by the Spaniards, in a hundred years. Everybody there does not belong there. Africans came from Africa; the Indians came in indenture; the Scots were there; the Spanish had been t
here before; the French were next door in Haiti. It was the first Diaspora, and one of the longest, because, after all, Spain conquered us in [1494] - whatever it is. So it\rquote 
s a funny place. So the society is layered by that, and one section of the middle-class, now, is Indian \endash 
 as you know. Another section is Lebanese and Syrians who came as traders. Another small echelon are the Indians who came as indentured workers. Then the Chinese who imported - so if you see the layers of the society, you see how compl
exly structured it is. Now, unlike racially divided societies formerly, like the Southern States, or like apartheid, there was no formal lines, so everything was part of an informal system. You know, you could cross, nobody would stop you. You know, a bla
ck person, uneducated, if they had the money, could go into Merchant Bank Hotel and he wouldn\rquote t last for two minutes because the atmosphere would be so hostile! But nobody would come and say, \'93You can\rquote t have a drink here\'94 or \'93
You can\rquote t order lunch here\'94. Nothing. So it had to be managed informally, it was a society that had to be constantly read \endash  it had to be made legible. Now, the way in which you understood that was another thing. I\rquote 
ll tell you another element which adds to its complexity, of course it\rquote s a colony, and a colony means that it\rquote s judged according to a norm which is not internal to it. The white English are the norm \endash  that is what civilisation is 
\endash  and the further away you are from it, the less in life you are. So it\rquote s graded, but towards the centre, which is not inside your society, it\rquote s somewhere else. So, what does one make of that? Well, the anthropologists call it \'93
white mass\'94, but I don\rquote t know whether that\rquote s quite category. It makes the society lopsided, so always yearning for something it doesn\rquote t really know about. Yearning to be in England, never been in England. It yearns to be white, can
\rquote t possibly be white. It yearns to be rich or landed, it won\rquote t be that. So everything is a compromise towards that, so that creates an extremely rich ki
nd of social matrix. Another factor had to do with the way in which race and class are linked together. And I would put it this way. Class, obviously, had to do with land, property, wealth, spending power, education \endash 
 all the things that those things buy. The class system: masses of poor people, small number of elites, middle-class elites, the wealthy landowners \endash  some there, some absentees, etc. \endash 
 the big class divisions. But all of it was, of course, also graded by colours \endash  by skin colour. So the mass, w
ho were poor, were largely black, and the intermediate class, who are quite well-off, like my family, were brown. And the rich and the landed, were either English or what we call \'93white Jamaicans\'94
, i.e. it all got mixed up so early on, nobody could tell any longer (LAUGHS), but they could pass as white. So the class system and the skin colour system were interlaced. They weren\rquote 
t the same, but you could correlate them. Now, that meant social judgements, evaluations, were extraordinarily rich in terms of complexity. It\rquote 
s an extraordinarily complex society. And then the other thing to say is that people had internalised the models of this other place that were not present with them. So when Abolition came, the Abolitionists thought that the British who had been
 there had gone native: they\rquote re not really as educated, civilised, restrained, as English people in England, they were pretty Barbarian. And the big thing was, of course, because there weren\rquote 
t many women in the early stages, so there had been substantial sexual miscegenation, and planters and overseers and engineers in the sugar factories, etc., simply, you know, took African wives \endash  women, not wives \endash 
 women, and had children with them. So although everything was graded by an interlocking of class and colour, you couldn\rquote 
t be quite certain what that meant. A lot of black families would turn out to have one white forebear six generations back, you know! The brown middle-class obviously did, but in what proportion? Was it ten generations ago, five generations a
go? How close were they to the ideal? How far away? How mixed? How impure? You know, the whites were - if I can exaggerate, their connection was over there \'93
we are really just here temporarily in the warmth, but really, our families are back there, we go back there, we send our children back there to be educated\'94. So when I think about it in that way, and the absence of an indigenous population \endash 
 which, of course, is not the case in South America, there are still indigenous \endash  there are no Arawaks in Jamaica. Absolutely none. It\rquote s a kind of absent trace of the past. And when I think about that, I think, \'93I don\rquote 
t know a society which would rival it in terms of the infinite elaboration of social, racial, you know, divisions. Intricate, intricate, intricate. So that\rquote 
s why I have no doubt the middle-classes were so fascinated by it! They had to mark their distance. But do you mark it by education? You can\rquote t change your features. You look rather English, rather European, \'93
but we know that you have a black family\'94. So where do you stand in the social ranking? This complex hierarchisation of racial difference. What I discovered was that everybody knows this. Everybody understands it. Because it\rquote 
s a taboo system related to racial impurity, and it\rquote s related to slavery, which at that stage nobody wanted to know about at all \endash  you couldn\rquote 
t talk about it openly. But you had to have a thousand euphemisms and circumloCurtions to refer to this glaring heart of the society. So the talk was hints, innuendos, you know what people
 are talking[about], you had to internalise a kind of matrix, complicated social matrix, which allowed you to read the society. But you couldn\rquote t say, \'93Oh, I hate black people\'94 \endash as a middle-class person. You couldn\rquote 
t do it. Of course not. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
