\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes. I mean, in a way (LAUGHS) - in a way I\rquote 
m telling this in this detail because most of the questions that have preoccupied a lot of my work come from that experience, long before I knew anything about sociology or social sciences or anything like that, and informed it really. I\rquote 
m not saying, it\rquote s not a kind of causal thing, but do you understand what I mean? I encountered the reality of a complexly racially divided society long before I knew the concept of race \endash  long before. Also what I didn\rquote 
t understand - and I must say this - I didn\rquote t understan
d that race, as a concept, was not very actively understood. But colour was the visible sign of race, so if you wanted to operate an informal social system of distinctions, you had to find a language that was non-existent there, [that was] visible. \'93
Well, I don\rquote t know where they come from, and I don\rquote t know who their parents are, who knows? But I can see a touch of the tar brush there!\'94 (LAUGHS) So colour is a signifying system for that which you can\rquote t see \endash 
 race, biological \endash  these things operate genetically, hidden, you can\rquote t smoke them out, but colour you can\rquote t avoid. You can\rquote 
t avoid. You have only to look and you see the whole of Jamaica resumed in the colour, class, bearing, physique, of the people in front of you. Yes, I learned what reading of society was about then (LAUGHS) - my mother\rquote s milk! }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
