\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, yes. My mother\rquote s family, the Grossets, we knew, but I never - I didn\rquote 
t live in Port Antonio, by then my father was working in Kingston, things had moved, really, from places like Port Antonio and Montego Bay, to Kingston, as the central capital and focus of everything, so I didn\rquote t know them very well, and I didn
\rquote t really get on with them. They were rather snooty about us, because my mother had married a Jamaican \endash  more obvious Jamaican than they were. The real influence was, as you can tell from everything I\rquote ve said, my mother. She\rquote 
d go and analyse, and she set the standards. She imported into this Kingston middle-class family the pretentiousness, the aspirations, the manners - she had our servants dressed in uniforms. In addition to the four servants who served us, ther
e was a gardener, then there were a retinue of people who looked after bits of her affairs, who were like feudal serfs \endash  he cuts the hedges; he sharpens the cutlers. He looks after the knives; he repairs the roof. \'93Do you pay him?\'94 \'93
Well, I give him something\'94. You don\rquote t pay him a fee or a wage or anything like that, but you give him something \endash  it\rquote 
s a kind of bounty. So this bounty relationship, this funny fantasy relationship with England, and this really despising of black people, ordinary black people below. When Independence started to come, my mother said, \'93
Our way of life is finished. It is passing\'94. And it was. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
