\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 She said that? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 And it was. She could feel it because, you know, s
he was already anachronistic. That state had already passed. The future was with my father, but she still wanted to impose on that the models of a previous - so she\rquote 
s a massive influence. I mean, I could spend all the time talking about her and my complicated relationship with her. Okay. On the other side, my father\rquote s family stayed living in Old Harbour \endash  a fishing village on the southern \endash 
 there were ten aunts, and he had a brother. He had married, gone to work, good job, etc.. The aunts still lived in thi
s tiny provincial town with my grandmother, after my grandfather died. Now, this was a much poorer household. Gingerbread house, I never understood where the ten aunts slept. I did not, I never decided it. They all lived in there. The oldest aunt \endash 
 my Aunt Geraldine \endash  built a school in the yard, a two room prep school, at 19, and in Redemption Song I interview her \endash  she\rquote s 102. She\rquote s still teaching spelling to some children from Aunt Geri\rquote 
s school, on the background. \'93I\rquote ll spell \lquote government\rquote \'94. \'93No, there\rquote s an \lquote n\rquote  in there somewhere\'94! So she had the school. My Aunt Iris was a wonderful person, very exuberant \endash 
 she was another postmistress. She would jump on, in the roads, of any passing car coming to Kingston, to stay with us. At the centre of this was my gran
dmother. She was just a wonderful person. Chuckling, being maternal, this extended family, still in charge of the household, but not a pretentious household. And the sharpest contrast is Christmas. I would have Christmas at home \endash 
 deathly. Absolutely deathly! Very good food, of course, as you can imagine \endash  ham and turkey, and two kinds of hot Christmas puddings! (LAUGHS) Temperature outside 95\'b0! (LAUGHS) But formal, not until 3 o\rquote 
clock in the afternoon. And what do you do after that? My parents go and have a rest. \'93You can go to the cinema\'94
. The next day, Boxing Day, we went to Old Harbour. Completely different. The place teeming with people. You know, everybody laughing and telling jokes and gossiping. My grandmother would have lunch, which was prepared in 
her kitchen out at the back, and always invited was the Anglican priest and the Catholic priest, because my father\rquote 
s family was divided between the two. Christmas morning, the Catholics went with Aunt Geri to one place, and the Anglicans with my grandmother to another. And my grandmother said, \'93
There are only three things I will not have discussed at the Christmas table. One is religion. Two is politics. And three is the abdication of Edward VIII\'94. So I just adored her. I wear her wedding [ring]. So my mind
 is furnished by the contrast in these two places \endash  a poor, transparent - not transparent, of course it\rquote s greatly complex, but living the life that they really lived, there\rquote 
s a certain authenticity about how they lived, and full of sociability, and this au
stere thing that we had created in Kingston. My mother designed the house, it was in three-quarters of an acre of land. Eventually she built a tennis court in the front, and [held] tennis parties. She would try to induce the grass to grow (LAUGHS) so they
 could play tennis! They had tea parties. I mean, just poles apart, these two things, and unfortunately I just felt that emotionally I became divided between the two. I didn\rquote t want to be at home, eating Christmas dinner that way, I just didn
\rquote t want to. I didn\rquote 
t like it. It was too false. There was something completely inauthentic about it. I loved going to Old Harbour, although when my mother arrived, when we arrived, driving down from Kingston, she was like visiting her country cousins. She expected they
\rquote re going \'93Miss Jessie\'94
, and to look after her, and kowtow to her, etc., which I hated. I hated that aspect of our lives more than anything. My father belonged to Kingston Cricket Club, where he [watched] test matches), he would take me occasionally. I knew t
hat the people around were not making jokes of it, but poking fun at him in some way. He never understood it. I hated it. I resented it. He said, \'93Shall I make you a member?\'94 I said, \'93No, I don\rquote 
t want to be a member of that Club at all. I don\rquote t want anything to do with it\'94. So there are these contrasting worlds of mine, none of them, you\rquote 
ll notice, are real, authentic - you know, country black Jamaican family. I know all about them, every bit of them \endash  their complicated relationship to the land, their exten
ded families, I know what their life is like, etc. - but I was not one of them, and I couldn\rquote t get there. I just couldn\rquote t get there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
