\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Well, what can I say? I was, of course, the bad one, the naughty one. I was always naughty, always rude, always in trouble, you know! Edward
 Said, when he writes about his boyhood and says he too was just identified, in the family, as the one who was out, the one who didn\rquote 
t fit, the naughty one. So, of course, we had rows with my father. My father was not a very tough disciplinarian, my mother
 fathered me from that point of view. But I came to understand that she felt closer to me than to some of the others because I was a kind of rebel. Really, because I resisted her, she took to me, though she wouldn\rquote 
t take me to her, but she had a feeling for me which she didn\rquote 
t have for the others. The others were good children - they tried to behave, they subscribed to the norms of the family, the identifications with that way of life, they shared many of the pretentious preoccupations of the family, the ri
sing aspirations, etc. But she knew I was somehow not in it. She didn\rquote t approve of what I was, and what I wanted to identify with, but she thought, \'93Mmm - \'94 I\rquote 
m a kind of strong spirit, yes, strong spirit, and the others are a bit flabby, like their father!\'94 (LAUGHS) So what else? What else can I tell you? I never felt loved by her, but, I mean, I don\rquote t know whether that\rquote 
s significant at all, because I\rquote ve discovered that sons never feel loved enough by their fathers! (LAUGHS) So maybe that\rquote s gone. But one t
hing I notice now is that my friends talk about their parents in this completely different way. You know, ordinary Jamaicans they had a happy - do you understand what I mean \endash  this complicated family relationship, families always complicated 
\endash  but they had
 a kind of modus vivendi with their families, even when they were breaking from them, and I never had that openly with my own parents. I came to disapprove deeply of them, and of the life they wanted me to lead. I came to not be able to recognise myself i
n their image of me, but I never had open rows about that with them. I had open rows about everything else. For instance, my mother, when I went to school - school is interesting because I went to Jamaica College - one of the five or six big boys\rquote 
 schools, and three girls\rquote  schools that the educated middle-classes go to - by that stage, black boys on scholarship had come to the school, so the school was, in a way, more socially diverse than my family\rquote 
s friends and surroundings. My mother would not allow me to bring a black boy home. Not one of us. \'93You\rquote ll learn bad habits from them\'94. \'93We don\rquote t know who his parents are\'94
. No. So my life was divided between people that they liked \endash  including girls that they thought was appropriate for me, about whom I had no feel
ing whatsoever (LAUGHS) - and my underground life with my friends at school, a much wider posse of intimates. So she patrolled those boundaries, and I felt that as a weight on me. I haven\rquote 
t mentioned one thing which I should say something about very briefly. My sister went to work. Well, before that, because my brother was blind, and my sister was a girl, that they had brought up the children in a very kind of hothouse way, so I can
\rquote t remember my brother ever bringing a girl home, and I can\rquote t remember my sister bringing a boyfriend home. Like other people they had groups of friends, etc., but the house was a sort of haven of - I don\rquote 
t know what you call it - purity, fresh, I don\rquote t know what it was. So when I came along, they didn\rquote t know what to do with me! I
 wanted to be out, I wanted to be with my friends, I wanted to be cycling, I wanted to go to parties, I started to be interested in girls, and what is that? How do you cope with that? Well, my sister went to work and fell in love with a black student. The
 University of the West Indies had just started, and a black Barbadian student, medical student was there \endash  very educated, etc., etc., but black. My mother said, \'93No! It will not happen. Not from this house. Absolutely not\'94
. She forbade it. They broke it of
f. My sister had the most tremendous mental breakdown within two months. She was given shock therapy, bouts of it, by ordinary GPs, because there were no psychiatrists, blitzed her mind, cleared her mind of these funny ideas she\rquote 
d somehow gotten hold of! And I suddenly saw that the whole microcosm of Jamaican society and its problems and intricacies, were being mirrored inside the family culture, you know? She wasshe was the victim of Colonialism! You know, I don\rquote 
t know any other way of putting it. She was sacrificed to the social system. But, of course, with the emotional torment - of course these words are not the same, but they\rquote 
re not separate things. I really have never been able to make a clear distinction between the emotional and the psyche on the one
 hand, and the social and the cultural on the other, I see them inter-penetrating all the time with one another. I just looked at her, and I thought, \'93Now, this is a certain kind of emotional death, and if you ever get a chance to leave here, don
\rquote t come back to it. Do not come back to it, because you\rquote ll either adapt to it and become another Jamaican middle-class boy, and make a success of your life, but you\rquote ll give in to a system that you don\rquote 
t like, that you hate, or it will get to you emotionally\'94. And that\rquote s when I decided, if I get the chance to study, I don\rquote 
t want to go to the University of the West Indies and live at home, I want to go elsewhere. I want to go somewhere else to study, and just see whether that can free me of these dilemmas of identifica
tion which I have been unable to resolve within that context. So she is really governing force in my life. Governing force in my life. She came to England. Twice she brought my sister to England when I was here as a student. Of course, they thought gettin
g a Rhodes Scholarship to go to Oxford was the pinnacle of the family\rquote s aspirations! This was like magic. They never thought I would. My brother, George, ought to have, but because blind, or very bad sight, so he couldn\rquote 
t get - but Stuart, with a Rhodes Scholarship, going to England! My family home was called \'93Merton\'94, I went to Merton College! \'93Where did you get the name?\'94 \'93Oh, I saw it in some book\'94
, or something! So it was like my destiny. My mother brought me, with a huge steamer trunk, full of coats and
 warm things, and delivered me to Merton College, Oxford. Well [later], she came with my sister, and during the early period of the anti-nuclear Movement, and I was speaking in Trafalgar Square, and she came, the last day of Aldermaston, it was a really m
a
ssive thing. The people who had marched all the way, and it took about five hours to get them into the Square, and I was one of these young radicals, who had become involved in the anti-nuclear campaign], and I spoke. So afterwards, I went to my mother an
d said, \'93Well, what do you think of that?\'94 \'93Well\'94, she said, \'93I never thought I\rquote d see anything like this in my life, but don\rquote t come back home, it\rquote s not the place for those ideas. Don\rquote t bring them back\'94
. So, you know, she had a shaft of insight somewhere, and she really did not hesitate to say, \'93You wouldn\rquote t fit in. You wouldn\rquote t fit in with us, and we wouldn\rquote t fit in with you. I would stay. I\rquote 
m sorry to see you go, but stay\'94. So, you know, it\rquote s hard to call her an influence in my life! (LAUGHS) You know, she just shaped it from the inside \endash 
 as much by my resistances to her, as by her influence over me. I never knew when the positive became negative! But whenever it was, she made it, she shaped it, she governed it, she induced it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
