\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Oh, that\rquote s fascinating
. You mentioned Jamaica College, but I think it would be helpful to hear about your schooling altogether, and people who were influential. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 

\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Okay. I was always quite clever. I went to a small, I think private prep school, as it were, run by an interesting woman \endash 
 the sister of a woman called Una Marson, who later came to England, worked for the BBC. There\rquote s a famous photograph of Una Marson producing a World Service programme with Orwell, T.S. Eliot and so on. She became a Garveyite. Her sister ran 
the school, very religious, so that\rquote s when I read the Bible one end to the other, all day, under some mango trees, in an open classroom, etc.. Then I got a Scholarship to go to Jamaica College. Well, Jamaica College is one of these big elite boys
\rquote  school, secondary boys\rquote  school. Ours was part boarding/part non-boarding \endash  part-day boy \endash  I was a day boy. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 This is at age 10, or what was it? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes, I guess 10 or 11. Yes, 11, it must have been 11. Modelled on the English public school, and Jamaica
 College has a highly coloured walled chapel, (LAUGHS) the grass track grew out of this baking hard soil, induced to cover the wall. We had a tuck shop, imitating Tom Brown\rquote 
s Schooldays. But I think you will find these schools throughout the Caribbean, and all the leaders \endash  political leaders, business leaders, etc. \endash  have been to one or other of them \endash  all of them. C. R. James went to QRC \endash  Queen
\rquote s Royal College \endash  he taught Eric Williams there. He became a master, then came to England. Everybody. Norman Man
ley had been to Jamaica College, got his Rhodes Scholarship, becomes a very distinguished lawyer, Queens Counsel, and then leader, one of the nationalist leaders. His son, Michael, was at school with me. The month I went to Jamaica College first, Michael 
had had a row with an English master about English history, and been suspended, and Norman Manley came driving up in a big car to collect him. So, people talk about these schools now, like the English talk about Oxford and Cambridge Colleges. \'93
 J.C. Boy?\'94 \'93No, Kingston College.\'94, Kingston places you in a certain fraction of the middle-class. But as I said before, though the education that they transmitted was very solidly English-based, and we did \lquote O\rquote  Levels and \lquote A
\rquote  Levels \endash  well, \'93Ordinary Certificate\'94 and \'93Higher Certificate\'94
 I think they were called, marked in England. I did Latin, history was principally the history of England. Empire, was not, as far as I know, ever mentioned. I never was taught anything about slavery in my entire life formally in school
. I knew Keats backwards. I knew the names of daffodils, but I wasn\rquote 
t sure whether the flowers in Jamaica were called poinsettias - you know, it created an imaginary landscape into which we were induced. We were the subalterns. They were going to leave eventually, and the place had to be left in safe hand \endash 
 those who knew and understood European and English virtues from the inside, we\rquote d been educated in them, yes? Not just formally adapted to them. So that was their purpose. They were somewhat more mixed by
 then, as I say, than the rest of the society, and so you could find an echelon of boys from the country, you\rquote d find very clever black boys, and you\rquote 
d find a lot of expatriates. I mean, in my class there were some black guys, people brown-skinned like me, there were Jews, Ashrams - there was an Indian, there was a Syrian \endash  a close friend of mine, Mafud \endash 
 and there were children of expatriates. It became a more accurate microcosm of the social world than you would have imagined. But the education was rigorou
sly oriented towards an English syllabus. Well, there was a break in that because, at one stage. We usually had English headmasters, and we had a lot of expatriate masters, so I was taught by the Scots, by the Irish, by the Welsh, and the English, as well
 as by Jamaican teachers. I was accustomed to that. I\rquote 
d never been taught by anybody else from anywhere else in the West Indies. I hardly knew the rest of the West Indies existed. At one point a Barbadian called Harold Jackman, came to the school to teach u
s Latin. We thought he was a riot! Absolute riot! He spoke in this funny way. Where was he from? Barbados so small, what are they doing down there? We had a story that when you played cricket in Barbados, you had to hit the ball into the sea to get a four
 because it\rquote 
s so small! You know, incredibly provincial. Incredibly provincial we were too. But Scots and Irish, Yes, I was taught history by a man who would come to play in the Corinthians visiting football side, married a white Jamaican and stayed. He was
 our football coach and my history master. But I do remember when a Jamaican finally became Headmaster, Mr. Chambers, he introduced a choice you could make, a little bit of the background of Jamaican history. And the Daily Gleaner is the main paper there,
 
produced a sort of summary geography and history of Jamaica, and so for the first time we began to learn about - well, mainly the governors and what they had done. My house in my school was named after a governor called Musgrove, etc., etc., so we learned
 about that. We learned about the pirates, we learnt about Henry Morgan, we learnt about Port Royal, romance of the Caribbean really. Not history, but that\rquote 
s my first sense that there was another kind of curriculum, an alternative curriculum there, which then did become the basis of a much more thoroughly Jamaicanised, indigenized curriculum. So I took \lquote O\rquote 
 Levels, okay. I was always near the top of my class. I had another friend called Herbert Hall, and a friend called Charlie Levi, and we were always 1, 2, and 3, or 3, 2, 1, etc., every term\rquote 
s exams. So I was identified as a clever, rather precocious boy. I played games, I played cricket, I played football, I played tennis. I didn\rquote t play any of them terribly well, but I was good at tennis, probably because I\rquote 
d learnt at my mother\rquote s! (LAUGHS) I learnt on my mother\rquote s tennis court, although she never invited me to play with her friends. Never. They would come, I would be a ball boy. I played, I was captain of my school team, they never said, \'93
Do you want to play with us?\'94 Still, tennis. I enjoyed being - I constructed school and the friends I made there as an alternative life. They didn\rquote 
t want to meet them at home, fine. My bicycle was the agent of my liberty. I could go with them, you know, and we started to exp
lore another part of [Kingston] (LAUGHS). One of my friends already had a 20-year old mistress (LAUGHS) in some part of Lower Kingston. We would go to - I mean, Mother would have died if she\rquote d known what I got up to! But I didn\rquote 
t tell them. I didn\rquote t talk to them. I kept myself to myself. I didn\rquote 
t let on. So I lived these two worlds. But school, in that sense, although it was a powerful acculturation to European and English values, was also, paradoxically, an arena of freedom and exploration for me, because 
I did get close to all sorts of people that I would never have learned through the narrow funnel of my own family. Never conceivably. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Intellectually, were any of the teachers important? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well the man I told you about, who taught me history
, was important, because I was poised between doing English and history - I mean literature and history. I really wanted to be a historian, but I was good at both. I remember one or two of the people who taught me literature, but not terribly well. But he
 was very influential. It\rquote s true. What I was learning about was, you know, the Seven Years War of Jenkins\rquote  Ear (LAUGHS), and things like that, but nevertheless he did teach me. And at one point he said, \'93You know, you don\rquote 
t know any contemporary history, no? Well, there\rquote s a thing called Keesing\rquote s Archives, which is a sort of loose-leaf, they send you things every month, and it tells you what\rquote s going on in the rest of the world, and I\rquote 
m going to get it. And you can do a paper, a sort of alternative paper in history, in this thing, if you wanted to\'94. And I said, \'93Yes, I want to do it\'94
. So this was a big eye-opener, because one of the things you had to do in this course was to read British Council pamphlets. Of course, you learnt about English public schools lik
e this, English monarchies, etc., but also the fear of anti-Colonialism and Communism, at work in the world. Communism, what is that? Lenin, who is he? So I started to go to the library and get outLenin. I can\rquote 
t remember what: Imperialism the Highest Stage of Capitalism, you know, some book I couldn\rquote 
t understand. But suddenly, in a backwards route, I came in touch with exactly the ideas I was being inoculated against. Yes. It explained to me why the Empire\rquote s as it is, all of that, in a way to win me over to the other side. But it couldn
\rquote t stop opening the mind. So it was very influential to me, though he wasn\rquote t a great teacher, and I was exactly the opposite of what he was trying to produce. Nevertheless, he was very influential. But other than that, I was a
 bright boy, so I was, you know, well-liked, and I became Head Boy, and etc.. I took \lquote A\rquote  Levels twice, because the first time I was too young to get a Scholarship, so I stayed on to take \lquote A\rquote 
 Levels a second time, because you couldn\rquote t get a Jamaica Scholars
hip until you had been ranked through everything. You had to be one of the five best boys in the country to get a Jamaica Scholarship. So I took it. I got a Jamaica Scholarship. Then I stayed on for a year, during that year I went to teach at a small coun
try school \endash  a school in the country \endash  which was also a revelation. I\rquote d never lived in the country before. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Can you say a little bit more about that, then? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 It was run by a Presbyterian educationist, called Louis Davidson. It was a kind of p
rogressive school. The idea was to create an education for ordinary Jamaicans, but especially for people not from the city. So it was in Spaldings, or Christiana, outside of Mandeville. Red Earth. Lots of wonderful children, but not destined for academic 
careers like I was \endash 
 I had the mark on my forehead, as it were! But this was very wonderful experience, because he was inspiring - rather religious motivation, it was a very interesting pioneering kind of new educational ideas, more application of ideas and
 so on. And so that was very influential. But what was influential was living in Spaldings with the parents of these boys. Bright boys. As bright as buttons, and full of fun and humour, but who weren\rquote 
t part of the middle-class elite. I got a taste of that, and that\rquote s when I formed the decision \'93I want to teach. You are a teacher. That\rquote s what you want to do. You want to teach\'94
. So that was influential for me, but he was my headmaster and I was working for him by then. He wasn\rquote t my teacher. I think what you\rquote re asking is, people usually talk about their teachers at this point, and I wouldn\rquote 
t talk about my teachers. I\rquote ll tell you about two other things that really re-educated me. One was Institute Library \endash  the big Institute in Jamaica, it\rquote s the Institute of Jamaica Library \endash 
 and I think he was an expatriate, or he might have been a white Jamaican, started a Children\rquote s Section, and on Saturdays I would go down to the library. Well, I had never seen books like that, full of things about Italian painting, and poetry. 
\'93What\rquote s this? What is this world?\'94
 I read voraciously, without guidance. This importance is that he created the opportunity for me to do that, and because it was exactly not the school curriculum, I went from here to there, you know! I remember reading T.S. Eliot, \'93
What is this about? You don\rquote t write poetry like that! You write poetry like Keats. You write To a Grecian Urn, you don\rquote t write about crowds flowing across London Bridge, and depressed people in pubs!\'94 (LAUGHS) \'93What is this? You don
\rquote t write about poetry in the vernacular, in the language people speak. Who is he?\'94 \'93Well, he\rquote s an American living in England\'94, and he has these footnotes about Freud, \'93Who is Freud?\'94 Well he also refers to Frasier\rquote 
s Golden Bough, \'93Well, what\rquote s that?\'94 \'93It\rquote s an anthropological text about myth\'94. \'93What\rquote s myth doing? That doesn\rquote t have anything to do with poetry\'94. It just reversed my intellectual world, and I thought, \'93
I want to know more about all of this. This is the life. This is an intellectual world \endash  exciting. It doesn\rquote t compare with provincial Kingston. There are lots of things I love about provincial Kingston, but it\rquote 
s not ideas. If you want ideas, you must find out about these other things\'94. Okay? So that\rquote s one big influence. It\rquote s like a teacher, but it was not in t
he context of formal education. The second was, a school friend of mine, slightly younger than me, became an aficionado of modern jazz, and I first heard Charlie Parker, Miles Davies, and I thought, \'93This is incredible music. Absolutely incredible!\'94
 Of cou
rse, I love Jamaican music, what I dance to, I was a very good dancer. We had parties, etc., so I love Jamaican music, I love Jamaican folk song, etc., but this was something else, and it was a very interesting other thing, because highly sophisticated, f
ormally developed, and a black voice still. You can just hear the blues in Miles Davies \endash  unmistakeable. I thought, \'93
My God, this is another kind of black music altogether. What has this come out of? Who is the Harlem Renaissance? Who are these poets?\'94, you know, \'93Who is Langston Hughes?\'94 \'93
Where have they managed to write about another black experience like this?\'94 So these two things formed me in ways which were not available to me in the formal curriculum I was exposed to. They were extra school things whic
h I think of as my attempt to construct an alternative curriculum. There\rquote 
s a third influence, and that is that, of course, all this while Independence was growing, I increasingly identified with it. We should get rid of Colonialism, Jamaica should govern themselves \endash  self-government. My family wouldn\rquote 
t hear of it, but I didn\rquote t talk about it there. That was my identification. I became an anti-Colonial boy, and a lot of people I knew in my school, were the same. Well, it was along with the rise of Independenc
e came a much-revived local artistic and cultural scene. Edna Manley, who was Manley\rquote 
s wife, you know, was a sculptress, ran a sort of social circle of new musicians and poets and painters, all of them wanting to paint indigenous Jamaican things. I didn\rquote t 
think you could make poetry out of indigenous Jamaican things. They were beautiful, I love them, they were me, but you didn\rquote t make poetry out of it! You wrote about daffodils! So, you know, this was another - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
