\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 I didn\rquote 
t, but I knew of them, and I knew the people. I knew Albert Huie, who was a portrait painter, you know, etc., etc.. I knew so and so was interested in theatre, and there was a little theatre started, which suddenly wanted to see plays by Sean O\rquote 
Casey and etc.. I knew people who were going to England to study music. I just opened up. It opened an indigenous cultural world to me, and it was associated with
 Independence. They were all pro-Independent Nationalists, but they were interested in modernism. They were interested in new ideas, Jamaica was to be modernised, it was to come out of the old Colonial backwoods, it was to be in touch with modern ideas, m
o
dern artistic movements, modern music, etc., and so that enabled me to identify with the rising cultural movement. Yes? Yes, if I had to stay in Jamaica, that is what I want to devote time to, but I also want to know about some of the places where things 
like that are a matter of everyday life. So I would cite those three \'93educational\'94 - in quotation marks \endash  Yes, impact as more formative, than Mr. X or Miss Y, etc.. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
