\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 You know, no part of Jamaica is hidden from anybody else. You just know a lot about parts that you\rquote 
ve never lived in. You know all about the countryside, you know all about downtown Kingston. Remember that, at this stage, the centre of Kingston was down by the harbour \endash  not where it is, up towards the mountains \endash 
 and we lived just below the half-way point, a place called \'93Half Way Tree\'94, so we went down into Kingston all the time. We shopped in Kingston. My father\rquote s f
irm was there. Myrtle Bank Hotel which was fashionable was there. The shopping area was there. The Legislative Council was there. The main Post Office. The shopping streets. We\rquote 
d go, by bus, with my mother and I, down into Kingston to shop. Well, to one side of that was the railway, and the railway at the time, round the railway was a sort of \'85 it was called the \'93The Dungle\'94
, a kind of dumping ground, and a lot of Rastafarians were already there, living there - well, who were they? Well, I didn\rquote t know anyth
ing about Rastafarianism, but they used to come as beggars and knock on the door. My mother would call me inside. \'93Careful! Careful!\'94 \'93No, nothing today, thanks\'94, you know, etc., and send him away. But I knew, you know, I\rquote 
d seen where they live. Downtown Kingston was masses of people in tenement yards. I mean, our four servants used to leave after serving dinner, quite late \endash  fashionable hour, eight o\rquote 
clock - washing up, they would leave about half past ten. They\rquote d walk all the way down to Trench Town or Jubilee Gardens, or wherever it\rquote 
s like that. They presumably had families, you never knew anything much about them. They would sleep. They would come back to serve my father\rquote s breakfast. Well, they were living in tenement yards, they were living in corrugate
d shacks, and I knew that, of course. I didn\rquote t like it, I didn\rquote t think - nobody in my family seemed to notice, really, where they went. I knew that one of them \endash  the gardener \endash 
 was a leading figure in one of the ecstatic sect churches. He took large numbers of people up the Hope River, and submerged them. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Baptism. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Baptised them, or in the sea. Well, nobody knew about that world. But I did. I certainly knew about it. And the other one, the cook 
\endash  who brought me up \endash  I mean, I spent more time in Ethel\rquote s kitchen at the back of our house, than I spent with my mother. I learnt how to cook from her. I just watched her. The back yard was full of them \endash 
 the washer, the gardener, the cook, the housemaid \endash  chatting among themselves, talking about their lives, their families, you overheard that all the time, so although I wasn\rquote t one of them, and I couldn\rquote t say, \'93Oh, I\rquote 
m just a Jamaican like everybody else\'94, it wasn\rquote t because I didn\rquote t know about it. I knew masses about it, and I
 had encountered it in all sorts of different ways. I told you about my grandmother and Christmas. Well, right next door to my grandmother\rquote 
s house was a Church of God, some ecstatic breakaway sect church. We would come home from church, my mother and fathe
r would arrive, my mother would make special rum punch, the two priests would come, drinking themselves sozzled (LAUGHS) waiting for this magnificent meal, and my grandmother\rquote 
s cooking, and then the service would begin next door. Hymns,. Moodie and Sankey, good old Baptist hymns, sung by this very black congregation, and it became more African as you listened to it \endash 
 slow, more rhythmic, more tied to the - more earthed. I remember also the guy who was a friend of mine, who was a Rhodes Scholar who was the founder of a Jamaican Dance Company, and he said to me once \endash  I went to watch him rehearse new dances 
\endash  and he said to me, \'93You know, the tradition of European dancing is that you can almost fly. You want to escape from the earth, you jump and leap and so o
n. The tradition in African music is that you go down, grounded, grounding, deeper and deeper into a sort of earth. One is ethereal, one is Caliban\'94
, and it was so. So I knew, and I heard that music all the time. At home, you could hear an area just near t
o Papine where my parents eventually moved to, you know, just by the University, which is, you know, a slum. The poorest of Kingston poor live there. They\rquote 
re within spitting distance of the University, and they frequently these days spit! They raid them, they steal from them, because they\rquote re the enemy right in the middle of them. So you can\rquote t live in Jamaica and say, \'93
Well, I was brought up in upper middle-class Kingston\'94. I was, but you wouldn\rquote t know everything that was going like that. I spoke patois. My mother wouldn\rquote t allow me to speak patois at home. I couldn\rquote t speak patois in school. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
