\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes. And the only ways of understanding Ethel and Cecil and Dorothy were to understand
 patois, of course! I mean, in their way, they were quite well-educated, but that\rquote s what they spoke. All of us spoke - I don\rquote 
t suppose patois is regarded as a language, so I spoke one and a half languages! One was there for respectable middle-class society, and one for being a Jamaican. But everybody understood it. My mother understood it, although she wouldn\rquote 
t speak it for a moment. Impeccable accent, but she wouldn\rquote t speak it. But, of course, she could sing, \'93Carry me ackee, Go a-Linstead market.\'94 She knew the folk songs, you know, she danced to mento music. So it\rquote 
s what I said before, there are these stratifications, but they overlap, they interweave, there\rquote s no formal distinction between them, they flow into one another. The requirement to be aware of the distinction is because they\rquote 
re so fluid. Precisely because they\rquote re so fluid, you have to be all the time drawing little lines, and they\rquote re there and we heard it, otherwise the whole thing would have been indigenized from beginning to end. So I\rquote m only saying, it
\rquote s not just school. By then I knew a lot about Jamaican life. I knew that there was a black consciousness movement, I knew there was Garveyites who were, you know, followers of Garvey. I knew there was an attempt, a strong attempt, to recover the s
tory of slavery, which had never been told. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
