\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 And nobody, of course, ever called themselves \'93black\'94
. Nobody. My family would have a thousand euphemisms for it. And people call themselves \'93coloured\'94, but they never called themselves \'93black\'94. I never thought of myself as \'93black\'94 until Civil Rights, and became \'93black\'94
 in England. As I would say, I became West Indian in England. I\rquote d never met another West Indian, apart from Harold Jackman. I\rquote d never been to anywhere there. I came to London, off the boat train, millions of other West Indians \endash 
 Barbados, Antigua, Grenada, etc .. Well, George Lamming says, in Pleasures of Exile, \'93My generation became West Indian in London\'94, and we did. And the West Indian novels create in London. This was also Selvon
, Lamming, Harris, on and on and on, they were all in London, around the World Service, broadcasting poetry. I worked for them. So all of that happened in the diaspora. So that is one of the reasons why I say I am a diasporic subject. I came to myself thr
ough the diaspora. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
