\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, it\rquote 
s a strange experience, you can imagine. I arrived on what was, in fact, a banana boat and passenger ship, and my mother was with me \endash  my mother brought me, with a huge steamer trunk, to deliver to Merton College, Oxford. But I suppose summing up
 that experience, the first impression is two-fold. One is, it was all, in some way, uncannily familiar. I knew everything about it, in a certain kind of way. I had an image of what the English countryside should look like, as we went up to Paddington fro
m
 Bristol and so on. On the other hand, of course, completely strange. Completely different from what I had imagined, and not prepared for the dark sombre colours, for the drizzly wet of August. So, in between just what you had expected, and a sense of ver
y great strangeness from what my eyes had become accustomed to. So familiar and strange really. So I was then in London for a couple of months, because Oxford didn\rquote 
t start until October, so we were tourists really. We went to the Festival of Britain \endash  1951,
 we went to the Houses of Parliament, we did the usual rounds. My mother had been to England before. Went to The Mousetrap! (LAUGHS) We did all the tourist things. But the one thing which now stands out for me, looking back, is we were staying in Methodis
t International House around about Bayswater, and I walked past Paddington Station one day, and I saw this stream of ordinary Jamaican people coming out of the station, and I thought, \'93Who are these? Where are they going?\'94 You know, \'93
These are not middle-class travellers, these are ordinary working people from Jamaica. What are they doing here?\'94 Well, of course, it was only two years after the arrival of The Windrush, which is 1948 - two or three years \endash 
 and the migration was just beginning to build up really. Well, that was a very strange experience to me, because I regarded coming to England as a kind of escape attempt, I couldn\rquote t come to terms - I wasn\rquote 
t the person my parents wanted me to be. But somehow that formation prevented me also from identifying as an ordinary Jamaican boy. So I felt blocked in both directions, although my feelings were in one clear direction, but I just couldn\rquote 
t be that, so I thought, \'93You should go and see the wider world for a bit\'94. But there they were. There was my problem! (LAU
GHS) On the station forecourt, all there, all in England. What were they doing here? Where were they from? A lot of them were from the countryside and never been in Kingston, though it\rquote s been a bit exaggerated how unskilled they were, it\rquote 
s turned out. But, nevertheless, they\rquote d scraped together and found the wherewithal to travel, and here they were, in their brimmed felt hats and their brightly coloured jackets, and their baskets an incredible sight! And I thought, \'93
Well, what will happen to them? They\rquote re not going back right away, they\rquote ve come to work. Can they find work that isn\rquote t available in Jamaica?\'94 \'93They\rquote ll have to live here. They\rquote 
ll have to live somewhere. Where? What relationship will they have with the people that they\rquote re living amongst?\'94 \'93What kind of jobs will they find?\'94 But more especially, \'93What sort of Jamaicans will they be in ten years? They\rquote 
ll be habituated to something else\'94. They are really, themselves, of composite cultural background, and here is another layer, to be lived in Hounslow o
r Notting Hill or wherever it is, Brixton. What I realised is that they would never be the same as they\rquote d come, as this experience would transform them. I couldn\rquote 
t see in exactly what ways, but they could never quite go back. In that sense, they, and I, couldn\rquote t really go home again. And so I felt \endash  perhaps I\rquote ve said this before? No. And so I felt, \'93Well, although I\rquote 
m not the same class as the majority of them, and I\rquote m not from the same background, I have this weird middle-class, coloured middle-class formation, but all of us are going to change by staying\'94
. So for the first time, their fates and mine were sort of the same! That\rquote s where I learnt to see life as a diasporic subject \endash  as somebody who\rquote s living the in-between life there and here, between cultures
, between temporalities, between forms of authority and power, and finally decide, \'93Could you make a home here when you really thought of that as home? But if you went home, you could never make a home there\'94. You\rquote 
d always be thinking about there. Well, that is what diasporic subjects are like. They\rquote re going to be them, and so am I. So it\rquote s a critical experience for me, because suddenly I saw myself from some other person\rquote s place. Yes? It
\rquote s like seeing yourself as an object rather than a subject, what they call in literary analysis \'93from the place of the other\'94
. I saw my subjectivity, but from the place of the other, rather than from within, what I felt like and all the ideas I had. So it was a very important experience. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
