\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Yes. I went to Oxford to read literature. That was an odd experience too! First of all, the English middle and upper-middle classes, completely strange to me, I\rquote d not met English people like that befo
re! (LAUGHS) But also [there were] a lot of people straight back from the War, so rather more mature servicemen, serious about their business rather than fritting away their lives. And as well as that, the Scholarship boys that Hoggart wrote about, becaus
e, you know, post-\rquote 45 education, etc., etc.. So it was a mixed experience for me. I was reading literature. There were no black students in my College, there were a few Indian students. There were black students elsewhere in Oxford, I wasn\rquote 
t the only one, but there were very very few of us. And I first tried to make myself into a literary scholar. I thought that\rquote s what you do, that\rquote s what you\rquote 
ve come to study, you might teach it here, you might go home to teach it, but that\rquote s what you ought to know about. So
 I got involved in debates about literary theory, and about literary criticism, and F.R. Leavis and all that. Yes, so I had a sort of quasi-literary theory experience. And the people most important to me in doing that were a group of Americans who were in
 the College, all of them reading English, many of them Rhodes Scholars, so it was their second degrees - they were slightly older than me - but they knew a lot about the literature which I didn\rquote 
t know anything about. They really taught me about American literature. And we were committed. We used to wait for copies of Scrutiny to come from Cambridge, cut the uncut pages to read the latest controversy that F.R. Leavis had - So that\rquote 
s one group. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 And what about any staff, were any staff an influence? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
