\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Oh, the staff were an influence, but not in my College. I had a tutor who was, in his own way, a magnificent anachronism, an 18th century gentleman really, studying the 18th century \endash  Hugo V. Dyson-Dyson. A learned man, but urbane. He always arrang
ed for me and the person I had tutorials with, to come late in the afternoon, because he would offer us sherry, and we\rquote 
d go downstairs and see a very ancient literary scholar called Garrard, who had rooms below his, so we visited Mr. Garrard. And the Ameri
cans were rather much more confident than most of the English students, they were 19 or 20, so we used to take Hugo out to the pub. It was my only taste of urbane life! But I can\rquote 
t say I was influenced by him. The people I was influenced by were people that he arranged for me to go and have tutorials with. So he said, \'93I think you ought to go and have a term with Helen Gardner\'94
, this great T.S. Eliot scholar, so we trooped round to her College \endash  all the Americans, all of us \endash  a big class with Helen Gardner. Well, that was a tremendous experience. Very very impressive person who\rquote 
d written about T.S. Eliot. But, of course, the idea of teaching of it was - (LAUGHS) so we would ask her about \'93Mr. Eliot\'94, she\rquote d call him. She taught us metaphysical poetry, and tha
t was a hoot, I have to tell you, because the Americans kept saying, \'93I don\rquote t understand this line\'94. She said, \'93Well, it\rquote s from Ovid. Do you read Ovid?\'94 So she climbed up a ladder and brought it down. \'93I don\rquote t read Ovid
\'94. \'93Oh, well, I think you\rquote ll find, Mr. Burwell, that it\rquote s a sexual pun\'94. A sexual pun! (LAUGHS) Once she wrote a letter \endash  after we left her, before we got to College - the letter from Helen saying, \'93
I think you will find that metaphysical poetry, Elizabethan poetry as a whole is full of sexual puns. So when you see \'93quaint\'94, it means \'93cunt\'94. Now I\rquote d be pleased if you wouldn\rquote t raise this again in class\'94
. (LAUGHS) They sent me to a woman called Edna Bednarovska who was very nice \endash  taught me Chaucer. So I was sent out to some very good specialist
s. But all of my essays were written for Hugo, and we would read [them to him]. I had a tutorial with a working-class, very brilliant working-class Newcastle boy, and he and I read these wonderful productions \endash  as we thought \endash 
 and Hugo would comment on it and bring out the sherry! (LAUGHS) So I can\rquote t say that Oxford influenced me in that way. There were, of course, clever people around that you could go and listen to \endash 
 Lord David Cecil. I went to a seminar with G.D.H. Cole. Lots of interesting talks and clubs and things, so I got a rich diet, but [I was] not influenced as some people are by a particular tutor who sort of shape their lives. It didn\rquote 
t. Dyson once said to me, \'93Oh well, Stuart\'94 \endash  in my third year \endash  \'93When you go back, you\rquote ll be Governor, won\rquote t you, or something like that\'94, and I thought, \'93What are you talking about? You don\rquote 
t have a clue who I am. You don\rquote t know where I come from, where I\rquote m going back to. I\rquote ve been sitting in this bloody room with you, week after week after week, pouring out my heart and my mind, and you just don\rquote t know who I am!
\'94 So I didn\rquote t get on with that very well. But bright students, wonderful people around. Very very clever, of course, the acme of English intellectual, a bit strange, bit peculiar, but nevertheless I learnt 
from them really. The other group were a group of Trinidadians - Eric Williams had just taken power in Trinidad, just entered politics, very dramatic entry into Trinidadian politics, with lectures in Woodford Square, and Port of Spain and so on, and he re
c
ruited a bunch of young civil servants, whom he sent to Oxford to train up as the leading echelon when Independence came. They were doing development economics with Mrs. Hicks, Bertha Hicks. They were older than I was, the start of their working careers, 
but they were my natural cohort. And that\rquote 
s where I became a West Indian rather than a Jamaican, because very few of them were actually Jamaicans. We talked about Jamaican politics all the time, about Jamaica, about Independence, about anti-Colonial Movemen
ts. I remember celebrating, with one of them, the fall of the Dien Bien Phu when they threw out the French! (LAUGHS) So, you know, it was a sort of hothead world really, and we used to invite West Indian writers, there was the pure and the West Indian nov
el. Naipaul was in the College next to me; Lamming was already there; Selvon was already there. We\rquote d get them up to speed, and we\rquote d go down to the West Indian Students\rquote 
 Centre in London. So I was polarised between this literary critical world, on the edge o
f trendy Oxford, and this deep involvement in West Indian politics and West Indian life. And really, those are my two main reference groups until I met people from the Oxford Left, which became my third. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
