\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, I should think it\rquote 
s quite early on. Quite early. So these are co-terminous, I guess, and my work is centred around literary theory, my politics and social analysis c
entred round the West Indians. And then I began to meet people in politics. Chuck Taylor, I mean, Chuck Taylor and I and Raphael [Samuel] went on an anti-nuclear demonstration that Raphael organised in 1952. It\rquote 
s way before CND or any of those things. Abou
t a handful of us. Then there was the 12 of them in the Communist Party, and I had a friend called Alan Hall, a classicist, Scotsman, who has since died, but we were sort of Independent Lefty twins really, and I\rquote 
m sure the Communists thought we were like r
ipe plums about to fall into their hands! (LAUGHS) And neither of us had any intention of being, but we were, of course, intrigued by Marx, intrigued by the discussions. They used to let us come to what I think must have been, from the Party disciplinary 
point of view, private political meetings, so that\rquote 
s on the one hand. Then there was the broad Labour Left, etc.. Then there were a bunch of Third World people involved in anti-colonial work. So it was a very broad grouping, and those are my reference groups, as it were, and they\rquote 
re almost entirely students and graduate students, rather than lecturers and professors. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
