\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Were you a Labour Club man, then? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 I used to go to the Labour Club. I
 used to go to Labour Party meetings, but I was not a member of the Party, and I never became a member of the Communist Party, never had any slightest intention of doing so. For some reason I\rquote 
d been inoculated against the idea of the Soviet Union being the
 paradigm case. I remember going to a Communist Party meeting at which Palme Dutt, great intellectual figure, an ascetic Indian, no less, first order, and after Palme Dutt spoke, I thought to myself, \'93
Well, you are the kind of floppy Marxist that he would send to Siberia in about two minutes flat! So I don\rquote t think that world is quite yours. Not quite for you!\'94
 So I never felt, I never suffered the entrancement of the Soviet Union, the hopes vested in the Soviet Union, or, indeed, of the broader aspirations 
vested in the whole Soviet experiment, of people who had been in the Popular Front. Yes? This was by then a narrower political attachment, and I wanted to know about it. But then, when it became more open, I used to go to the meetings that the Communist P
a
rty held, open meetings, and started to debate with them. I remember deciding, at the end of my undergraduate work, when I started to do graduate work, deciding I was going to have a debate about class, in the Communist Party, because I thought their conc
eption of class was antediluvian! (LAUGHS) You know! We can say more about that \endash 
 you can ask me about that if you like. So I entered into a debate, as it were, with people like Raphael. Raphael was very clever, very bright, wonderful historian, from a Part
y family, in terms of his mother and so on, and his uncle, a long tradition of devoting his life to Party work. I remember the point at which Christopher Hill said to him, \'93If you\rquote 
re going to get a First, and continue to be an academic, you have to take a term off, or two terms off, and go home, because you\rquote ll never do it like this\'94
. And he did. He got his First. So he was a luminary really. Very clever. Full of ideas. Very learned about the history of the Soviet Union, about the tradition of British politics, British Socialism, which, of course, I knew very little about. I\rquote 
d done British history, but mainly the Seven Years War! (LAUGHS) You know, I didn\rquote t know anything about all of that, so I really learnt a lot about British politics through the debates wi
thin that Group, and reading around them, and arguing with them and so on. Gabriel [Pearson] was, again, a literary scholar, a magnificent raconteur. Gabriel would turn up at the student house that we went to live in at a certain point, late at night, abo
ut ten o\rquote clock, and start to talk about Dickens, or Henry James, etc., terrific! But we couldn\rquote t actually envisage them managing to get Gabriel out of bed on a Sunday morning, to deliver the Daily Worker to the Cowley workers! It just wasn
\rquote t quite him! Stan
ley Mitchell was slightly separate because he did Russian, so he had a different sort of connection to politics in that sense. A wonderful translator, as you know, of Pushkin and so on, but his connection to the Soviet experience was different because of 
t
his deeper understanding of Russian culture and Russian literature and so on, whereas the others was mainly a political identification of an international kind. But then there were people from the Labour Party, David Marquand - the names escape me. I mean
, they were people who then occupied the front bench, whose aspirations were clearly already located on professional political careers. I\rquote 
ve forgotten his name, and I must try and remember, but he did say to me one day - he became a very sharp and cutting critical Right-wing Labour MP, and he said to me once, \'93The Labour Party is not for the likes of you\'94. And I thought, \'93You
\rquote re probably right, Brian!\'94 - Brian Walden. (LAUGHS) I thought, \'93You\rquote ve got me right, Brian!\'94 So it was a mixed, and, of course, becaus
e it was Oxford, ambitious world. Also, I mean, Heseltine - lots of people who became prominent in the Conservative Party afterwards were also up at Oxford, and other - not strange characters, but, I mean, some astonishing people like Tariq Ali. I remembe
r
 Tariq when he first arrived in his elegantly brocaded waistcoat, as President of the Oxford Union. There was no higher than that. He was who he was, but nevertheless, he was an Oxford figure of distinction. So I began to debate about Socialism and Marxis
m
 with the Left; I began to debate about literature and culture with my cohort in literary studies; and I entered a huge debate with my West Indian colleagues about what would happen once Independence came. What should happen? What could happen? What Jamai
can or Caribbean society was like. George Lamming said, wrote, in The Pleasures of Exile, \'93Most of us became West Indians in London\'94. I arrived as a Jamaican, I\rquote d never been to any other West Indian island, and lots of the others hadn\rquote 
t. People from the southern Caribbean travelled a lot more between the small islands, but Jamaica is way up at the top of the chain. I\rquote 
d never been to anywhere down there at all, so I suddenly discovered there was the rest of the Caribbean, and there was a thing called \'93Caribbean identity\'94. There was a thing called the \'93Caribbean novel\'94
. So I identified with the region, for the first time, in England. And a lot of experience with a lot of other people, that that consciousness was not created in the Caribbean at that point, but a
mong Caribbean people who had left and were looking back, or forward to Independence and what would follow after. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
