\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Well, my Rhodes Scholarship, which had lasted three years, then I was - I had won a Jamaican Scholarship which allowed you to travel abroad, and I\rquote d given it up for the Rhodes, but then they allowed me to take it to do graduate work. So I thought, 
\'93What do you want to do?\'94 Well, by then, I\rquote d become very interested in American literature, as I said to you, through this group of American friends, and I said, \'93I\rquote d like to work on the Thir
ties, a muck-raking novels of the Thirties \endash  Steinbeck, etc., Dos Pasos\'94. \'93Oh\'94, they said, \'93They\rquote re still alive\'94! (LAUGHS) So I began a backward track. Well, anyhow, eventually I ended up with Henry James. \'93
Well, yes, okay. Henry James\'94. Now, in some ways, most of the people I know \endash  not at the time, but since then \endash  are completely puzzled that I would be interested in Henry James, and I can\rquote t think of anybody more different. I don
\rquote t know whether Henry James knew where Jamaica was, or anything like that. There isn\rquote 
t a line about race in his work, really, except for about Jews and Judaism, but about black people, nothing. Aristocratic, etc., in taste, very refined, very pro-European, etc., so what was it about James? Well, I thought that it was what they call the 
\'93international consciousness\'94
 in James. His work is structured around the contrast between Europe and America, and that was what I was, in a completely different dimension, puzzling about. So I regard James as a diasporic novelist, which, of course, n
obody else does, or ever does, but the American, the Europeans, you can see what that\rquote s about. Daisy Miller, about an American heiress, etc.. Then the middle novels - and then the big novels at the end, all of which are about Americans in Europe 
\endash  The Ambassadors \endash 
 an American heiress who saves a very corrupt English pair in The Wings of the Dove; Princess Casanova, American family who married Italian aristocracy, on and on and on, these worlds are culturally and morally contrasted, socially, culturally, mo
rally contrasted. I was more interested in that work than I was in James\rquote s more English-focused novels. I never finished the thesis. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 

