\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 No. I started to work on it, but instead of wo
rking on it in a steadily progressive fashion, I started to go to Rhodes House Library, and read about anthropology. I wanted to know what culture was, and only in anthropology did I see something that resembled what I thought it was. Of course, there was
 
a very exalted conception of culture, which hovered as an ambience around literature and the arts and philosophy and so on. I was interested in that, I was part of that, excited by ideas, but really by culture, to try to understand my own culture, it wasn
\rquote 
t about that, it was about text. Yes, it was about habits, it was about attitudes, it was about unconscious feelings, it was about shared modes of thought, and forms of life. Well, only in anthropology - so I started to go back and read anthropology. One 
of the things I read about, because I was puzzling about Jamaica, was the debate about slavery, and about what had been retained of African civilisations, and how it had been broken up, and, you know, how they\rquote 
d mingled with other cultures to preserve thems
elves and so on. Herskowits: long debates, mainly from American cultural anthropology, but long debates about how Africa survived Colonialism, and how those were were integrated with other cultures, for instance, the language. Jamaican patois, as you know
, is still full of African words, certainly African concepts. The structure of the grammar is English, a kind of English, as it were, it\rquote 
s a kind of fusion of these two languages. And the more I looked around, the more I saw Caribbean culture as a fusion of
 different cultures, essentially not authentic in its own terms. Everybody who came from that region had died out - the Spaniards killed them off in a hundred years, hard work, Arawak Indians, etc., there was nobody left in Jamaica. Everybody there is a c
oloniser, or an African, or an Indian indentured person, or a Chinese trader, or a French person running away from Haiti, it\rquote 
s all somebody somewhere else. But this was one of the puzzles I was trying to track through the anthropological literature, \'93What is this thing, an authentic culture that everybody is rooted in? One authentic culture that everybody\rquote 
s rooted in. How come we folks are not at home quite in any culture, but at home in several at one and the same time?\'94 There\rquote s a point where Salman Rushdie says, \'93I\rquote 
m just one of those mongrels. I am a mongrel. The idea of purity is something which - \'94 well, I think in some ways he\rquote s mistaken, I think Salman could have found an authentic culture if he\rquote d worked at it, but I certainly couldn\rquote 
t! I certainly couldn\rquote t. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
