\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Well, I was, up to that point, just losing any confidence that I could be a writer. Of course, I came, like everybody, and I [hoped] to be, unfortunately, a poet, but I was no bloody good! And then, well, a novelist at least. I knew all tho
se novelists, because I worked on a thing called - the BBC World Service did a programme called \lquote Caribbean Voices\rquote , and all the West Indians writers in London wrote for \lquote Caribbean Voices\rquote 
, and I would do some writing for them. I reviewed some novels, may have read the odd poem, etc., and through that met that circle of writers. So I thought, \'93Well, that\rquote s what I\rquote ll do. I\rquote ll write one of the great Caribbean novels
\'94. But it wasn\rquote t going to happen! First of all, I wasn\rquote t terribly good. But much more, I was too
 critical. My training in criticism destroyed my innate capacity for creative writing. I saw myself in the active ranking too much and too early on. So I settled for the next best thing to a great writer, which is a lukewarm critic! (LAUGHS) I always rega
rded it as a second order career! (LAUGHS) But anyhow, that\rquote s what was happening. So a little bit of publishing of that kind, a little bit of publishing in some of the literary and artistic journals had started in the Caribbean. There\rquote 
s a very good magazine
 called Bim, which, again, reviewed literary developments in the Caribbean. And so on, but not real publishing. Not real publishing. I guess my first publishing was in Universities and Left Review, in the first article I did. It was on Conservatism, inter
estingly enough, in Universities and Left Review. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
