\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Yes. Well, Universities and Left Review comes out of that engagement with sections of the British Left in Oxford. Because as the Cold War
 slowly declined, the barriers between different groups and the suspicions of people being secret members of the NKVD or Soviet spies, etc., had melted away, a wider discussion began to occur amongst the three groups I\rquote 
ve identified. People on the Left - that is to say in the Labour Party, the Communist Group and the Third World Group. And Raphael and I revived a moribund thing called \'93The Socialist Club\'94
, which I think had been started in the thirties, and to which, I believe, the Communists, in the thirties, who\rquote d since become very successful professionals, had signed standing orders that they\rquote 
d never, you know, stopped them! So the Socialist Club was still an entity, though I don\rquote t think it ever met. So we revived the Socialist Club, and the Socialist Clu
b became the centrepiece of this debate, wide-ranging debate, amongst these different groups. So\rquote 54, \rquote 55, a lot of debate going on, etc., and some signs that a similar kind of revival of the Left was going on in other universities, and that
\rquote s where the idea of Universities and Left Review [came], to connect up these debates. And then, \rquote 56, of course, which was a very very important traumatic experience for all of us \endash  and I\rquote ll say why in a moment \endash 
 but its implication for this is that everybody left the Com
munist Party. So this free-ranging Left, and the independent Left, were somehow the inheritors of that tradition, because they were the only people who had stayed outside of the terrible people that had brought the Soviet tanks into Budapest. On the other
 hand, we\rquote d always maintained a Left position on the Empire, Colonialism, Imperialism and Capitalism, etc., so we were very well-placed to be a focus for a lot of debate and discussion. So that\rquote 
s one thing. And very shortly after that, Raphael, of course, ever-ready with a new stratagem, said, \'93We need a journal. We need a magazine for this. Other student groups will come. We\rquote ll join in the debate. We\rquote ll create a big ferment\'94
, etc.. So we began to think about publishing a journal. Well at the same time, Raph
ael left, a lot of other people left the Communist Party. Some people were thrown out. At the same moment at which Edward, and John Saville and that lot are publishing The New Reasoner and being expelled, etc.. So there\rquote 
s a similar sort of grouping a generation ahead of us, rather the same, and Raphael said, \'93Well, we\rquote ll get some of them to write\'94 \endash 
 E.P. Thompson, Lindsay Anderson! So by the time we came to put together the list of editorial contributors to the first ULR \endash  Universities and Left Review \endash  and, by the way, that\rquote s why the title is such a ridiculous title! You won
\rquote t sell a magazine called Universities and Left Review! But that\rquote s what it was, to connect up Left groups in the universities, but to be like the old Left Review, which was a more litera
ry production in the Communist Party. So the idea germinated. And after \rquote 56, we thought, we are the inheritors of the Left tradition. This debate is where it\rquote s happening, it\rquote s not just happening within social democracy, and it\rquote 
s not happening in the Communist Soviet oriented Left, it\rquote 
s happening round here. Well, lots of things to say about that, but one thing in particular. Because I think of the composition of that Group, in part, it was massively preoccupied with the question about culture, and Hoggart\rquote s
 Uses of Literacy was published in that period. Massive debate. And the debate was about what was happening to working-class culture after the War: would it be affected by the American models, and American mass culture? Television and all that was coming.
 
Was capitalism the same as it had been before? Was this new orientation to affluence and consumerism and so on, did this represent another stage or phase of capital? We had to debate that. Well, could class be interpreted in the same way as it had been in
 the high industrial period? What was the equivalent of the cloth cap working class in 1950? So when I say \'93culture\'94, I don\rquote t just mean that it was about cultural questions, it was about culture in exactly this broader sense that I\rquote 
m talking about. But it w
as also about culture in another sense. It paid attention to the cultural dimensions of politics, of the political, and therefore it was from the inception in my head opposed to the narrow base/superstructure model that prevailed within classical Marxism,
 which gave culture, and literature, and the symbolic dimension, a dependent status. It depended on, [was] reflexive of everything else. We just were not able to think about that in that way. So there\rquote 
s a theoretical thread going which leads all the way through cultural studies, and there\rquote s a political thread going of a position in between the major currents and tendencies. Yes? And the focus was on, \'93How would you describe Britain in 1956, 
\rquote 57,\rquote 58? What would you expect it to be? What will this new kind of capitalism be like?\'94 Well, this, as you know very well, was not the debate [just] we were having, we didn\rquote 
t generate this debate, everybody was talking about that! I remember the 1959 Election, Gaitskell\rquote s speech to the Labour Party Conference was, \'93What w
ill happen to the Labour vote in the light of the coming of the small motor car, the washing machine, the fridge, and the television? Will affluence undo all of that?\'94 Well, Hoggart had said, \'93Well, no, but it will change it. It will change it\'94
. I was brought up in this kind of culture first half of the book, and here, in the second half, I\rquote 
m trying to come to terms with how advertising and television and so on is going to change it. So there were deep cultural questions, and the debate about what was the n
ature of modern capitalism was a cultural debate, in part. So we never, we had never made that distinction. But, of course, that gave a particular quality to Universities and Left Review, because not many other Left groups were discussing The Uses of Lite
racy at that time. So I think that just makes sense of the fact that when finally the New Left declined and changed character, cultural studies arose out of it. It\rquote s an ongoing debate. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
