\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes. Yes. Yep! It does. That\rquote s, I think, one of the earliest things I published. But you can see what that is coming out of 
\endash  that debate about affluence. And when we got the New Left Review, I wrote a piece called, \'93A Sense of Classlessness\'94
. Well, the sense of classlessness was left out, it was thought to declare that we were now a classless society, so it was entirely misread, I didn\rquote 
t mean that at all. But I meant there was a growing sense that people were being loosened from their class position and origin, and that in any case the content, social and cultural content of economic classes was being very different in the new p
eriod, and we had to come to terms with it, and to find a language to define that difference. Well, of course, Edward on one hand, and Raphael on the other, came down on me like a ton of bricks! But you know, I think I am vindicated by history! Not the fi
r
st time! But I just think there was something going on there. And, of course, you will have interviewed David Lockwood], so, you know, the question of the affluent worker, of embourgeoisement. And the work that Raphael did in looking at New Towns was an a
ttempt to give a social description of a post-War world. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
