\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes, well, on the back of Raphael\rquote 
s promises, it was going to be well-subscribed! We, none of us, had any money at all! I was living in a student house. Raphael was just about to leave, already left London. Chuck was going back to Canada. Gabriel had a teaching job elsewhere, so
 that particular formation was breaking up in some ways. But we thought we\rquote d press on with this journal. I can\rquote 
t remember having an abstract exactly at one point, we had an abstract discussion with Raphael about how many copies we would get the people to print. We went to the Tribune printers, so they gave us a lot of credit - \'a34,000 \endash 
 where were we going to put them? Well, 5,000. When they were eventually delivered, they came by train to Oxford Station, we had to borrow one of those trolleys that you ran a
long the line to bring the copies back to 12 Richmond Road, for storing! And not very long after that, it was sold out. It was a big success, selling like hot cakes outside of the student body that we had expected. And Raphael said, \'93We need some more
\'94, and I said, \'93We can\rquote t pay for the ones we have! You must only order another 3,000\'94. Perfectly right, they are very scarce these days, can\rquote 
t find one for love nor money! So eventually we got rid of them. But we were always in trouble, financially, because we had no \'85 you know, none of us had any money to draw on, except Chuck. And Chuck\rquote 
s was family money, not easily acquired to sink into some Left wild project in Oxford, you know! But he did keep us going for a long time, as well as spiritually. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
