\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 No. ULR was launched while I was still in Oxford, and I didn\rquote t leave Oxford until \rquote 
57. What there was, was the journal started a Club. One day we decided we\rquote d got so many readers we\rquote d hold a Universities and Left Review Club meeting in London, okay, and have a conversation take place between these readers whom we didn
\rquote t know, and ourselves. Raphael said, \'93We must hire a room in a hotel\'94, so one of the Bloomsbury hotels we had in the end \endash  the Royal or one of those \endash 
 and he insisted that the room be laid out like a scene from Berlin, the thirties Berlin \endash  separate tables, a bit of chess, p
olitical discussion going on etc.. Well, we went away and had an Indian meal, when we came back 700 people were waiting outside to get in. We didn\rquote t have a ticket, we didn\rquote 
t have any idea how much to charge, and two friends, one called Sheila Benson, who had worked in Prague, and a friend of mine, Egyptian friend, a friend called Suzie Benghiat had taken it on themselves to set up a table and charge, I don\rquote 
t know how much, and the room was absolutely crammed full! What were they listening to? Isaac Deutscher lecturing on \'93The Red Sixties\'94, and that\rquote 
s because Isaac Deutscher wrote for the first Universities and Left Review. We knew about Isaac Deutscher, and we wrote to him and said, \'93Would you contribute to this journal?\'94 And I thought, \'93Never, under any circumstances!\'94 When he said, 
\'93Yes, I\rquote ll think about it, but you must come and see me\'94. So Raphael, Chuck and I made a pilgrimage to Reading to see Isaac Deutscher, and he quizzed us about who we were, and he said, \'93All right, I\rquote ll give you a piece which I th
ink is prophetic about changes in the Soviet Union. But,\'94, he said, \'93it is not to be touched. If I give it to you, that is how you must print it. If you don\rquote t want to publish it. That\rquote s copyright to me\'94. We said, \'93
Oh yes, yes, of course\'94. But as you can imagine, when the proofs came back from Universities and Left Review, Raphael had added a footnote saying, (LAUGHS) \'93Since this, I think Madame Futseyeva (??) has been heckled at the car factory,\'94
 you know, completely - well, in line with the piece, but he was furious, as you can imagine! Anyhow, we did it. So we had drawn in the ex-\rquote 56 people, particularly the historians group; we had drawn in a lot of people in the Free Cinema Movement 
\endash  Lindsay Anderson, Karl Reisz, making films about the working-class for the first time, after Jennings, in the post-War period; we touched drama, a member of the Universities and Left Review Club was Arnold Wesker - we all went to see Wesker
\rquote s first play at Sloane Square. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
