\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Oh, it was Raphael\rquote s. I tell you, we climbed into All Souls\rquote 
, Oxford, where Chuck was a Fellow, to take a final decision on whether to go with Raphael\rquote s proposal to start a coffee bar \endash  European style coffee bar, French style coffee bar \endash 
 in London. We spent hours and hours debating it, and we all said, \'93Nobody here has ever run a sweet shop, let alone a coffee bar in the centre of London. No.\'94 We took 
a decision, no, and then the Partisan opened regardless, two or three months later! (LAUGHS) And Raphael, himself, was the impresario: used to go to the market, and buy beetroot to make borscht, and insisted on filter coffee. Well, right opposite where th
e Partisan was, was \'93The Gaggia\'94
. The Gaggia was the home of the first Italian espresso machine in London, so the Partisan had a model somewhere in the past, and the Gaggia was about to be cappuccino, the new cappuccino generation. So people had sort of to 
choose between these two cultural models. I was, unfortunately, addicted to cappuccino, so I would drift across quietly, leaving the filter coffee behind, to the cappuccino. But it was that kind of period \endash  the opening of the Italian caf\'e9
, boys in Italian suits, with Vespas \endash  it\rquote 
s that era. I should say one thing more, which is very important. Universities and Left Review Club was used, in addition to The Partisan, we had offices upstairs, and we had a library, in which you could have small meetings and sem
inars, and a lot of groups - one related to schools, one related to education, one related to film and so on, used to have meetings, 50 people in this room. That became the place from which Ernest Rodkear among others, organised the first leafleting of Lo
ndon for the first Aldermaston March. But also, Universities and Left Review Club became, in \rquote 58, one of the first groups to go into Notting Hill after the race riots, and try to establish or set up with local residents, black and white tenants
\rquote  groups. So we were there negotiating with the Labour Party, with the churches, to some kind of common front. We were there when Mosley made his first appearance on the Saturday morning, you know, first appearance since the War, saying, \'93
Send them back home! They\rquote re just as bad as the Jews, the blacks, etc.. Fascists started to organise. I mean, this was a very very tough period. It\rquote 
s the moment when the underlying racism that had always been there from the end of the War really \endash  \'93No coloureds, no dogs, no Irish\'94, etc
. in lodging houses - really surfaced. The Notting Hill riots. And it was, of course, made more volatile because it connected with the new youth culture that was growing, yes, Teddy Boy culture, a mixture of style and aggression, etc.. So it was a lethal 
kind of combination. I got to know a man called \'93Michael X\'94, yes? Michael de Freitas, who came to the offices one day, and he said, \'93I see your people are on my manor\'94. I said, \'93What do you mean?\'94 \'93
People from your Club are down my way, trying to organise. I can\rquote t remember anybody asking permission\'94. I said, \'93I beg your pardon!\'94 \'93Well\'94, he said, \'93I more or less run things down there\'94, which he did! I said, \'93
What do you do?\'94 \'93Well\'94, he said, \'93you know, I run the streets really. I have connections with the prostitution, but mainly my job is - our job is\'94 - he said \'93ours\'94 \endash  \'93our job is, we work for the landlords\'94
. This turned out to be Rachman. So we stumbled across the Rachman empire at a very very early stage, long before it surfaced as a major question. So I said, \'93Well, what do you do?\'94 He says, \'93Well, we mainly put tenants who can\rquote 
t pay their rent, on the street\'94. I said, \'93But they\rquote re black, aren\rquote t they?\'94 \'93Yes, yes, well, you know, that\rquote s our job\'94. \'93But,\'94 he said, \'93I don\rquote t like it. I don\rquote t want to do that. I
 want to be somebody else\'94. I don\rquote t know whether he knew of Malcolm X, but it was a kind of repetition of the Malcolm X story, you know. \'93I want to do something else, so I want you to tell me what you\rquote 
re all up to, and I will provide contacts in Notting Hill\'94
. So we got involved in Notting Hill. The Club got involved in Notting Hill. So the Club became a more activist centre through these different activities as well as a place where the big Monday meeting debate was still held. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
