\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, Universities and Left Review had its own Editorial Board. The Reasoner had its own Editorial Boa
rd. Because of our common germination in the \rquote 56 moment, we were very close to them, and wanting to know what was going on. Some people in Universities and Left Review - we had four editors, myself, Chuck, Gabriel, and Raphael \endash 
 two Communists, two ex-Communists, and two independent - but we really represented the current of opinion in the Socialist club I\rquote 
ve described to you before. We were sort of leading figures in that debate. It could easily have been three or four other people, but that\rquote s who we were. Well, those we knew of that \rquote 
56 generation had been dissident Communists, historians mainly, who\rquote d been finally expelled or decided to leave, and people like Raphael. Of course, they were not the same generation, but they were the same political formation
, so we always felt very close to them. And after a while we started to have joint Editorial Board meetings \endash 
 we would go to the Reasoner Board, and they would come to the Universities and Left Review. Or we appointed joint people who run both. Edward came to us. They took Raymond, etc.. Then we decided, \'93We aren\rquote 
t managing, financially, to keep either of these journals afloat. We should come together and form one new journal, which was the New Left Review and pool our resources, and then try to make a go of one journal, rather than pinch-hitting for two. It wasn
\rquote t only that people, by then, had been involved in the maelstrom of British politics on the Left, from \rquote 56 onwards, people like Edward and Dorothy Thompson had been tirelessly working, keeping the Ne
w Reasoner alive, financing the New Reasoner, involved in the Yorkshire Peace Movement, you know, they were completely wiped out. Completely wiped out. I sometimes think of their house in Halifax, which I used to go to often \endash 
 I used to sleep in one of the boy\rquote s [rooms] upstairs, beds \endash  and, you know, there was a moment when Lady Eden said, \'93Well, I\rquote m afraid the Suez Canal just flowed through our drawing room\'94, and I thought, \'93
The New Left Review has flowed through the Thompson\rquote s drawing room!\'94 (LAUGHS) And I just don\rquote t think they could go on like that. They couldn\rquote 
t go on doing it. So we had a big launch meeting for New Left Review, we had a joint Editorial Board \endash  pooling the two Editorial Boards \endash  so John Rex was on our Editorial Board, Peter Worsley was 
on our Editorial Board, joined the New Left Review Board. People like Ronald Meek, the economical historian, would be on the Reasoner, Doris Lessing joined the New Left Review Board. So we had a big Board, one journal to try to make a go of. We held a lau
nch meeting and then the question was, \'93Who would edit this journal?\'94 Well, Edward said, \'93I\rquote m finished. I can\rquote t take this on, the baton has to pass\'94
. Raphael? Well, I think the New Reasoner people felt that if Raphael did it, we would be in serious financial difficulties! (LAUGHS) You know, we\rquote d be over-extending ourselves. You know, they just weren\rquote 
t sure he was a secure enough person to deliver on time, etc., etc., etc.. So they asked me whether I would do it, and I stupidly said yes! So that\rquote s how I became Editor \endash  26, 25, 27 \endash 
 not really inward with British politics, you know, not with the long label, working-class tradition. Knew all about it by then, but not formed by it, in the way in which, say, Raymond was formed by it, or Hoggart was formed by it. A
 neophyte really amidst these titles \endash  Edward Thompson, Dorothy Thompson, John Saville, Alasdair MacIntyre, Doris Lessing - can you imagine? - Raymond Williams \endash  Editorial Boards were a complete nightmare for me. \'93
This is what I think are the contents of the next issue,\'94
 holding my hand before the storm broke, before the fathers spoke! (LAUGHS) My great salvation in that period was John Saville, who was the Chairman of the Editorial Board, who was in Hull. John protected me from the wrath that began to eman
ate from Halifax. Because the Thompsons, although they gave it up and couldn\rquote t do it, of course had very distinct ideas about what they wanted it to be, who should appear, what the proper editorial - they were sticklers for editorial procedure 
\endash  quite rightly \endash  acknowledging articles and so on. Frequently we would find the odd article sort of hidden amongst our correspondence, and we\rquote d never even thought of publishing it. So they were quite in their rights to think, \'93It
\rquote s chaos down there.\'94 But they also brought to it a deep suspicion of London. Yes? Provincial left view of the Great Wen, in Edward\rquote s view, full of corruption, full of trendies, etc., So he would fire off these rockets, \'93I see you
\rquote re publishing this. You never sent it to Dorothy and myself, we have views about that\'94. \'93Yes\'94. John Saville would say, \'93Well, I\rquote ll speak to Edward, I\rquote ll talk to Edward\'94
. So I used to go to Halifax quite often for Board Meetings, joint Board Meetings were held there, but I used to go to Hull where John Saville was professor, on Editorial Board business. But I should also say \endash  we haven\rquote t talked about CND 
\endash  but from CND onwards, during the high point of CND, I did a political meeting somewhere in England once every week, every two weeks, so, you know, there are all sorts
 of places in England that I have been to. I once set out from London, because I opened Tribune, and I saw, \'93Speaking tonight is Stuart Hall on the bomb\'94. And I thought, \'93My God! I can\rquote t get there! I must go there now!\'94
 So I rushed to the station, and just before buying my ticket, I looked again, it was at Stuart Hall! There\rquote s a hall called Stuart Hall! (LAUGHS) I\rquote 
d have chased up, because I was just accustomed to going here and there and everywhere. So I really saw a tremendous amount of England, and spoke to the most widest variety \endash 
 Trade Unions, Labour Clubs, a lot of Trade Union audiences; mixed audiences of the Left; ex-Communists; Labour Party people; Left Labour people - a wide variety. Peace Movement people, Pacifists, etc.. So that was really my fi
rst practical experience of political Britain, if you like, political England. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
