\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
No. Raymond Williams is a completely different kettle of fish. I met Raymond because he was an extra-mural tutor in charge of the South Coast \endash  Hastings, he lived in Hastings \endash 
 and he organised classes all around there, but for the Oxford Delegacy of Extra-Mural Studies. So he was always in Oxford, and I met him in Oxford. He used to go to a thing called the Critical Society, closely associated with the critic called F.W. Bates
on, who started up a journal called, I think, Critical Studies or Essays in Criticism - I think it was Essays in Criticism. So we began to meet in the political/literary circles, and Alan Hall, who I\rquote 
ve described to you before, and I started to talk to Raymond, and he sent us to read, it must have been in \rquote 
56, in draft form, two chapters of what became Culture and Society. So from then on, I was close to Raymond, always trying to meet him whenever he came to Oxford and so on, and reading this stuff. He was, 
obviously, also a very distinguished person, and a wonderful thinker with a huge range of imaginative things going on in his head \endash  like Edward \endash 
 but at the absolute opposite end of the pole. You know, the more Edward got into - the more excited he became,
 the more wild the hair would [become, till] you could see him in a sort of prophetic role. The more excited Raymond became, the quieter he became. Yes, went into a kind of Welsh burr: you had to listen very carefully to hear what was being very scrupulou
s
ly formulated. So temperamentally they were at opposite ends of the pole, interested in very different things. But I found Raymond incredibly approachable, and because of his interest in literary, historical, political things, much closer to my own format
i
on than Edward ever had been. So when we started editorially Universities and Left Review, we invited Raymond to become an editor. And Raymond became involved in New Left Review through us and the joint Editorial Board Meetings. He was never a member of t
he New Reasoner. I don\rquote 
t think he worked for it. And that was a very long and wonderful friendship. But they were my fathers. I was younger than them, more inexperienced than them, influenced by their ideas. I thought it was a remarkable opportunity to have
 them as friends and mentors. I didn\rquote t feel I was their equal, I couldn\rquote t debate with them, and often didn\rquote t quite share the positions they had, but I didn\rquote t feel I was able to really take them on. I didn\rquote 
t really want to. I didn\rquote t know enough history to take Edward on. I knew a lot more about the things that Raymond wrote about, but that wasn\rquote t such a divergence from what he was saying. But The Country and the City was a wonderful book 
\endash  literary history. I thought Culture and Society was a fantastic re-re
ading of what really began as the course on morals in Cambridge. He kind of refashioned what he taught on that course into Culture and Society, re-reading the literary critics of the 19th century. And then The Long Revolution, which was the Bible of cultu
re studies. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
