\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well (LAUGHS) how many times have I been asked that question, Paul! Well, I\rquote 
ll tell you first of all about my own - the Editorial Board, as you can imagine, was quite h
ard for me to handle. I had all the editorial responsibilities, and surrounded by these great towering figures of the British intellectual Left, so it was very difficult to negotiate. But then the Clubs started around the country. There were, by the end, 
20 New Left Clubs, and the Clubs said, \'93Well, why don\rquote t we have a more controlling say in the Journal?\'94 You know, \'93We are the Movement in a way\'94. Well, I didn\rquote 
t think that was right, because they needed something more immediately political, they needed a ne
wspaper or an internal bulletin, or correspondence about campaigns that were organised, but the Journal was not like that. It was never going to be like that. So most of the people on the Editorial Board thought, \'93We can\rquote t do that\'94
. But it was a quite strong feeling. And we had a Clubs plus Editorial Board Meeting, where all this came to a head in Wortley Hall in Leeds, in Yorkshire, and I thought, \'93You know what? This is not for me\'94
. So I resigned. Immediately after, there was a huge crisis, of course, as you can imagine, and I was succeeded by a troika \endash  Raphael; Dennis Butt; the American who was Assistant Editor to me \endash 
 Norman Fruchter; Frances Kelly, who was then the New Left Review Secretary; and one other, I can\rquote t remember who the other one was. They w
ere to produce the next issue. Raphael was the guiding inspiration. I could see that although Raphael had gone along with the New Left Review, it wasn\rquote t his kind of thing really. It wasn\rquote 
t really my kind of thing! In some ways it fell between Universities 
and Left Review, which was a more serious journal, and monthly production drove us into a more immediate relationship to campaigning, so the wider debate between the Board and the Clubs was refracted in some of the tensions: why New Left Review could have
 wonderful things in it, but was never, itself, a satisfactory production. So Raphael had different ideas. He\rquote s going to do an entire issue of the Journal on housing. I don\rquote t know whether you\rquote ve ever seen it \endash  it\rquote 
s a double issue, because, of course, it never appeared for months and months! (LAUGHS) It didn\rquote 
t appear. When it appeared it was three times as long as anybody could conceive it. You know, we had to find the money for it, etc., and that was obviously not a permanent resolution. So the Board decided we\rquote 
d have to appoint somebody to be Editor. Well, Perry [Anderson] had come to Oxford I think just before or just after the first generation New Left people left. Yes, I overlapped with him very briefly, I think \endash  I don\rquote 
t remember him very well there \endash  bu
t he belonged with the kind of New Left generation which followed, which started its own magazine, some sort of student journal, and that included Mike Rustin, Alan Shuttleworth, Robin Blackburn, that generation, very mixed in terms of political orientati
on, but that was the generation. And Perry started to do work, and to publish, but was obviously an incredibly intellectual high academic kind of person. I mean, Perry is the only person who still uses six words in any essay that I\rquote 
ve never seen before in the English language! If you have that kind of Eton education, really you just know things that ordinary human beings don\rquote 
t know! He was very very very clever, clearly. Robin was another potential person. But we felt if we had to go for one or other, probab
ly Perry. We took advice around the place, and they said Perry. So it was perfectly decided by [the editors], that Perry was going to be the Editor \'85
 who would be the Editor. He started. He got the offices in Soho Square and so on, but almost immediately it was clear that that echelon had a very distinctive political formation and project of its own \endash 
 very different from the amalgam that had made the old New Left, and it was not going to live in the same house for very long. Anyway, he started to move people in. They really were practically not interested \endash  as they still aren\rquote t \endash 
 interested in British politics. No interest at all really. As Perry Anderson said in Peculiarities of English, we\rquote ve never had a proper bourgeois revolution. Actually, I think it\rquote s had the only real bourgeois revolution we\rquote 
ve seen, but nevertheless, not one like France, not a textbook Marxism, weak, all over the place as compared with the Germans or the French, or the Russians, or Italians. He knew about this other world, could read 
all those languages, spoke Russian, had been to the Russian Language School during his military service, as had a lot of them, a whole group of them. Jeremy Wolfenden was also on that generation \endash  Wolfenden\rquote 
s son, who was The Times correspondent in Moscow, and committed suicide \endash  a lot of them had all been through this highly selective training in \'93intelligence\'94
 - well, Heaven knows what it was! But to speak and to understand, to know about Russia, in the period after the 20th Congress. So high flyer, but w
ith a political project of a much more scholarly, academic, international kind. And gradually people on the Editorial Board became more restive with this project, and it all came to a head when Edward wrote a very long, and so far as I know, unpublished c
ritique of the tendency of the Journal, and Perry \endash  I think I\rquote m right in saying \endash  refused to publish it. And at that point, most of us said, \'93That\rquote s the end\'94
, and left the Board. So they were then free, much freer, to even sideline those people in their own
 generation who were closer to Edward than to us and to Raymond. It was a more selective [group], amongst classical Marxists, high level Marxist analysis, elite, with international connections. Well, out of that came a very high-powered journal over many 
years. Out of that came Verso Books which translated for the rest of us all sorts of Marxist traditions and political traditions we never had encountered first hand. I\rquote 
d never read Lukacs till the translation of History and Class Consciousness appeared. I\rquote d read a little Gramsci \endash  that\rquote 
s another connection I had with Italy, but not before The Prison Diaries ... A tradition, block. The European tradition of Marxism, which they made available to a generation which had never really understood or seen it before.
 So it was a great project. It has its limits I would say, but that\rquote s not what we\rquote re talking about. But it wasn\rquote t the product of the old New Left Review. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
