\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes. You know, by the time we met, which was in the early 1960s, I\rquote d been involved in the New Left, and edited 
New Left Review, I had loads of friends in that milieu. She was 18 \endash  I\rquote m 13 years older than she is \endash 
 so I was already a kind of established figure, you know. We met after an Aldermaston March, and two Aldermaston Marches after that I spoke in Trafalgar Sq
uare, she was on her way to Sussex to do her undergraduate degree. So there was a big disparity between us. But the reason we did was because of my question. Mike [Rustin] had gone to university just shortly after I did, became active in the sort of secon
d generation New Left with Perry Anderson and Robin Blackburn and that generation, and met Margaret \endash  that was Catherine\rquote s older sister \endash  and so they were with me on the march, and they said, \'93
We must introduce you to my younger - my baby sister, Catherine\'94. So we met, and then they were going to Wales, and I was going with them, with a couple of other friends, and they said, \'93Somebody has dropped out, would you mind if Catherine came?
\'94 And she came. So that\rquote s how it started. She was an active YCND\rquote er, though it wasn\rquote t a good period of her life, because her father was a wonderful man \endash 
 Baptist, radical Baptist Minister, not very established, not that sort of figure, but a kind of beatific figure \endash  a wonderful man. He had had a very serious, severe stroke, and he lived for another 13 years, but he was paralysed, couldn\rquote 
t speak very well. So her mother looked after him. It was a big blow on the family, and they moved to London and left Catherine in Leeds to complete her \lquote A\rquote  Levels. And after that, she moved to L
ondon with them. So it was not a happy period of her life. And not a very happy period of mine, because I\rquote 
d, by then, taken the decision to stay, but not fully reckoned what that meant. You know, what did it mean to live in England for the rest of my life,
 rather than in the Caribbean? So we were both at odds, in a sort of odd situation. So we got together. She then went to Sussex to do history, well, you couldn\rquote 
t do history at Sussex, to do whatever amalgam that history was embedded in! (LAUGHS) And I went
 to Birmingham. So we went the opposite directions from London. I had a room, place in London, she went to Sussex, and I spent the first months in Birmingham, travelling every weekend, down to London, going to Brighton, back to London, back to Birmingham.
 And eventually I said, \'93This is not going to work\'94. And she wasn\rquote 
t terribly happy at Sussex either. She liked the courses, some of them, but there was a very intransigent kind of Trotskyist/Entryism in the Labour Party Group, which picked on her - very innocent, active Young CND\rquote 
er, Socialist, etc., and because of me \endash  I think they got at me through her \endash  so she wasn\rquote t very happy. So I said, \'93Well, why don\rquote t we get married and you come to Birmingham?\'94 Which is what we did. By Christmas \rquote 
64, we were married, she left Sussex, transferred to Birmingham, so came to Birmingham to live with me, and started history, a different kind of history altogether, with Rodney Hilton, and did the full three years at Birmingham. So that\rquote 
s the background. So by then we were living together, and she was really an undergraduate, and I was already the research person with Richard Hoggart at the Centre. So that\rquote s a long time ago, and we\rquote 
ve been together all that while. You may want to ask more about this, but I\rquote ll just say two thin
gs. One is, it took a long time equalise that balance, between me as a more established figure on the Left, in his early thirties, and an 18-year old trying to learn how to become a historian. It took a long time. There was a big imbalance, and I\rquote 
m afraid,
 in my characteristically masculinist way, I thought this was right! (LAUGHS) We have love letters in which I in entirely D.H. Lawrencian language, sees planets circling around the moon! (LAUGHS) Ridiculous nonsense! But when you look back at them they we
ren\rquote t at all anti-Feminist or anything, one just assumed that the man led, and was experienced and knew things, and talked well, and did theory. So righting that balance took a long time. It was not easy. And it\rquote 
s quite a while before our interests began to converge, and then, really, we were able to learn from one another, though she said she always learned from me. But I didn\rquote 
t think, in that area, I had much to learn, I learnt that, and then I learnt from her! (LAUGHS) So there\rquote s been a shift in the balan
ce of the relationship all the time. The second thing is, of course, Feminism. Because what happened was that she finished her degree, got a very good degree, decided to stay on to do her Ph.D. in Mediaeval History, with Rodney Hilton, started it, got pre
gnant. Well, now she\rquote s locked up at home with a young baby, starting a Mediaeval History Ph.D., and I\rquote m teaching my life out at the Centre. So she was ready-made for first-wave Feminism. And lots of other people like her \endash 
 those mothers with academic, or husbands, or people who worked elsewhere, who are locked up for the first time, at home, with children - got together. So Birmingham started a cr\'e8
che, and a school, and jointly parents looking after other children, and the whole neighbourhood became a kind o
f Feminist network. So it took root in that. So the second thing is that this is a very difficult period for us, because that rubbish about moons and planets just had to go! It had to go! (LAUGHS) And what I discovered from it is that you change your idea
s
, but your practice is much more stubborn. So, of course, I was in favour of this equality. Of course! Obvious! So obvious, you know! Men bossed them about and tell them what to do, as I have done with Catherine, so this has to stop. But what was an alter
native way of relating to one another? I didn\rquote t believe many could become Feminists, I still don\rquote 
t believe that. I think they can become sympathetic to it, and understand it from the inside, and try to change their own practice In any case, you\rquote ll almost certainly remember, the beginnings, the early stages of second-wave Feminism, they didn
\rquote t want to hear from me! \'93Shut up! We\rquote re going somewhere else. Have our conversation, listen to our own voices for a change!\'94 So that has been another big transformative m
oment for us. It took quite a long time, and by the end our relationship was very different from the dependent/independent thing that it started out. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Different in what way? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 

\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 In every way, Paul. It\rquote s hard to pinpoint. I mean, I just assumed our inequality, and after that I couldn\rquote 
t assume it. I had to assume our equality, and therefore had to tolerate - you know, if she\rquote d have friends I didn\rquote t particularly like, okay. We had to decide what sort of marriage it was: an open marriage \endash  whatever that is \endash 
 or, we\rquote re going to try to remain monogamous. What did that tell you about men and women, and about marriage, as a kind of contract, a binding contract on women. Then there\rquote s the sexual politics. So it\rquote 
s a period of huge turbulence. And because Catherine was involved in all of that \endash  very actively involved \endash 
 it was a matter of in the home as well. How do you bring up the children? Do you give the boys guns? I had always had guns, I grew up with holsters and air rifles at home! Yes, but what does that mean? Why don\rquote 
t they have dolls? Dolls? What about the girls, read them cowboy stories, etc.! (LAUGHS) So, in every detail, we had to re-think the whole of that. Were we going to stay together? And if we were staying together, it was going to transform
 our relationship. And eventually there was no question, we decided to do so, but after that we couldn\rquote t live the old relationship. Not possibly, inconceivably. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 And what about with the children, then, did it change your relationship with them? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes. But as I say, you know, she started to change, almost with their birth, so it\rquote s really pretty much right through. She
\rquote s there in the Play Group, one of the first Feminist Play Groups, called \'93The Pumpkin Shell\'94. Catherine\rquote s written, they\rquote ve written a pamphlet called, \'93Out of the Pumpkin Shell\'94
, in which they set up this group for - a lot of our friends were involved, and the men were all helping, while the women had discussions, the men were helping with the kids, and helping at the school. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
