\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Very interesting. And I was wondering, you were a mixed couple, and is that something you were very aware of, or not? }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 We were aware of it. I was aware of it. The truth is, Paul, I will never not be aware of it. I\rquote 
m perfectly comfortable in England, I feel I know the English like the back of my hand \endash  I\rquote m married to one, I\rquote m friends with so many English people \endash  and anyhow, what else am I? But I can\rquote 
t ever forget that I am, in some significant ways, different from other people, and the mixture is partly race and colour, but it\rquote 
s then also the reminder about quite another history. That which is still present in me, came into the relationship through me, and makes me a different person. That\rquote s what
 I tried to talk about a little bit, just to suggest, in what I said at my 80th birthday \endash  I lived my relationship to Jamaica, which had become impossible \endash  it would have finished me off. I couldn\rquote t stay there, and I couldn\rquote 
t go back there. It is \'93home\'94, but I didn\rquote t feel at home in it, and decided to live in England, which is now \'93home\'94. But I don\rquote t feel quite at home here either. So that\rquote s me. And I\rquote 
m sure Catherine, as a young 18-year old Yorkshire lass, was completely - I mean, I don\rquote t know, I\rquote ve never 
talked to her about, the early times we met and started to go out, what on earth did she thought? A mixed couple was much rarer then, as you can imagine, mixed middle-class couple. I remember failing to meet her, because I was at some CND ExeCurtive, when
 I was taking her to see Antonioni in his L\rquote 
Avventura, and made her wait an hour and a half outside the cinema in Soho! Well, you know, and up I rode! So from then on, for a long time], often we were the only mixed couple in the room, absolutely. Amongst Ne
w Left people, I was the only black person. We were the only mixed couple. So I\rquote m both aware of it, but it didn\rquote t stop us. And she, I think, would say, \'93
Well, I just grew into it. I met him before I really understood what I was doing, and after that my life has just been as a mixed couple\'94. But objectively, of course, that wasn\rquote 
t always easy. When we went to Birmingham, we had to find a place to live, very difficult. Birmingham atmosphere was declining significantly after Powell and all of that, so it wasn\rquote 
t easy. People shout terrible things at us, as a mixed couple, often more nastier things at her than at me, , for going out with a black man, etc.. But it was sort of outside our relationship. Our relationship has never been structured around that as an e
motional focus. It\rquote 
s been structured around that as a cognitive focus because, of course, I was always interested in it, and we went to Jamaica all the time, she met my family, she understood what my feelings about that were. Then she became interested in J
amaica, then she did research in Jamaica, together. I took her all over the country to go to these Baptist Chapels in the most remote parts of Jamaica which other people didn\rquote 
t even know existed, and she became a Caribbeanist and now she knows much more about the Caribbean and about Jamaican history than I do \endash  much more! So that\rquote 
s another aspect of the tilt, yes? But we are, therefore, conscious of racialised and colour differences, but it has never been the subject of trouble, or difficulty between us. Th
ere have been all sorts of other things, like in every marriage have been, but I don\rquote t recall that that ever was. I don\rquote t think I ever felt, \'93She would like out of this relationship because it\rquote s a mixed one\'94
. Never. I just thought, \'93She came into it as an innocent, and she just never thought of it\'94. (LAUGHS) She never thought from within that position. Other people put us in that position, but she never thought, \'93We\rquote re in that position\'94. }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 What about the families, did they relate to each other? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Well, my family, of course, remained in Jamaica. In that period I had virtually nothing to do with them. We went back home a couple of times after we were married \endash  Catherine went with me \endash  but then I broke off relations really, so we didn
\rquote t have much relationship between the families. I very much remember, after we got married, the first time Catherine and I went home on a banana boat \endash 
 wonderful journey, 13 days, out of London, first to Barbados, then to Trinidad, then to Jamaica on the way back to En
gland to pick up the bananas, etc.. Banana boats had - bananas were first class citizens and the rest of us were sort of making up the space! (LAUGHS) So that was a very big experience, and difficult for her, because in that period, the animosity - it
\rquote s in
 the middle of Black Power, and the middle of all those troubles, and the Rastafarianism and so on, so the idea of mixed black couples was not a good thing, not an easy thing for her. And she internalised that, she felt people were thinking of her as a on
e of the perpetrators of all the things they\rquote d suffered from. So it\rquote s not been easy for her. Whereas now, she has a much easier relationship to it. It\rquote s not that it\rquote 
s unproblematic, but then our relationship to it is non-problematic. She had a much easier relationship to it. But there was never much of a time when - I don\rquote t know that my family ever met her family. She\rquote s from a very different background 
\endash  Yorkshire. Her father was converted, being Baptist, went to Oxford to theological college. Became a Baptist Minister, well-known in his region. Belonged to the Liberal Wing of the Baptist Church, not the Conservative one. Her mother\rquote 
s family had been millers. And they met at Oxford, because her mother \endash  my mother-in-law \endash  was one of the first women to go to Oxford. She was a kind of blue stocking. And very good historian. There\rquote 
s a reference to her research in Christopher Hill\rquote s big book. So this was a completely different world from my family. They wouldn\rquote t have gotten on. They wouldn\rquote t have understood one another really. But it wasn\rquote 
t like a normal migrant family these days, in which my family came a lot and met everybody else. It\rquote s very much outside of my family. I just decided I was staying. I wanted to marry Catherine. They - it was quite complicated but, 
you know, they accepted me without question. I had known the family through Margaret, even before I met Catherine, and Michael\rquote 
s family and so on, it was going to be my home. So we decided to get married with no reference to - one of the reasons [for] the final break with my family was because they kept interfering in my relationships. They\rquote d always done that \endash 
 usually on social or racial or class grounds, and after that, just because they didn\rquote t like the sound of the people I wrote to them about! So by the time it got to Catherine, well, if they\rquote d written to say, \'93Not appropriate\'94, I wasn
\rquote t interested in that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Did you cut off, really, for a while, from Jamaica? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes. I did. There was a period in which I didn\rquote t go. I think it\rquote 
s the period from when I was in Oxford, over the New Left, it\rquote 
s the period of my transition to England, and a politicisation here, and of my coming to terms with why I felt so alienated from my middle-class, coloured, Jamaican background, and why I felt th
ey had blocked my pathway to establishing what I felt was an authentic relationship to the majority of Jamaican people. I never felt I was just another brown middle-class Jamaican boy, never felt like that. I wanted to be. That\rquote 
s what I wanted to be. You know, I just wanted to be perfectly ordinary! You know, just another Jamaican lad. But I wasn\rquote t. I\rquote d been brought up in this incredible - well, I\rquote 
ve described it - this pathological world. Really, it was pathological. And this colonial world. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 [Later] you re-established your relationship with Jamaica, didn\rquote t you. You started visiting again. So when did that happen? }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well my mother, brought my sister on a trip to England, shortly after I\rquote d met Catherine, that\rquote s \rquote 
64, so there must be a period sort of in the early sixties when I decided, \'93Look, I\rquote m not going back home. I understand, now, what happened to me, and that phase of my life is over\'94. I can\rquote 
t remember whether I went very often in that period, when I was doing graduate work. But then, by the time I got together with Catherine, we went, and they said, \'93Do come\'94
. And before that, my mother came, brought my sister on a visit, so by then, clearly \endash  that\rquote s \rquote 63 \endash  I had re-established a distant relationship with my family. Jamaica is sort of diff
erent. I always was involved in what was happening in the Caribbean and Jamaican politics and Jamaican writing, and because I felt they didn\rquote 
t represent Jamaica - I had another relationship, which they stood between me and it. But once I was in England, I had a relationship to my Jamaicanness, through the diaspora. When they came, I thought, \'93Well, they\rquote re just like me!\'94
 Jamaicans who, for unemployment, or for whatever reason, [or like] me, because of unhappiness and my terrible formation, find ourselves in England at the same time - strangers, brown, we\rquote re going to have make a life for ourselves. We won\rquote 
t become the same sort of people, but they are not going to be Jamaicans like the Jamaicans I wanted to be. They\rquote re going to be transformed by it, and I\rquote m n
ot going to be the old son of a colonially-oriented coloured middle-class family because I will have changed too! So what changed was, I wasn\rquote 
t going back to live in it. Yes? That was a tremendous break, because before that, I thought there was a clear path \endash  I\rquote d go to Oxford, I\rquote d get my degree, I may stay around a little while, then I would go back. I\rquote 
d go and teach at the University or something like that, and I may get involved in West Indian politics. That was the trajectory. That trajectory was broken,
 it was fractured. I never re-established it in those terms, but in terms of wanting to know what was going on, and feeling and identifying with it, tremendously so. I mean, it\rquote 
s interesting that my generation at school, bigger boys and that generation of 
younger ones, became the new class that inherited power and authority and everything, position, from the Colonials. They were the inheritors of de-colonisation, so I know them all. You know, the day I arrived at Jamaica College, well, not - the week, Norm
an Manley\rquote s son, Michael, was dismissed from school. I think I may have told you this. So the politics was inside the School and so on, so that group became very involved. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
