\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Yes. Exactly. Exactly. I identified with this, of course. You know, when I came to England, I was already in that position. Quite political, very anti-Imperial; anti-Colonial politics; very
 pro-self determination; waiting for Jamaican Independence; aware of growing black consciousness; and though I didn\rquote 
t have it, aware of poverty and unrest. I left Jamaica already politically completely transformed. Not very experienced, and not understandi
ng it very profoundly, but I was a different kind of person from my parents, which is partly what created the distance between, because I thought, \'93You don\rquote t agree with a single thing that I think\'94
. I was six in 1938, which is the big rioting that happens throughout the Caribbean \endash  especially in Jamaica \endash  and it\rquote 
s the birth of modern Caribbean politics, modern Jamaican politics, and of the Independence Movement. It gives a huge fillip to it. Well, in 1938, when all the rumours came from Kingston, \'93The mobs are on the march and the blacks are taking over\'94
, my mother said to me, \'93Well, this is the end of my world. This is the end of our world\'94. So I couldn\rquote t belong to that. I was already transformed. So when I came to England, although I couldn\rquote t participate i
n it, I still felt it was a continuation of the things I was identified with. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
