\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Oh, it was a secondary modern school at Kennington Oval \endash  I\rquote 
ve forgotten what it was called. Oh, there was one called Kennington Secondary, and then there was another called Stockwell Manor, and I think I was
 at Kennington Secondary. So it was one of those schools which was so forbidding that supply teachers, if they survived, instantly became full-time. I never left it. I walked in to do a job on a Monday, and was a class teacher by the end of the month! (LA
UGHS) So I stayed quite a while. And I taught - as you did, in those days \endash  formally, everything: English, geography, some of it I was complete acronym. I could never do, I said, \'93I won\rquote t teach maths, because I was badly taught, and I
\rquote m not going to muck up somebody else\rquote s mathematics. But English, of course I can teach English. And literature, yes. And a bit of French, yes. Geography\'94. I thought, \'93
I learnt geography in my sixth form, you know, it was one of my early sixth form subjects, of course I can teach geography\'94. I well remember when somebody came into my classroom and looked at the map I\rquote 
d drawn on the blackboard, with the South-East and South-West Trades, and I\rquote d got them wrong! I called them North-East - and he said, \'93I think there\rquote s a black moon out! I think it\rquote s not quite right on the blackboard!\'94
 But actually, of course, what I was doing was minding the class, teaching them football, or taking them to the playground, preventing a riot. Taking them swimming, a long march through the centre of Clap
ham, of Kennington, to the swimming baths and back, etc., that\rquote 
s what I was doing. But I was also teaching them. And they were from, overwhelmingly, families who worked in the print, and the parents worked in the print, and because of protective Union prac
tises, they were all going to get jobs in the print, so they didn\rquote t have anything to lose at mucking about in class. Why would they need any \lquote O\rquote  Levels? Nobody took any \lquote O\rquote  Levels, which was GCSE at that time. They didn
\rquote t need to. \'93We\rquote re okay, sir, our parents work in the print, and my dad\rquote s going to get me a job as a printer for a newspaper in Fleet Street\'94
. But it was a big experience because, of course, I then met and had a lot to do with the children of a sector of the English working-class that I\rquote d never encountered. I certainly never encountered in childhood in that way before. \'93
My dad will come in and see you].\'94 \'93My big brother\rquote s gonna come in and see to you, sir!\'94 (LAUGHS) \'93Yes\'94. I remember they said, \'93Well, can you teach them geography?\'94 \'93Yes, I\rquote ll try\'94. \'93Can you teach them history
\'94. \'93Well, Yes, Yes\'94. \'93Can you take them swimming, teach them life-saving\'94. I said, \'93I can\rquote t life-save\'94. \'93Oh well, we have a book\'94
. They gave me this book. I could swim, of course, but I could never life-save. So I thought, \'93You\rquote re going to drown one of these boys\'94
, so I did practice, I read the book, and we did practice on the hall upstairs, them lying down, you get your arm round, you pull, with the hope that I could stave off actually taking them to the swimming bath! But eventually I couldn\rquote 
t, so the crocodile wove its way through Kennington to the swimming baths, and eventually I didn\rquote t lose anybody, fortunately! Not only that, but we then built up a very good swimming team which won trophies, so, you know, it was all all
 right. But I was a neophyte at the first, innocent of the first order, and never planning to go on being a secondary teacher. The other thing I need to say, which I think I haven\rquote 
t said so far, I was then taking the train from Clapham to go up to Soho, at half past four, to start editing University Left Review. The ULR offices were at the corner of Soho Square, and I\rquote d be there in the evening, sometimes until two o\rquote 
clock in the morning, take the night bus from Trafalgar Square back to Clapham, sleep a bit, and be in class the next morning. So I\rquote d lead completely double lives. In school, form master, I was the master of what was called, in those days, \'934FX
\'94, which I believe used to be called after that, \'934F-Remove\'94. I don\rquote t know what \'93Remove\'94 means, but all the kids in my class had been removed from something, or had something removed! You know, they\rquote 
d all failed the 11+ - everybody in the school \endash  so they were the failures of the failures of the 11+. So, you know, academic work was not really in their purvie
w. I tried to teach them English grammar, because I thought this would be a way of improving their writing. Can you imagine, gerunds, adjectival clauses! (LAUGHS) Oh God! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
