\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 So were they rowdy? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 

\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Oh yes, rowdy, undisciplined, rude, threatening
, but quite lovable as well. I was very fond of them. I wrote a piece about teaching. After Colin McInnes\rquote s novel, Absolute Beginners, which is in ULR, called \lquote Absolute Beginners\rquote . It\rquote 
s about my teaching experience, and about, therefore, seeing through the
 eyes of that generation: first, the birth of youth culture, because they started to be interested in music. Secondly, the rise of racism. Because one evening I got on the train, and lots of kids from my class were on the train. I said, \'93
What are you doing here? You never leave Clapham, you\rquote ve never left Clapham in your life! You don\rquote t think you need to leave Clapham to see the world!\'94 \'93Well, we\rquote re going over the other side, sir\'94. So I said, \'93
Where are you going?\'94 \'93Notting Hill, sir\'94. I said, \'93Well, what\rquote s going on over there?\'94 \'93Trouble. Trouble. Trouble with the blackies\'94. \'93What sort of trouble?\'94 \'93Well, tthey play loud music and they\rquote 
re taking our women\'94. I said, \'93Our women? You would be so lucky!\'94 I said, \'93You don\rquote t have any women, what are you talking about?\'94 So I said, \'93You mean me?\'94 \'93Oh, not you, sir\'94. I said, \'93
Well, do you mean the boys from Brixton who are in our class?\'94 \'93Oh, not them, sir! Them!\'94 So I said, \'93Well, what goes on over there?\'94 Well, I soon discovered. They were going, standing in front of
 the tube stations, monitoring the passage of black men and women coming from work, and going into the back reaches of North Kensington \endash  Powys Terrace, and the terraces behind there \endash 
 full of multi-occupation, crumbling North Kensington housing, and shout
ing abuse at them. And behind them, in the summer, with the open doors of the pubs, and the fathers, or the equivalent of the fathers, were egging them on. So in spite of the fact that I didn\rquote t intend to stay there, didn\rquote 
t intend to become a teacher, or re-train as a teacher, I, nevertheless, saw a lot, felt a lot of what was going on. And because I was involved in the New Left Club, we then \endash  which was by then an active Organisation \endash 
 we then became involved in Notting Hill - in political work in Notting Hill \endash  in the aftermath of the riots in \rquote 58. I think talked about that, yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 But in terms of teaching, they were all white, there were virtually no black [children]? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
