\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 No, we didn\rquote 
t do much literature. I mean, I remember us trying to get them to read a scene from Romeo and Juliet! (LAUGHS) Because I thought the Montagus and the Capulets would 
appeal to their emerging gang mentality, but the language was just completely impossible. We read simple stories, but there wasn\rquote t much literature teaching as such. It\rquote 
s a keeping the kids off the street business at that stage! Just making sure they don\rquote t run riot. A bit of discipline. Some of the older teachers could do it more than the younger ones. If my class said, \'93We\rquote 
ve been in class all day, sir, it\rquote s time to go the playground, have a game\'94, \'93Mmm, Yes. Okay. Don\rquote t make too much noise, because I\rquote m not supposed to take you to the playground.\'94 But it\rquote 
s the last class of the day. You know, negotiating with them for that. But not much teaching in terms of content. I was teaching literature elsewhere. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
