\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Well, I was, at the same time, making some money teaching Adult Education for Raymond. Raymond was an Adult Education tutor, whose home base was the Oxford Delegacy of Extra-Mural Studies, but he was a staff tutor in Hastings, and I worked for Oxford Dele
gacy who ran classes in the Bexleyheath area, in the Heath area \endash  in Heath\rquote s Constituency. I would go every Friday night and lecture on Dr. Zhivago, Middlemarch, or Jane Austen. I\rquote ve forgotten who I\rquote ve told this story to 
\endash  maybe you, in which case expunge it! But, you know, an old gent - I went to a library and gave a lecture on George Eliot, and he came to me afterwards and said \endash  this old gent, grey-haired - tottered up, and he said, \'93
Well, I liked that very much\'94. He said, \'93It\rquote s my 13th class on Middlemarch\'94
. He just went to Adult Education literary classes, filling his life. But then I started teaching in Bexleyheath on a Friday night, at an Adult Education Centre, and the teaching became more intense, and almost all the people there were ex-Communists or
 members of CND, so it became more politicised. I mentioned Dr. Zhivago, you can imagine why we read Dr. Zhivago in that context. Yes, it was really exciting kind of discussion. And one of the people, one of the families there were the father and mother o
f a guy called Ben Brewster, very very clever, who became actively involved in New Left politics, translator of Althusser, and so on. So it was an interesting milieu. But that\rquote 
s my Adult Education teaching. Then I was teaching, well, teaching, you know what I\rquote m talking about \endash 
 not necessarily hired as a teacher, but teaching for the British Film Institute, because I was very interested in film. I met Paddy Whannel, a Scot, working-class man, who was in charge of education at the BFI. And Paddy started promot
ing the teaching of a bit of film in schools. Well, you couldn\rquote 
t teach it without extracts from the BFI Education Department, started to produce teaching extracts, the Western, the musical, melodrama, thrillers, etc.. And I was doing lectures in that kind 
of thing to film appreciation societies in universities around the country. So I was doing all sorts of teaching of one kind or another \endash 
 in school, in Adult Education, in film, and so on. Then I got hired at the Chelsea Advanced College of Science. I can\rquote t remember what it - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
