\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Oh well! Well, after the C.P. Snow debate about the two cultures, there\rquote s a period in which colleges like that \endash 
 the Chelsea College of Advanced Technology \endash  the Technology Colleges had to give some literary, artistic, or social sciency kind of teaching, and the sort of more literary colleges \endash  teachers, education \endash  had to inc
lude some science. So there was a Department, at Chelsea, which promoted this work, and I was hired to teach film and television, and I think I may be the first full-time appointment in a university, in this curious way, in what then became media studies.
 
So I used these extracts that we were generating, that Paddy was generating, and used them in class for discussion. And we became involved in the kind of movement within the English teaching profession, which wanted to address the question of the modern m
edia. Because they were aware that the kids were not listening to them at all, they were listening to Elvis Presley! (LAUGHS) And so, \'93How do we discuss this in class?\'94
 And because we were involved in doing a bit of teaching in schools, Paddy and I started to meet to write a book to help them out. And that is The Popular Arts, and that\rquote 
s a result of our friendship, and my then spending weekend after weekend with Paddy and Kay and their son, Gary, Whannel, in Putney. Home from school at the weekend, I\rquote d go th
ere early Saturday morning, I would stay overnight. First of all Paddy would talk to me about golf, which I\rquote ve never played and didn\rquote 
t know anything about, because he was deeply, a Scot, working-class, golfer. But very smart, very natty dresser he was. Lov
ely man. Wonderful man. On the Editorial Board of New Left Review eventually, and of Universities and Left Review. But we would listen to jazz, listen to Billie Holliday, talk about television, watch television, talk about films, talk about advertising, a
nd that\rquote s what became the book. But the book was really a teaching manual. If you want to teach this stuff in schools, this was how you might do it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
