\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Well, it was a turning point, because, you know, now - am I still a literary scholar? Not sure. Not sure. I mean, I never really was, but we might go over that if you\rquote 
re interested. But not even to the degree that that was in Oxford, was I a writer \endash  which is what I really wanted to become \endash  no, I wasn\rquote t. I wasn\rquote 
t going to be a writer. Unfortunately, becoming a critic had destroyed my creative capacities, say. So, you know, I was too analytic, not willing to just give myself up for experience. So I decided, \'93You\rquote 
re not going to be one of the great novelists\'94. Like the group that I was close to in that period, in London, I was also doing some programmes for a thing called, \'93Caribbean Voices\'94
 on the World Service, which was an incredibly important organisation, was the nursery of Caribbean writing in England. So that\rquote s where I used to do some writing, some reviewing. There I met Sam Selvon and George Lamming, and E
dward Brathwaite, the whole generation of writers, mainly writers who had emigrated at exactly the same time as I had, living in England. George Lamming wrote an account of this in a book called, The Pleasures of Exile and he said - and it was true of the
m, and it was true of me \endash  \'93We are the generation that became West Indian in London\'94. We\rquote d all arrived with our Trinidadian, or Jamaican or Guyanese identities, and we became West Indian here. So we all worked for West Indian \endash  
\'93Caribbean Voices\'94. So I was still in touch with creative writing and with that group, but I wasn\rquote t going to be one of those. So what on earth was I going to be? Well, I was going to be somebody who worked on some of this stuff I\rquote 
d tried to help secondary teachers talk about, was going to do stuff on the media, or stuff on film, or stuff on popular culture. I mean, in some ways, the whole area that I\rquote 
m talking about is the area of popular culture, and my interest in popular culture is really a huge turning point in my intellectual academic interest. Huge. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
