\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Yes. It was about that, in part. It was the residue, but it was also the product of being a kind of critic and associated with critical debate in Oxford, very much influenced by F.R. Leavis. We were in Oxford, Leavis and Scrutiny were in
 Cambridge, but we thought, although he had a very elitist, undemocratic social programme, that Scrutiny was a serious journal, and thought culture was a serious matter, and literature was a serious issue, and language was a serious issue. Whereas my own 
tutors in Oxford, I thought, were just dilettantes. They savoured literature over the port, but they hated Leavis, they hated that what my tutor called \'93the beetle-browed Puritanism\'94
. So we sort of identified with that spirit, although we were very critical
 of many aspects of Leavis, and one of the things that interested us was, of course, that Scrutiny and Leavis became interested in popular culture. Q.D. Leavis wrote the book on popular fiction \endash 
 18th century popular fiction. And Leavis, himself, took part in these debates on modern advertising, from the position of the decline of cultural values, of course, which wasn\rquote 
t exactly our take on it, but that was bringing a kind of more stringent critical sense to bear on the arena of popular culture. But that wouldn\rquote 
t be right to think of this as the point of my transition from literature into something else, because I\rquote 
d always been more interested in the social dimensions of literature. So even when I was doing my undergraduate degree, I wanted to know not only Shakespeare, but Shakespeare\rquote 
s relationship to popular theatrical traditions, to spectacles and the mediaeval plays. I was always interested in the background, always interested in the social context, and that had arisen much more from becoming an adept ob
server and critic of my old social milieu. So though it looks like, well, at this point you started to be interested in wider things, it wasn\rquote 
t quite like that. It became more formalised, more central to my intellectual work, but always been present. I thi
nk I may have described to you before, my aunt took me to the cinema, the matinee cinema in Kingston, at the Carib Theatre, every Saturday afternoon. I saw every Humphrey Bogart, Lana Turner, Bette Davis [and John Crawford], musicals, millions of Westerns
, I just imbued with popular culture. Then, of course, I was interested in the popular culture of Jamaica \endash 
 African residues, African rhythms, etc. It never occurred to me until much later, that this would be regarded from the position of traditional high culture as a kind of slumming. I never thought of it as that. Okay, let\rquote 
s not formalise the study of film, but film is manifestly the most exciting 20th century art form - just how I lived it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Mmm. Now, in the book, [you argue that] the best popular
 artist as good as the best high cultural artist. There are just different criteria. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes. Now, at that point, it becomes a more sustained serious and theoretical issue, yes? Because I begin to understand that there
\rquote 
s a difference between the criteria being applied to high culture, and the criteria being applied to popular culture. High culture is serious - Shakespeare, Mozart, the great painters, etc.. Popular culture is all this rubbish about Bette Davis and Lana T
urner and, you know, Joan Crawford, and, you know, Guys and Dolls, and, you know, it\rquote s inferior. That\rquote s very much the stamp of Leavis, yes? This represents the decline of Western civilisational values. Well, I felt, \'93It\rquote 
s a funny thing, because I\rquote m into it as well!\'94 I love Shakespeare, I love Moby Dick, and I love \'93My Darling Clementine\'94
, and what am I to do with that? So I began to understand this as a socio-cultural phenomenon, and to disentangle the critique of high culture from the actual quality. Yes? I
 mean, Billie Holliday has an incredible voice, a great opera singer has an incredible voice \endash  they\rquote re not the same voice. But Billie Holliday isn\rquote t not worth taking seriously because she\rquote 
s a drugged black woman singing the blues, do you see what I mean? This is a social judgement, not a judgement on the thing itself. It\rquote s a social judgement. This is a category of what the common people listen to. It isn\rquote 
t television, all those cheap media and so on. The other thing has been taken up into aesthetic and philosophical and theoretical refinement. So it\rquote s a judgement about social refinement as much as it\rquote 
s a judgement that this book is better than that. After all, there are books in hard cover, they\rquote re a load of rubbish! And there are books in paperback that are wonderful! Chandler is a fantastic story-teller. I\rquote 
m listening, still listening, in my audio, to The Big Sleep. It\rquote s a wonderful novel, and his use of language is incredible. It\rquote s as good as any of the thirties writers like Steinbeck and so on. But Oxford didn\rquote 
t regard even Steinbeck as serious literature. You know, it\rquote s too popular, etc.. So I began a kind of cultural critique of the category of high culture, and of popular culture, and about that split. Then all the things I\rquote 
ve mentioned to you before are beginning to become an intellectual question, a theoretical question, as well as a practical love or experience of identification. I\rquote m constituting it as an arena of enquiry. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
