\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 But one of the things I noticed, too, there, was that you argue in favour of what you call the \'93direct response\'94
 as a way of evaluating popular art. Would it be worth saying something about that \endash  how that relates to more traditional ways of deciding what\rquote s good and what\rquote s not good. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, the \'93direct response\'94, there\rquote 
s not much in evidence (LAUGHS) not much in evidence in high culture. You know, understanding it, appreciating its values, but nobody said, \'93Do you really absolutely adore Turner?\'94 And, \'93Does he give you a heart lift?\'94 Well, you couldn\rquote 
t not say that about \'93My Darling Clementine\'94, or Billie Holliday, or John Ford, I\rquote d say, \'93Wow! I was, you know, really into that, and actually, it\rquote s quite good. And it\rquote 
s much better than nine-tenths of the Westerns I have looked at\'94. So I did value that. It may be, that may be a Leavisite hangover, a Leavis privilege, what he called \'93lived experience\'94
, and he brought lived experience into formal criticism as one of the criteria of value. And I thought, \'93Well, if you use \lquote lived experience\rquote , you divide this artistic world differently\'94. Differently. And it\rquote 
s perfectly open to you to say, \'93Carlyle is a bore. I don\rquote t care how important he is. He\rquote s a racist pig, actually. I can\rquote t stand another word. I won\rquote t read another word of Carlyle all the rest of my life, and I don\rquote 
t care how intellectually important he is. He\rquote s a bore\'94. And this is very unlettered, very unsophisticated, but gets hold of something concrete and gives you an experience, a lived experience, of what he\rquote s talking about. \'93That\rquote 
s a fine artist\'94. I don\rquote t know whether that\rquote s the greatest artist. I wasn\rquote t interested in saying, \'93Chandler is as great as Tolstoy\'94. That\rquote s a different matter. For me, that\rquote 
s more a matter of how deep the perception is. Yes? What the complexity is. Chandler and popular culture is much more
 stereotyped, or typed. Tolstoy opens up an extremely complex world of feeling and emotion and ideas, and forms of social life, so Tolstoy is a very very great artist, but these are different kind of perceptions. He doesn\rquote t have the \'93
Chandler moment\'94, and Chandler doesn\rquote t have the Tolstoyan perception or depth of understanding. So I was never unable to make discriminations, but there were discriminations between particular works \endash 
 not discriminations between the categories. You could ensure yourself value b
y printing in hard cover, and you could ensure yourself denigration by printing in paperback. Not so. That is a social judgement, not a literary or aesthetic one. And you can see where that leads in terms of, well, both the politics, but also cultural stu
dies. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
