\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, I published The Popular Arts, which Hoggart was 
interested in. And when I was at Oxford, in the era of the Socialist Club - have I talked about the Socialist Club? Which is really the sort of founding milieu of ULR. And one of the things that distinguished it was that it gave culture a much more signif
i
cant place in politics than was traditional. So we read The Uses of Literacy, absorbed The Uses of Literacy, and, you know, read it, discussed it. I edited the Labour Club magazine called Clarion. It was almost entirely a discussion of The Uses of Literac
y. Okay. So what was that about? Well, that\rquote s about a dimension I haven\rquote t talked about yet, namely, one of the interests in popular culture, was popular consciousness \endash 
 mass consciousness. What is the consciousness, not of the great intellectual figures and philosophers, what\rquote 
s the consciousness, the modes of understanding, of perfectly ordinary people? How do they understand the world? Do they have to be able to understand contradiction? No. They don\rquote t have a phrase for it, they don\rquote t know what the dialecti
c is, but they know things that are contradictory. They do know that. So how did that get there? And what studies it? What evidence can you find? You ask people about it, they don\rquote t know why you\rquote 
re going on about it. Well, can you read it indirectly in their letters and art? No doubt you could, but they didn\rquote 
t leave much letters. Well, could you read it in their conversations? Yes. And Hoggart tried to do that. He tried to do that. He listened to how their ordinary talk nevertheless involved the making of c
omplex moral judgements, which were never inspired by philosophical morality, philosophical theory over high blown morality, but were moral judgements. He had a sense of destiny or fate, well, fate struck from outside. And what was that? Well, that was a 
kind of way of acknowledging that you are not really in control of your life. Yes, in the end, circumstances will intrude and set a frame of opportunities for you. So we were interested in piecing out what mass consciousness was like, and we developed 
\endash  there\rquote s a bit on this in Popular Arts, but also many other things I\rquote ve written \endash 
 an indirect way of reading the things produced for popular culture, and the responses to them as kind of indirect evidence of popular consciousness. Yes? So if people responded t
o something, why did they respond to it? Well, the traditional argument Leavis had was because they\rquote ve been manipulated into it. The traditional Left argument was that they\rquote 
re being fooled. Well, yes and no. Yes, they are being manipulated, of course \endash  advertising is a hugely manipulative language and industry \endash 
 but the response is not completely accounted for by the response to manipulative impulse. Not completely. They bring a bit of their own experience. You listen to people talk about EastEnders, they\rquote r
e not just fooled by the narrative and the characters, and the drama and incidents of EastEnders, they like something about its ongoing character, what Hoggart used to call - if they\rquote 
re always going on, going on, and life consists of going on, going on, going on, trying to go on. And they\rquote re interested, and they bring - \'93Oh well, my family wasn\rquote t like that\'94
. So the response comes out in an indirect way in relation to these apparently corrupt sources. I wrote a piece called, \'93Deconstructing Popular Culture\'94, which is exactly about that. It opposes the folk culture tradition which says, \'93
This is the authentic views, attitudes, and emotions of the people, the common people\'94. It\rquote s not. Not that. Not pure. \'93Well, it\rquote s entirely manipulative\'94 \endash  no, it\rquote s not that ei
ther. It is some, yes, complicated formation in between these two things, therefore you have to develop an interpretative methodology for seeing what you can tell about consciousness from these indirect sources. Well, that\rquote 
s become one of the things that cultural studies does \endash 
 it treats popular cultural film, television programmes, and tries to read it as itself, the product of much deeper social causes, and with much more complicated and profound social effects than just the thing in itself. You look puzzled! }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
