\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 And we planned the programme and eventually opened the Centre. I remember discussions with Richard about, \'93
Well, what shall we call it?\'94 \'93What is this field?\'94 \'93Well, sort of cultural studies?\'94 Things like that! \'93Well, is it an Institute?\'94 I said, \'93It can\rquote t be an Institute because nothing is instituted there! People don\rquote 
t believe that the subject matters you\rquote re going to look at ought to be in universities at all, so it\rquote s not institutionalised. We don\rquote t have a programme, we don\rquote t have a methodology, we don\rquote t have a curriculum, we don
\rquote t have a tradition of ideas\'94. \'93No. Well, Centre?\'94 \'93Yes, that\rquote s better\'94. A sort of rallying point for this kind of work. \'93How should we do it?\'94 \'93Well, we\rquote 
ll try to get good graduate students who have grants, but who are interested in moving away from traditional literary and other topics\'94. \'93Could they come from history?\'94 \'93Yes, perhaps\'94
, because this is also the era of more interdisciplinary research, and, \'93Are you interested in culture?\'94 \'93Well, there\rquote s Raymond\rquote 
s huge discussion about what culture is about, and his critique of high culture as the only category of culture, and what is called the \lquote beginnings of the anthropological definition of culture\rquote \'94 \endash  culture as ways of life. So it
\rquote s a very important moment, intellectual moment. Hoggart, Williams, in my head, these two defined the terrain that I thought of as cultural studies, and that\rquote s why I went to Birmingham. There\rquote s one more thing that I\rquote ll
 say, which is the question of popular consciousness was, of course, massively political, because this is the beginning of the period of affluence, post-War capitalism is revived, and the question is, what Gaitskell put to the 1959 Labour Party Conference
, \'93Will Labour\rquote s working-class support survive the coming of the telly, the fridge, the small car?\'94
 In other words, will mass culture undermine, destroy, unravel the working-class culture which has remained, which is the milieu in which Left politics, the U
nions, etc., have been generated and sustains them and allows them to survive? And this was the big, big, big political question. The nature of mass culture, and the nature of contemporary affluence, as the solvents of older working-class culture, and per
haps the production of a kind of mass culture which wouldn\rquote t support those institutions at all. That\rquote s the debate with Crosland, and that\rquote s the debate with Gaitskell, \'93Will the culture survive?\'94
 I remember a huge debate with Mark Abrams about the Sun, \'93Is this really the new working-class? Is this the voice of the new working-class?\'94
 Not the Mirror or the Sketch, but the Sun: something new here which has never been quite seen in this form before \endash  a certain kind of demotic populism, certain kind of sensation
alism, etc. So the question of what was happening to working-class culture was a huge political issue. Hoggart, though he doesn\rquote 
t discuss this directly, knew perfectly well that the sketch that he offered of an older working-class culture in which he\rquote d bee
n born and brought up as a child, and what was happening now was a key contribution to this debate, though people were conducting the debate in political terms, and economic terms, but not in cultural terms. But actually, if there was no social milieu in 
which these ideas could take root and become institutionalised, they weren\rquote t going to survive. So that\rquote 
s what we fastened on in Oxford, why we took The Uses of Literacy as so important, because it was our discussion about how is capitalist society changing in the post-War period? \'93
What is the meaning of affluence? What is the meaning of the coming of television? What is the meaning of the coming of mass advertising to Britain? What\rquote s the meaning of the rise of an independent youth culture? What\rquote s the meaning
 of music? What\rquote s the meaning of Elvis Presley? What does it tell you about the mind-set of another generation, altogether different from Hoggart in his teens, in Hunslet in the thirties?\'94 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
