these students in, they got their topics, which of us was going to supervise them? Not many people came, but they were really from mixed backgrounds \endash  somebody from history, several people from literature, some people working on the local press 
\endash  a mixed bunch already, interdisciplinary bunch already. Okay. How do you forge a kind of field of work out of that? Well, you draw things together. Okay, Richard would give a seminar, a working seminar, on largely \'93
how to read the culture through text\'94. So what would he read? He would read, with them, Sons and Lovers, or he\rquote d read Orwell, or he\rquote d read Orwell\rquote s, Shooting an Elephant, and I would do bits of theory \endash  we didn\rquote 
t call it that, but that\rquote s really what it meant. Erm, you know, you get me into very deep water! Because what bits of theory? Well, sociology. \'93But you don\rquote t really know much sociology\'94. \'93But it\rquote 
s something to do with the social\'94. \'93Yes. Something to do with the relationship between culture and what is not culture\'94. \'93Well, Marxism has a particular vi
ew about the superstructural role of culture in relation to the economic. Is that what you think? Should they know about that theory? Should you critique that theory?\'94
 So it began with us reading The German Ideology and so on. Then my friend Lidia Curti came from Italy, active life, and activist in the Italian Communist Party which, as you know, is a very distinctive formation. And she said, \'93
Well, have you read Gramsci?\'94 \'93Well, I know Gramsci\rquote s name, but - \'94. I\rquote d seen a little collection of papers that Lawrence and Wishart put out called The Modern Prince. But I didn\rquote t really know what Gramsci was about. \'93
Well, you ought to read Gramsci. Gramsci\rquote s very interested in these issues. And behind him, Croce. So, \'93Well, let\rquote s read some Gramsci together\'94. They were kind of reading groups. They didn\rquote 
t know what culture studies was, I was making it up, and Richard was making it up! And the students were engaged in making it up! So I couldn\rquote t teach - well, there\rquote s no cultural studies to teach. We were making it up out 
of elements, bringing all the different elements together. So, \'93What will we read?\'94 Well, you start by reading a chapter from Uses of Literacy, you start by reading Raymond Williams\rquote 
 Long Revolution, a chapter on the definition of culture. That becomes the curriculum. But it couldn\rquote 
t be taught in a characteristically typical academic way, it had to be one which recognised the novelty, the lack of definition, the absence of a constituted body of knowledge and research, the confusion about which traditions you were drawing on. \'93
Well, we ought to read a bit of Leavis, then\'94. \'93Yes, a bit of Leavis\'94. So then we\rquote d have a discussion with them. We knew a bit more about them, I was seven, eight years older than them, and I\rquote 
d been nosing around this terrain for longer. But I couldn\rquote t teach them. They, and us, in the position of discussion leader and participants, made cultural studies up. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
