\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, I\rquote m trying to think of
 the echelon which first seemed, to me, to feel like a cultural studies generation. And what I would say was, that was partly the result of a change in the collective practice of the Centre. Because what we began to do was to institutionalise these discus
sion groups, so it\rquote s not only Hoggart\rquote 
s seminar and my seminar, but a series of working groups where, for instance, people on the media came together discuss media texts, whereas the historians came together to discuss the making of the English working-clas
s, and women came together to discuss Juliet Mitchell. So, yes, the Centre now looks like two main Centres and a series of working groups. Well, the working groups were intended to help people go deeply into the background of their research. Ph.D.s often 
begin with a review of the literature, a critical review of the literature. Well, I thought, \'93Am I going to have to read ten critical reviews of the mass culture debate, or mass communications research, and what\rquote s wrong with it? No. Let\rquote 
s get together and discuss it\'94
. And out of some of those groups individual projects began to emerge, so the group became involved in its own project, not in doing their Ph.Ds.. I mean, we sacrificed a lot of good people who got their Ph.D.s 20 years later, or 10 years later, 
because they became completely absorbed in Centre projects. And all the early books were constructed that way - as a result of group work, not of the formal pursuit of their theses. They related to them, so then you see a kind of collective practice sprea
ding through the Centre, through its intellectual work. Well, are these separate ones? No. We need to bring them together. So you need to have a general discussion group in which each report, \'93This is what we\rquote re talking about in the Media Group
\'94. \'93This is what we\rquote re talking about in the Literature Group\'94. \'93This is what we\rquote re talking about in the Freud Group\'94
. So to report to each other. So this is how what you might call a common cultural studies conversation came to be constructed. And by the time the third wave of students came, I thought, \'93Well, we can\rquote t pretend we\rquote 
ve never read Gramsci before, so somebody had better tell them about Gramsci, and make them read him\'94. So I began to teach my Theory Workshop, or seminar, became the first theory course, and Hog
gart continued to do his reading for tone, trying to read the social relationship behind the text. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
