s not a theoretical thing. And The Long Revolution and Raymond Williams\rquote  work, and to some extent, Edward\rquote 
s work, because Edward was a very cultural historian. Very, you know! No classical treatment of The Making of the English Working-Class would have given Methodism the role which he gives in The Making of
 the English Working-Class. So these are the three fathers, yes? Each different from the other. So all of that is then the founding of cultural studies: the debate about the cultural foundation of the politics, then the founding of cultural studies, and t
heorisation about culture, all of that had subsequently come to be defined as the \'93cultural turn\'94, and that\rquote 
s where you get, suddenly, cultural historians, and cultural geographers, all of that begins in the cultural turn. Well, then everything is struck as
under by the advent of European theory, by the arrival of Roland and Levi-Strauss and structuralism and so on, and that theory gives very central place not to culture but to language, and that is called the \'93linguistic turn\'94
. And cultural theory became implicated in the linguistic turn. I can say more about that if you want. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
