\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, the linguistic turn - I mean, why a language? They don\rquote 
t mean language in an empirical sense, they mean language as a system in which meaning is constituted and communicated. Yes? Of which language is a sort of paradigm instance. And this comes from the influence of the structural linguist Saussure \endash 
 French theory rediscovers Saussure \endash  which is about how meaning is constituted. And Levi-Strauss tries to apply that to the analysis of myths, and Barthes applies it to the analysis of Citroens (?? \endash 
 99.55) and Imperial photographs and so on, you know, and so all of this comes to bear on culture studies. So you need to know more about language. 
This is not language and power, which is what you asked about first, this is, first of all, language and difference, because the big thing at the heart of Saussure\rquote 
s theory is that meaning is constructed through difference, through the combination of similarity and difference. Do you want an example of that? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
