\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 The simplest example is the Latin verb \'93educare\'94, meaning \'93to draw out\'94
. Okay, that concept is at the centre of a whole list of words in English. Well, how do you distinguish between the person who does the drawing out and the persons from whom the drawing out is? You combine it with variable endings \endash 
 education, educating, educator, educated, to educate - meaning something very different. Okay. So how do these meanings arrive a
s much through difference as through similarity? So this is preoccupied with questions of the creative role of difference. This is major in my own thinking, because, of course, insofar as I was still, at that stage, very influenced by Marx, and in an argu
m
ent with Marx, I believed in the totality, and I believed in total explanations, [so I was wanting to be] adapting and reviving Marxism, so that it would explain the world, and the world in one framework. The dialectic covered everything. Well, suddenly I
 thought, \'93Well, it does, but only because of those moments when they\rquote re different through contradiction and opposition, not through just weaving similarities together\'94. So difference kind of enters the field of cultural studies \endash 
 for me. Meaning and difference. Meaning and difference. And, I would now say culture - well, you didn\rquote t ask me to define culture, and I can\rquote 
t. But one dimension is the constitution, of communication and meaning, and I am as influenced in that by Weber, as by anybody. I\rquote ll come back to that if you want. But after that, if you\rquote 
re interested in language, not just as a system, social system, but if you\rquote re interested in it as a part of social practice, well then you\rquote re interested in the questions of ideology, and, therefore, you\rquote re inter
ested in the power of language to persuade, to confuse, to convert, to describe the world in certain ways, to challenge the descriptions of the world in certain ways, so the connection between language and power is kind of written in to the Marxist langua
ge through which we read linguists \endash  if that makes any sense. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
