\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 It\rquote s not until you get to Foucault that questions of power and meaning become absolutely central. So it\rquote 
s a second wave of the impact of French theory on cultural debates, and the rise of something called \'93cultural theory\'94
 [in quotation marks], which we never thought we were doing. We thought, and I may probably still think, that cultural theory is a form of
 social theory - social theory in relation to a particular domain of practices and institutions, or, rather, as Weber says, \'93It is a dimension of every social practice, but it doesn\rquote t constitute its whole\'94
. So practices are not [all] cultural, which you\rquote d sometimes get the impression from \endash  when you read cultural theory these days \endash  makes culture autonomous. It\rquote s not. But there\rquote 
s always a cultural dimension to social practice. Social practice accomplishes something, changes the world, makes a new world, for
ges relationships, and running through that is always the dimension of signification. Or as Baudelaire later, in a very crude way, said, \'93Everything that exists is also a sign\'94. It\rquote 
s not only a sign, but it is always a sign. Every gesture you make carries 
a meaning. When I said Weber, the influence of Weber, in the Methodology of Social Sciences, Weber talks a quite different way from how he talks in much of the rest of his work, precisely about this \endash  \'93
How do I know what was the causes of the Punic Wars?\'94 \'93I\rquote ll see somebody chopping down a tree in the next yard, how do I know what\rquote s going on? Well, they\rquote 
re chopping down a tree, yes. Are they clearing the garden? Are they building a new design? Is it George Washington chopping down the cherry tree?\'94 How do y
ou know? Well, you interpret what meanings you can give to an action which you can fully observe. It\rquote 
s changing the world, the material world will lack the tree in two minutes time, but what does it mean? What is its meaning? Well, you might ask somebody, and I\rquote d say, \'93Oh, I don\rquote t know, I was hired to chop the tree down\'94
. What you do is, you mobilise existing frameworks of interpretation to apply to it. Well, it might be this. Or it might be that. Or it might be that, but that\rquote s less persuasive. [BELL RINGS: PAUSE] The problem of cutting down a tree. Ultimately it
\rquote s a matter of interpretation, it cannot be scientific. He might think he\rquote s doing that, but he may not know why he\rquote s really doing it. He may be subconsciously a vandal of nature, so you can come to 
what seems like a good interpretation, and he can corroborate it, and contextually you can see, \'93That\rquote s probably what it was. Somebody hired him to cut down this tree\'94. But ultimately it\rquote 
s a matter of interpretation. And what you do is, you mobilise codes of interpretation, many of which constitute the content of your culture. You say, in our culture, you don\rquote t say this, this is what is going on \endash 
 if I see that, I bring to bear on it stories I\rquote ve read about Washington, interpret it in frameworks, and that i
s one of the things that culture is. It consists of a repertoire of interpretative frameworks and their different ways of life and not only different ways of life, but we use different interpretative frameworks, and when we share, widely, a set of interpr
etative frameworks, we are members of the same culture. And when you see somebody who says, \'93Oh, it\rquote s nothing to do with that, and do you know that in Latin America, the natives cut cherry trees because it\rquote s the devil?\'94 \'93No, I didn
\rquote t that. It\rquote s not my interpretative framework\'94. But, they said, \'93Well, if I saw that, that\rquote s what I would think. We never hire someone actually, we don\rquote t hire people to do anything\'94
. Well, these are two ways of life. The actual practices are different. What they signify is different. And the way of interpreting what they signify, or getting meaning from it, is is interpreted too. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 And you used the word \'93codes\'94. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
