\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes. And that really comes from structural linguistics. Yes. The idea is, for instance, Saussure has his d
escription, this discussion, \'93If you see a light changing from red to green, or green to red, why do you stop? Does red mean stop?\'94 Well, only in our culture. In our culture. It doesn\rquote 
t necessarily, you might not expect a native American Indian to stop driving because he\rquote s seen a red light! He never heard of it. He doesn\rquote t share the code. Well, the code is a particular organisation \endash 
 red to green, to orange warning, back to red \endash  and once you know that, you can obey it, it signifies something, and you adapt your practice to it, you stop the car. Everybody else stops the car so we don\rquote 
t run into one another. So if you don\rquote t share the code, or if you want to breach the code, like Italian drivers, it won\rquote t work, we\rquote ll have accidents. But it\rquote s because we have shared codes. Well, that\rquote 
s not the only code in which red figures. Red figures also as a symbol of blood. Ah well, that\rquote s different. If you go to a Spanish culture, if you go to the bullfight, there\rquote s a close relationship between red, danger, and blood - but that
\rquote s not what the stop sign is talking to you about! So there are two different codes. So which ones are you using? You can\rquote t drive the street according to the bullfighting code, and you can\rquote 
t fight a bull according to the driving code, so we have to choose. I say \'93choose\'94, but that gives a very conscious account of it. Of course, we don\rquote t choose at all, we just unconsciously mobilise. \'93This seems - \'94
 or you press the button, or \'93Oh, Paul\rquote s making a cup of tea, Paul\rquote s making a cup of coffee or making something with hot water\'94. I know right away. But if I don\rquote t have a kettle, never heard of electricity, I wouldn\rquote 
t know what on earth you were doing. I wouldn\rquote t know what a switch was. So that\rquote s not how you get hot water. So we\rquote re absolutely full of interpret
ative codes, and for me, that is as much what culture is as Shakespeare. Indeed, the opposite way round. Shakespeare is a refinement, he offers us a particularly rich set of interpretative frameworks which enable us to gain huge complex insights into huma
n behaviour, but it\rquote s not a different thing from understanding what you\rquote re doing when I see you turning on the kettle. Exactly the same thing. Much of that culture is unconscious \endash  not unconscious in the Freudian sense, but it\rquote 
s unconscious in the sense it\rquote s outside of our awareness. If you had to think about it self-consciously, you couldn\rquote t get out of bed! You would be so wary, with thinking, \'93
What shall I do, are those shoes? What are shoes? Do I put them on?\'94 You\rquote d never move! So, of course, we inhabit them as instinctively what things are. That\rquote s what you use to think with \endash  these interpretative frameworks \endash 
 we mobilise them as codes, to de-code social practices, to find out what their meaning is, and then we can do things. Much of those meanings, then, sediment out of awareness. So I don\rquote t think, \'93
What does it mean to buy a ticket to get on the bus?\'94 \'93I\rquote m getting on a bus, so I\rquote d better have a ticket\'94. Sure. Ticket. Well, tickets, you know, imply buying something, which implies the existence of money, an
d implies shops. It implies commodification, but you don\rquote 
t know anything about any of those, just part of the ordinary interpretative framework we bring to bear on the world. And since every practice is signifying, every act of interpreting a social practi
ce is an act of mobilising an interpretative framework, sometimes very unconsciously. Literary criticism is a very rich and complicated interpretative framework, but everyday practices also involve interpretative frameworks of that kind. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
