\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes. Yes. Yes. These are two - \'93encoding\'94 and \'93decoding\'94 are two quite different moments. They\rquote 
re different moments. An event happens. There\rquote s a report on it in the media. You can\rquote t 
reproduce the event in the media, you can deal with pictures about it, so you can put it into visual language, therefore you need codes of producing the meaning, you have to say, \'93The Vietnam War means this\'94. Well, I\rquote 
m looking at it, unless I share exactly the same code of encoding, I\rquote ll get a different reading. I\rquote ll say, \'93Oh well, they think it\rquote s a good thing, but I don\rquote t, for these reasons\'94
. So codes are not necessarily aligned at all, so the moment of putting a thing into a narrative, and of getting the meaning of that narrative, and either accepting it or opposing it, are two different moments in the process of communication. }{
