\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, there are really two sources to that. One is a critique of th
e positivism and sort of false objectivity of mainstream sociology as I encountered it at the time of Merton and Parsons and so on, which I read into at this stage, and I thought what interested me were things which clearly were of a more interpretative k
i
nd. The only place I could find that in American sociology, which was all the rage in the forties and fifties, fifties and sixties, all that I could find of this was really in the interactionist tradition, coming down from the structural level of analysis
,
 to a more interpersonal level, as it were. So that was one. The second thing was that much of that work, together with something else which interested me, which was close ethnographic descriptive work, both of them were principally to be found in devianc
y studies, and the reason for that, I think \endash  but I may be completely wrong \endash 
 but I assumed, at the time, the reason for that was precisely because not only did mainstream sociology assume that everything fitted into a structure, and that that was the princ
ipal object of analysis, but they assumed the structures basically stable, a matter of consensus, and the question which concerned them was the maintenance of social order. Well, what about everything else? (LAUGHS) And you didn\rquote 
t seem to find that except in Chicago School \endash 
 gangs, the underworld, the urban sociology, European migrants, and crime, deviancy and so on. So inevitably I was pulled to the literatures in those two areas, of which Becker was an early. But then there\rquote s a whole tradition of deviancy
 work which I followed through, and which was really the background to the work that we did in the Centre for Cultural Studies, first of all youth studies, which is in Resistance to Rituals, and the work around that, and that was very influenced by intera
ctionism. Interactionism was also interested in meaning, whereas it seemed, to me, more posivistic approaches had bracketed out meaning, on the ground that you couldn\rquote t do anything with it \endash 
 it was a sort of black hole. So there was no point asking why did 
anybody become deviant, you just took it that there were deviant and non-deviant career paths, and that some people ended up that way, and they were abhorrent to the system, and the system roughly produced okay people, well-adjusted, and so on. I mean, th
i
s is very crude, but, nevertheless, it was the basis of a kind of reluctance - this is the moment when we decided cultural studies had to know something about society, therefore had to have a way of analysing social interaction, social relations, social s
tructures and so on. So looking for that in the literature, I was put off by what seemed to be the mainstream kind of positivistic empirical work, and went to, itself, a deviant tradition within American sociology. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 And what about labelling theory? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Well, that, of course, I regard that as a development, in that interactionism, deviancy theory, the awareness of deviance of the controlled culture, its response to deviance is, itself, a part of deviancy, and therefore labelling, the action of th
e controlled culture in labelling things one way or another, this is what I meant, this is a question of a structure attributing social meaning to the actions of different people; and that having real effects and real consequences in terms of how the laws
 
apply, whether they were put in jail, whether they were sent to reform school where they were well-adjusted to society or not. So the whole baggage really from labelling theory. And the shift to labelling theory is really a move which happens in criminolo
gy at this stage. What is called \'93critical criminology\'94 arises out of that interest \endash  you can see it somebody like Stan Cohen, who is interested in deviant youth behaviour, but he\rquote 
s also interested in how the press label it, and how the State reacts to it, how the politicians interpret it. So the whole thing becomes deviance, not just the people who don\rquote 
t do the right thing, but the social context and the relationships in which that is produced, experienced, and dealt with. The whole thing becomes deviance. So you can see why, when we come to youth culture, we\rquote 
re as interested in, as Stan was, how does society see and react to this behaviour, as well as, \'93Why do some young people do it?\'94 It wasn\rquote t, \'93They\rquote re the problem, why do they do it?\'94 but \'93They\rquote re a prob
lem because the society defines some forms of response as acceptable.\'94
 Because that leads to consensus, maintains the social order, broadly speaking. And it is concerned about other kinds of behaviour which appear to challenge, fall outside of, not be normatively guided by any of those things. We\rquote 
re interested in deviance because it\rquote s a broader category than crime. Yes? So we weren\rquote t just interested in people who broke the law, but what you find in youth culture \endash  because people may or may not be breaking t
he law about drugs or whatever it might be \endash  but the essential thing is they don\rquote t really subscribe to the normative rules. They don\rquote 
t believe in the system, in that way. Their aim is not to adapt to the system, but to either change it or find a pathway, another deviant pathway, through it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
