re absolutely critical for us. Policing the Crisis is a study of how a variety of moral panics, in different areas of social life, begin to come together in a particular period, begin to overlap, and relate to one another, and as they say, \'93conjoin\'94
, which is the meaning of \'93conjunction\'94 \endash  the drawing together of these apparently different strands and contradictions and crises into a more general social crisis, which is what happened in the seventies. And that, in turn, led us to ask, 
\'93Well, why does it happen? Why is this happening?\'94 If I can just illustrate what I mean, by the time of the height of the crisis, Conservative politicians are mapping together everything in sight \endash 
 the fact that student are revolting in Cambridge, the Garden [Hotel], and then industrial militancy, and then student protest, everything is part of everything, you know? It\rquote s sort of general, society is 
going off the rails. Eventually, Heath says, \'93It\rquote s ungovernable. Ungovernable\'94. He doesn\rquote t just mean in the political or economic domain, he means general: you don\rquote 
t know where it starts. You pick up crime, and before long you find that you\rquote re led back into this crisis, and that\rquote 
s the definition of the conjunction, which is what Policing the Crisis is ultimately about. So that was the use and development of a concept of moral panic. We thought there was a moral panic about street crime, and there was a mora
l panic about street crime not because, statistically, it could be shown that street crime had grown in that period \endash  because it wasn\rquote t really the case. What\rquote 
s more, there was no such thing as street crime, as a crime, so where did they get the statistics 
from? Well, they had to put together, a bit of property crime, and a bit of theft, and a bit of stuff going on in the street, etc., to generate a figure. So you couldn\rquote t explain it. It wasn\rquote 
t that the police opened their eyes and when they had to prepare the annual statistics, saw, \'93Well, there\rquote s a bit of a rise in street crime, isn\rquote t there?\'94 It wasn\rquote 
t about that at all. It was about a much larger fear, which had to do with other people in the society, with the fact that it was changing too fast, with the f
act that affluence was deconstructing it, undermining its moral authority and patterns. It had to do with black kids, why there are so many of those people, and, therefore, with race. Do you understand me? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
