t just a factual observation about society which alerted people to it, they were already in a tizzy about a number of different things, and began to construct those different fears and anxieties \endash  or moral panics \endash  into one ge
neral moral panic in which you could find your way into that moral panic wherever you started. It didn\rquote 
t matter, everything led into it. Society was coming apart at the seams. Not just more crime on the street, or more housing problems, but crime on the st
reet and housing problems, and the inner cities, and violence, and property crime, and theft, and so on and so on, getting larger and larger and larger, less accurate in relation to any particular set of sociological observations, and more a kind of gener
a
l ethos of fear. So what precipitated the fear? Well, partly we thought, one of the things that precipitated it was what had happened before, namely in the sixties the undermining of all this by affluence, the sense that the post-War world would never go 
b
ack to being the same and so on. So we began to look at those aspects of the seventies, which provided us with an explanatory frame for why mugging, or forms of moral panic around problems like that, were folded together into a much larger crisis. The mid
-seventies was a general social crisis. It had been gathering for a long period of time, but it really comes to a head. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
