Well, Phil, of course, gave the work on deviance and the work on moral panics and so on, and on youth culture, a class dimension. Well, the [class dimension] is there, of course, in Stan and in Jock Young, but not explicitly, whereas the work that Phil wa
s
 doing, particularly where he came from, as you know from the East End. But himself a sort of deviant, (LAUGHS) politically active on all kinds of fronts, etc., understanding the kind of communities out of which this kind of behaviour was coming. Which we
 did in Resistance to Rituals, which is one of the problems of the Centre, Resistance to Rituals, is how this kind of cultural disaffiliation relates to older questions of class inequality, so that youth culture doesn\rquote 
t just float like that, and it doesn\rquote t relate to different social classes in exactly the same way. It\rquote 
s not necessarily simply a product of class conflict, but it is related to questions of class inequality, class behaviour, class-based behaviour, class-based attitudes and so on, and, therefore
, its incidence across the society will, to some extent, depend upon something which it doesn\rquote t talk about. It says, \'93Youth culture\rquote s exploding\'94. \'93Yes, but it\rquote 
s exploding among Teddy Boys, and among Mods and Rockers, and these are different fractions of the working-class \endash  one very old, very traditional in their cultural attitudes, the others on Italian motorbikes and belonging to the affluent world\'94
. Do you see what I\rquote m saying? That there\rquote s these larger conflicts underpinning the actual appearance of two strands of deviant behaviour. And many people were saying, \'93Well, is this just a sort of froth? It\rquote s just the culture\'94
. But that\rquote s because, of course, if it was purely cultural or mainly cultural, then it was, of course, unimportant (LAUGHS) \endash  because of the general role of culture and meaning in sociological analysis, which said, \'93If you\rquote 
re looking at social class, that\rquote s a serious business. You\rquote re looking at social structure, serious business. If you\rquote re looking at economic inequality, serious business, but if you\rquote 
re looking at differences between the traditional and the affluently-oriented youth of the period, well it must be of secondary importance, because culture is not one of the principal structures\'94. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
