\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 I don\rquote 
t think John Rex was theoretically important to us. I mean - what am I saying! Not in terms of the line of questions that you\rquote re asking now. Which is rea
lly to talk about the development of a distinctive theoretical landscape within cultural studies \endash  that\rquote s really what we\rquote re talking about now \endash 
 because these are the central core issues in cultural studies, which we can go back if you want to. Well, John R
ex was not interested in that, though, as a Weberian, he was more interested in interpretative meaning than other kinds of sociologists, because, as you know, in the methodology of social sciences, Weber offers you to roots to cause, one is interpretative
 \endash  historical, putting together as plausible a story as you can, etc. \endash  and the other is specifically causal \endash  \'93What caused the Punic Wars?\'94 \'93Well, that, that, that\'94 - or it\rquote 
s not a cause. A harder and softer definition of what a social cause is about. So as a Weberian, he was more interested in how groups developed themselves, he was never an interactionist, but Weber swung him in that direction. But that\rquote 
s not what we learnt from John. We learnt, from John, about race. It\rquote s more closer to the empirical obs
ervation of how these theories and theoretical issues were playing out in a place like Birmingham, which, of course, he did all his research on, and he knew very clearly, so we could learn a lot from that kind of work. But it wasn\rquote 
t conceptually significan
t to us, I would say. I mentioned Weber, yes? Remember that, at this stage, in cultural studies, we are aware of the fact that culture studies differs from other conceptions of culture insofar as it regards it as part of social practice. Every social prac
tice is also cultural. So it needed a social theory. You couldn\rquote t just muck around, and fill in the historical social background in a couple of opening paragraphs and leave it at that. You really had to - well, \'93Where did you find that out?\'94 
\'93Well, in sociology\'94. So you went to sociology and started to read it. That\rquote s when I started to read sociology for the first time, and that\rquote 
s when interactionism - we read Parsons The Social System, and we read Merton, which was interesting because he related crime to th
e social structures, and deviant pathways. But we also read the masters, Weber and Durkheim, very extensively, and we decided about both of them that some parts of what they were writing were very germane to what we were thinking about, and some parts wer
e not. I mean, the Durkheim of the period of Ann\'e9e Sociologique or the stuff on Death on the Right Hand and that whole school, Elementary Forms of the Religious Life. All of that is a very different thing from Suicide, which says, \'93You can\rquote 
t tell anything about why people commit suicide. You just tell what the incidence is, and you can work from that\'94
. And similarly, in Weber, there are these two sort of pathways - a more strongly rationally causalist pathway, and the more historical interpretative one. We a
lso what is far beyond that. We first read European social thought, we went back to Simmel and all those people who were less interested in sociological analysis as it had become empirically defined in the US context, and ranged wider between philosophica
l speculation and so on. So we are drawing on a very wide sweep of sociological thinking, while not being sociologists, not trained in sociology, and not following a strict sociological method of enquiry, or a strict sociological explanatory system. }{
