\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 No, encoding and decoding is a sort of 
side-step. Encoding and decoding arises in relation to the work on the media I was doing. Now at that stage, both my work and the Centre\rquote 
s was thought to be in media studies. We were not interested in media studies, we were interested in the media as forms
 of cultural production of meanings, as ideological influences in the society. We were not interested in a theory of media studies, as such. Indeed, we were very critical, precisely, of non-interpretative nature, of mass communications \endash 
 as it had become, a sociological sub-field within American sociology. And \'93Encoding and Decoding\'94 is written in critique of that model. There were two Centres. Remember, there was our Centre, and there was Halloran\rquote 
s much bigger Centre at Leicester, yes? And \'93Encoding and Decoding\'94 is given at an international conference which Leicester set up, and in which I gave a paper which was critical of that position. Okay? And I said \endash 
 like I said about before, about everything \endash  \'93It does not deal with meaning, and if you don\rquote t deal with meanings, you cannot take cultural questions seriously, because that is what culture is\'94
. So if you put it in a black box, fine, but there are some things you will never explain about it. Never. So \'93Encoding and Decoding\'94 arises in that context. Well,
 you know, there was what was called, in mass communication theory and practice and empirical work, very crudely, the \'93hypodermic model\'94 \endash 
 the media told you about deviancy, you saw what the media did, you went out and knocked old ladies on the head in the road! Yes? A straight causal line chain between input and output. What \'93Encoding and Decoding\'94 said is, \'93
The line is not like that, because deviancy, or crime in the street, is a social fact. My story as a reporter, about crime in the street, is a narrative. I can\rquote t produce the facts. I can\rquote t produce the thing in itself, I\rquote 
ve written a story about it\'94. Well, the fact that there is a story has, itself, imposed a sort of new structure of it. The stories have beginnings, middles and ends. The events may not h
ave a beginning, a middle and an end, but by the time you tell it, you\rquote ll find it began there, it developed in this way, and we can see it concluding in this way. So you\rquote ve entered the sphere of language, so you can\rquote 
t talk about the influence of the media without saying, \'93The influence is through language\'94. Well, does that happen because somebody, or some system, some institution, puts it into meaning \endash 
 encodes it. Puts it into linguistic narrative discursive form. Okay? That\rquote s what the programme consists of. That\rquote s what they are. That\rquote s all you see when you look at EastEnders, you don\rquote 
t see the East End, you see a narrative about it. A discourse about it. It\rquote s recognisable, drawn from real life, but, nevertheless, it isn\rquote t the thing in itself, so it can\rquote t h
ave a hypodermic effect of the simple kind. It can only have a hypodermic effect if it\rquote s put ideas into your mind, or it gives you a model of social behaviour you want to follow. It\rquote 
s a different thing from putting the needle in, it does that to your body, and you do that \endash  do you understand what I\rquote m saying? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 

\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 So we looked at the two moments of this \endash  \'93encoding\'94
, when journalists, the professions who report on the world, anybody who reports on the world, has to use language in order to do so. That\rquote 
s one moment. Well, what happens at the other of this hypodermic causal chain, so to speak? How is it getting to the people who behave in a certain way? Well, but they are not necessarily encoding the events in the world in the same way as the 
journalists do. First of all, they couldn\rquote 
t understand what the journalist is talking about, unless they shared, to some extent, the same codes. They also know what crime narratives are about. They also know what beginnings and ends and middles. They must share the code. There\rquote 
s no communication if you don\rquote t know language, you won\rquote t know what they saying, in the simplest way. But when you say, \'93share their linguistic code\'94, we don\rquote 
t just mean the capacity to understand in the literal sense, we mean the connotative structure. This is where Barthes comes in. \'93
Why is an advertisement about a sweater showing you a boy and girl holding hands, walking in the autumn mist, through a wood? Yes? Only because you see that that\rquote s what it is, but also this connotes a cer
tain kind of melancholy, a romantic ethos, tells a little story. And you see that the sweater is substituted in the story, because it is what attracts him to her. Do you understand what I\rquote 
m saying? So when you talk about the codes, the codes are not just l
iteral language, they are structures of meaning. Yes? Including denotative, which is literal, and connotative - more broadly defined, etc.. Okay. So most people who share the same culture, what it means to share the same culture is, in part, to share thos
e meaning codes. But the meaning, then, that you take from it, at the other end of the chain is not necessarily the way in which it was inserted, as you know. We don\rquote t all respond to EastEnders, in the same way. Some people say, \'93Oh, that
\rquote s just like real life.\'94. Some people say, \'93Well, it\rquote s not really like real life down here in the East End\'94, you know. And other people say, \'93I don\rquote t believe it\rquote s anything like it\'94. So there are three \'93
decoding\'94 basic ideal typical decoding positions which are not the same as the people who are saying, \'93This is what it means\'94
. So encoding and decoding are two different moments in the circuit of communication, which have to be aligned for any meaning to pass, and which almost certainly are not perfectly aligned. So what we said to the hypodermic model is, \'93
There is no input of a simple kind. There is no effect on the people who receive it, of a simple kind. And there is no single result or conclusion. There are two moments in the circuit \endash  the encoding moment, and the decoding moment.\'94
 Basically the encoding moment takes place in the institutions of the media and meaning-making in the society, and the decoding takes place in the audience. Unless you connect these two things together, not just audience studies or content analysis
, but content meaning and audience in a chain, you don\rquote t get an understanding of what the communication process is about. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 So let\rquote s think of looking at a programme then. How are you going to do it? Is t
his a form rather like literary analysis, that you look at the programme, and then you think, \'93Well, maybe that\rquote s emotive, which has this meaning\'94? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
