\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, in part it is, yes. In part it\rquote s literary, because what is the programme? It is language? It\rquote s metaphors. It
\rquote s images. So it\rquote s not just that you bring a literary analysis to it, you have to analyse forms, separate forms, because that\rquote s the form in which the message \endash 
 the thing - becomes a message. The message takes form. The audience responds to the form, takes a meaning, and may or may not behave in the world in a similar way. That\rquote 
s the chain. So that intervening period between encoding and decoding, you need literary or linguistic, or formal or visual analysis, forms of analysis. \'93What is being
 said? How is it being said? What sort of effect might that have? How are the real facts being reinterpreted by implying that kind of narrative to it?\'94 But the question of the audience, whether the audience may or may not understand that, so after you
\rquote ve conducted that analysis, you have to turn to the audience and ask yourself, \'93How are they responding to these forms?\'94 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 And how do you get that, then? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
