\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Well, in part you look at the broader social response to it, in part you look at what people say, and in part, we ought to have done more of long interviews with audiences. We didn\rquote t do that, and that\rquote 
s the weakness of the model. But before we get onto the weakness, let me remind you that about things like that, people often don\rquote t know, so you have to reinterpret even what they tell you, Yes? Because you can say, \'93
Well, what do you think about that news story about street crime?\'94 They\rquote ll tell you about mugging, \'93Well, down our road \'85\'94 - that\rquote s not what you\rquote re asking them. But if you say, \'93
Well, this is because you share the same way of encoding crime on television as the people who presented it\'94, they\rquote d say, \'93No. What do you mean?\'94 \'93Well, don\rquote t you share the same codes?\'94 \'93Well, show me\'94. Well, you\rquote 
d have to get a piece of their writing and show them that in spite of - because the processes we are talking about are unconscious \endash  not in the Freudian sense but in the broader sense. It\rquote s like how do you know that you\rquote 
ve produced a good sound grammatical English sentence? You don\rquote t know. You can\rquote t account for it. Most people who speak don\rquote t know any grammar at all, would have no way of describing it, but they do. If you say, \'93That\rquote 
s not what people usually say. That\rquote s not how English people put it\'94, they know, at once, what you\rquote re talking about. So, though I acknowledge that we ought to have done more \endash 
 individual interviewing ; social structured interviews with groups; and we came on to do that at a later stage \endash  Dave Morley\rquote 
s work on audiences in relation to industrial disputes is very much located, and in Nationwide and so on, is very much located in discussions with individual groups. But the basic methodology in cultural studies did not include that, partly beca
use everybody said, \'93But you\rquote re not proper sociologists, do you know about structured interviews? Could you produce a structured interview of an appropriate kind?\'94 \'93
Do you know about the weight of one cause or another, and how to investigate the level of significance of what is being said? Do you know anything about that?\'94 We were told we didn\rquote 
t, by the Sociology Department in Birmingham. When cultural studies first opened, it said, \'93Well, don\rquote t know what you are, but don\rquote t imagine that you\rquote re proper sociologists. Stay off our patch\'94
. So we were quite reluctant to become interviewers and so on. And also we were a bit doubtful that the interviews would yield the truth, because we thought the interviews have to be interpreted as much as the content has to be interpreted. So it\rquote 
s not that I refused that moment, but that there were problems about that moment which did not strike us as being obvious to the people who criticised us on those grounds. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
