\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, remember, Paul, that there was no pattern, there\rquote s not a model to follow. We were not a discipline, we were lodged insi
de English, because Hoggart, who had dabbled in this area himself in The Uses of Literacy, really opened this up, had begun to apply literary analysis to the mass media. So he\rquote 
d opened the door, and we were following in - but there was not an established curriculum. It\rquote 
s hard for people who have been trained in a field, you know, to understand what that means. What do you read? Well, you read a bit of Leavis because he tells you about literary analysis. You read a bit of Saussure, because he tells you about
 language. You read a bit about sociology because it tells you about deviance. So, is there a core, theoretical core? There was none. You made it up. Started The Use of Literacy. Went on to a bit of Raymond. Went on to a bit of Edward because he\rquote 
s the most cultural of the historians. Do you understand me? We made it up. So the structure, the whole structure, was made up! And when Hoggart and I said, \'93Well, here are students coming\'94, well, first of all, they weren\rquote 
t coming from our discipline. There were historians, there were linguists, there were literary people who applied to the Centre from the very beginning, so you couldn\rquote 
t rely on there being a disciplinary background. In any case, they were entering this new field when many of them had never read The 
Uses of Literacy. So you had to establish some structure which enabled these people to come into a single field of conversation and debate, and to then decide on what subject they wanted to study in greater depth, and then to discuss, or develop, a method
ology appropriate to that, and to conduct the research and write their theses \endash  that\rquote s the end point \endash  but to get there was not an easily prescribed route. What\rquote 
s more, remember, this is the period when so-called graduate studies is relatively undeveloped i
n Britain. In literature, nobody taught anybody to do literary analysis, except you were going to be a literary scholar, or a literary historian. All the people who taught me at Oxford never had a Ph.D., Oxford MA, what more would you need? So there were 
no post-graduate committees where you had to submit what your theme [would be], you had to get an okay from the Faculty, but it was much much less structured. So we were much freer to institute what we liked. We said, \'93Well, don\rquote 
t you bother with what we\rquote re doing upstairs with our students, in the end, we will produce a thesis of 40 \endash  50,000 words, in the traditional form. You can send it to two independent people, if they think it\rquote 
s worthwhile to pass. So we will produce what you want in its final form, but we are not responsible to you for how it is produced or developed in the student body, since it is not a discipline. It\rquote s not an established disciplinary field\'94
. So as a rough approximation, Hoggart and I, we\rquote re the only two people \endash  I\rquote m his Research Fellow \endash 
 we decided to split the groups. In addition to individual supervision, everybody had to come together in a group with Richard, which met on a Tuesday morning or something like that, to do bits of cultural analysis of literary texts \endash 
 the opening of Sons and Lovers, Orwell\rquote s essays - what can you find out about the society that this work is produced in, by reading, that\rquote s one. Then, \'93Well, there must be some wider theoretical framework\'94
 - and I was responsible for that. So that\rquote s where we read The Uses 
of Literacy. Raymond began to put together elements of a general theory course, which subsequently did become the theory course. It subsequently then became the basis of an MA in Cultural Studies. So it was woven together out of these different bits. It w
as genuinely an interdisciplinary field. But we were also reading Weber\rquote 
s Protestant Ethic. We were also reading Suicide. We were reading the critique of Suicide, because Durkheim did not attend the questions of historical meaning. So, we selected things wh
ich seemed germane to us, and the students had to read it. Well, I was in charge of - it wasn\rquote t called the \'93theory seminar\'94
, but a second broader theoretically oriented seminar, reading. Then we decided we also needed a framework within which the students 
could discuss their own research topics, so it seemed best to do that in roughly grouped areas of study. So some people working on the media, well, they should be in the Media Group. Then they would read the mass communications literature, they\rquote 
d know the debates about that, they\rquote 
d know the empirical work done in that, etc.. Some people are interested in the popular press, they could go to that media seminar. But somebody else who was interested in crime, deviance and youth culture, well, what were they doi
ng in the Media Group? So we had another group which was responsible for grouping together people who were interested in deviancy. Then the groups proliferated! As people brought new subjects which they wanted to research, so we tried to either put them i
n
to groups where they were reading roughly the same literature and discussing it, or set up another centre. Because some people were interested in literature, there was always a Literary Group. Later on that became interested in language, as that linguisti
c shift took place, it became a Literature/Language Group. There was one in history, because Edward was another influence. But what was social history? Well, you don\rquote 
t go into the Media Group to discuss social history, you go into history where you read The
 Making of the English Working-Class, and you read the early stages of British social history, and what is distinct between social history and economic history, and what are the influences on that, and so on. So each became a focus of independent reading,
 but related. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
