\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes, well, before that, let me say something about the Group you\rquote re asking about, because they not only started
 to publish things, but they started to do some work of their own together. So, for instance, the Media Group \endash  it\rquote s not just the Media Group \endash 
 a section of people in the Centre started to work on popular magazines, and they worked on analysing an issue of Woman magazine, in which there was a story, and the story was called, \'93Cure for Marriage\'94. \'93Cure for Marriage\'94
 was about a woman, locked into the domestic role, always in the kitchen, etc., not really part of her husband\rquote s wider social life, who develops 
a fantasy relationship with Cary Grant, and has a dream about him. And this dream, of course, as you can imagine, in a woman\rquote s magazine story, reconciles herself to her marriage, so everything\rquote 
s all right in the end. But we did an analysis of this. Well, what was it? It wasn\rquote t anybody\rquote s thesis. The Centre had no publications of its own. It consisted of papers that every member of the Group contributed. You can\rquote 
t publish that in a journal, you can only publish it for other people in the Centre and slightly wider than that, by using the Roneo machine! So everybody used the Roneo machine, and produced what were called \'93working papers\'94
, and these working papers were the results of individual and collective research in the fields where the groups were working. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
