\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes, but Education produced a book. Which Richard Johnson had a lot to do with.
 There were lots of people involved in education. Lots of people. A really major area of our work, including Paul Willis. And there was another book which is about Feminism \endash  Women Take Control - yes? I can\rquote 
t remember what its title is. That was produced in the same way. So there are lots of books. There\rquote s a book called Culture, Media and Ideology, which was the Media Group\rquote s work. So I\rquote 
ll say something about those two Groups, partly because they\rquote re some of the ones that I was most involved in, but you mustn\rquote 
t read that as the T Centre Group, because there was no T Centre group like that. At different times these different groupings took the lead in the weight of general discussion. The grouping that produced Resistance to Rituals, was mainly people who star
ted out who wanted to investigate youth culture. Youth culture led to deviancy, led to deviancy theory, led to infringements of the law and the norms, led to criminology, so it was in that kind of area, and eventually some theses began to be written in th
at area, and a lot of work began to be produced, and eventually that became the basis of an independent book, which was then no individual\rquote s book. It wasn\rquote t the Centre\rquote 
s whole book, it was the book work of this particular Group, and they included people like John Clarke - no, I\rquote m sorry, John Clarke, Charles Critcher, were working in another field \endash 
 working-class culture, they were interested in football. Yes? Working-class sport and entertainment. But the Resistance to Rituals Group included Tony Jefferson, 
and lots of people who are in Resistance to Rituals who were not members of that Group, and John Clarke would be one of those. ... Angela McRobbie, on the question of girls culture [which] began to be posed, as you can imagine, at that time. So a whole ra
nge of people involved in Resistance to Rituals. Out of that, given the evolution of that Group, as I\rquote ve described it, came the Group that was concerned with crime \endash 
 deviancy in the context of crime as a social problem, rather than as a fraction of the social norms, and that led to Policing the Crisis. That is the basis of the Policing the Crisis Group. We recruited from other areas. So there\rquote 
s Chas Critcher, who was mainly, as I say, doing work in class culture. There was John Clarke who was doing stuff on 
football, there was Tony Jefferson who was interested in youth culture. Of the four authors, there is Brian Roberts, who is not in the Centre at all, was in Sociology, doing a thesis on Chicago ethnography, but who came to all our Group meetings, took par
t in our discussions, and was interested in developing that ethnographic side of Policing the Crisis. So it was, itself, a heterodox Group. It\rquote 
s a question which is sometimes asked, as to whether Policing the Crisis was a cultural studies book or not. In th
e formal sense it was not, because after a while we put together these various papers, and got an agreement with Hutchinson to publish a cultural studies series. But Policing the Crisis is not one of those. We went, as a group, independently, to Macmillan
s, and they published it. So this is not part of a tight institutional structure. I can\rquote t describe to you, how ad hoc it was. Ad hoc. \'93You need a group? Set it up\'94. \'93Who will run it?\'94 \'93Well, I don\rquote 
t know anything about it. Do you?\'94 \'93Yes\'94. \'93Okay, well, not much!\'94 \'93Okay, well, you start to read, and you take charge of the conversations\'94. Because you can\rquote 
t teach them. None of us could teach anybody else in the sense of deviancy sociology. We were busily reading Becker for the first time, ourselves. But we were 
more experienced, a bit older, etc., we could lead this thing, but everybody was going to bring us a paper. So Policing the Crisis does not arise as one of those Groups, but as a kind of more mixed group of people interested in this. The reason why it tak
es that form is because the impetus comes from outside \endash 
 not from within the Centre at all. It comes from the fact that a lot of Centre people were involved in anti-racist youth groups and community groups in Birmingham. Charles Critcher ran, lived in, and 
was very active on the ground with young people and with social problems and with racial discrimination in the Handsworth area, and came to us one day and said, \'93Do you know what\rquote 
s happened? Three boys, all of them from different cultural backgrounds, were
 involved in a small-scale property crime. They saw a man, a drunk man coming out of a pub, and attacked him. They wanted money. They got a very small amount of money, and they beat him up a bit\'94
. So they were coming to court. They were coming to court at the moment when what I described earlier as the moral panic, was ratcheting itself up, and this got called \'93The first mugging\'94, or \'93one of the early muggings\'94
. Okay, well, then it entered a different empire altogether, and the boys went to court, were given 20 years each. Twenty years! Well, what is that? That\rquote 
s not just a societal reaction to crime, that is a moral panic. That is people feeding into the legal process, their fears, anxieties, nameless folk devils, their feelings about race, their feelings a
bout poverty, their feelings about people intruding into our neighbourhood, all of those things were what produced, in the law, a kind of response which said, \'93This mustn\rquote t go on. We must stop this in its tracks\'94. So that\rquote 
s where it came from. We said, \'93Well, we should look into it\'94. So we started doing some ad hoc research \endash  into the boys, into the event, and then into the law. What did the judge say? Why did he give them 20 years? \'93But he said this\'94. 
\'93Well, how was it reported in the press?\'94 In other word
s, how was this single event constructed, through social meaning, into a much larger phenomenon? How did it connect with the anxieties of the society, underlying anxieties of the society? So that\rquote 
s, first of all, we were all also attending in that Group, and the Resistance to Rituals Group, the Deviancy Symposium \endash  Stan Cohen, Jock Young, Laurie Taylor. Yes, all that Group had set up an interdisciplinary group, organisation, called \'93
The National Deviancy Symposium\'94. We used to go to these meetings, and so w
e started to present papers on the work we were doing in Handsworth to this Group, and so on, so it gradually congealed into a more substantial research project, which is what it eventually became. We were all teaching. They were working on their individu
al theses, they were probably in a Group, and they were doing the research book, Policing the Crisis. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
