ham is transfixed by the emergence of immigration, the impact of immigration, so not all of them were directly working, had a student house which was involved in that stuff. But everybody was aware of it, we were going on anti-racist marches, it was a liv
e
 political theme in the Centre. Not many of us would have been close to a particular community like he was. Well, he brought us the news, but only because people were receptive to this, they were watching all the events going on in Birmingham, from the ti
me of the Enoch Powell \'93Rivers of blood\'94
 speech onwards. At places, there were anti-racist demonstration every week. The place is alert with questions, for the first time, about race and class, and race and equality, and city deprivation, and in deprivation
 the relationship of crime to those questions. So there\rquote s a fertile ground, receptive ground, for somebody who says, \'93I\rquote ve got an example of what you\rquote re talking about. Yes, it\rquote s just happened in Handsworth\'94. }{
