I would have said respectable working-class backgrounds or lower middle-class backgrounds. Yes. Remember, young people, at that time, in England, were rather complicated to trace what you would call th
eir class background. They had all been to university, so they weren\rquote 
t lumpen working-class. They were the children of under-educated parents, but they were probably the children of ambitious parents, and some of them might have been working-class, some of
 them might have been lower middle-class, and they therefore took advantage of the Welfare State, went to good schools, then went to university. They were like Hoggart - on transition between one class position and another - so they knew enough about popu
lar life in an area like that, tried to make sense of it, but they weren\rquote t necessarily entirely formed by and within traditional English working-class culture. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
