\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
I just said that we borrowed, very eclectically, from all over the place, not respecting the paradigms within which those particular concepts were lodged. Yes? Weber had a particular methodology, we may not have subscribed to 
the whole methodology, but certain ideas in Weber were tremendously important to us. Marx had a lot of ideas to show the connection between cultural questions, social questions, and economic questions - we resisted forms of economic determinist explanatio
n \endash  but we borrowed a hell of a lot of Marx. I mean, I didn\rquote 
t say, in relation to encoding/decoding, that the model is drawn from Marx. The model is drawn from the Grundrisse, not from Kapital, but from the methodology of the Grundrisse. In which, just to b
e brief, Marx says, you have to start with what he called the \'93chaotic obstruction\'94, but you have to add more and more levels of determination in order to produce the concrete in thought \endash 
 that is the method of encoding/decoding. It adds determination to a very loose model, makes it more precise, more historically specific, yes? Doesn\rquote 
t just say that the background to these events, this is the strand by which this influences that, which influences that, which influences that, so when you say, \'93This is a cause\'94, well, it\rquote s not a cause in the strict sense, but it\rquote 
s more than just a kind of guess, loose, back-sketching in. The best way of describing it is as Foucault calls it, \'93concepts are tools to think with\'94. We treated them as tools to think with, sometimes in a rather loose and cavalier way \endash  that
\rquote s quite true. But if they were of service to us in analysing a particular set of events, phenomenon, social phenomenon, development, we used it. We would defend it, we would go back and try and read to understand 
out of what matrix of problems it came, but we didn\rquote t agree with, say, Althusser, which is you can only understand the concept because it\rquote 
s within a particular conceptual framework. We thought people actually break across their conceptual frameworks all the time. What\rquote 
s more, they change them, so, you know, what is this thing about consistency? Consistency of paradigm throughout your work. You know, is Weber consistent across the whole of his work? Is Marx consistent? Huge Hegelian period which is thrown up
 for political economy, what\rquote s consistent about that? I don\rquote t undermine it, I\rquote m not trying to say it\rquote 
s not important, you should be as rigorous as you possibly can be. You should be. There is an injunction on you not to be cavalier about it, but in the end it\rquote s an interpretive method, it\rquote s a hermeneutic method, it\rquote 
s not a positivistic proof, and can\rquote t be, and most historical work is of that kind. And all periodisation, which is the notion of conjunctural analysis, which we deployed in Policing the Crisis, they\rquote re all interpretative. You can\rquote 
t say, \'93Well, I know this is the neo-liberal conjuncture\'94. How do you know? Well, because of this and this and this, and that\rquote s connected to that, and that seems to appear there out of that \endash  you can give it a rationale, 
you can explore it as fully as you can, but you can\rquote t, in the end say, \'93It is proven that the neo-liberal era began when Labour went out of power, and Mrs. Thatcher came in\'94. It\rquote s not a discourse of that kind. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
