\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 But, Stuart, are you proud that Cultural Studies did become an established - I\rquote m not sure whether \'93discipline\'94
 is the right word, but are you proud of this? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Of course, I\rquote m proud of it, I\rquote m struck by it. I\rquote m amazed by it. We had absolutely no such ambiti
ons, or even considered it might be possible. But I am also aware of how much it has changed. What I\rquote 
m describing to you is its early moment, the moment of its formation. It has gone through masses of changes in becoming more international, becoming more g
lobal, the spread of it to Italy first of all, and then to the US, and then, since then, everywhere in the world has a Cultural Studies Movement, or whatever it might be called. But each time it does that, it changes in character, a different set of influ
ences come in. So I\rquote 
m not sure that I think of it as one field, I think of it as a set of preoccupations which have evolved and changed over time, which relate to the early moments in the way in which buildings relate to their foundations, but not in a stri
ctly logical or sequential flow. But I\rquote m interested in it. But, some of those developments I\rquote m as opposed to, as I\rquote m opposed to anything else. To tell the honest truth, I think a lot of rubbish is published and written, I think there
\rquote s a lot of rubbish in sociology, but there\rquote s also a lot of rubbish in cultural studies. Some of the international journals of cultural studies, I think if I see one more analysis of some particular television series, I\rquote 
ll die! (LAUGHS) You know! And this parading itself as cultural studies, it\rquote s not cultural studies at all, it\rquote 
s media studies - a sort of elaborate version of media studies, with a very particular element, segment of cultural studies. It doesn\rquote t ask the cultural studies question, and that is the question, \'93How is 
culture related to other practices which are not, themselves, cultural in the same sense?\'94 That\rquote s the question of that early moment. So it\rquote 
s not to produce a cultural theory, self-sufficient in itself, it is to produce a notion of how culture is not a dependent, but itself a constitutive element in every other field and social practice. So it\rquote 
s interesting in those connections, and when you lose those connections, and the questions of power - which they always bring into play \endash  when you lose that, I think you\rquote ve departed from basic paradigm cultural studies, though they\rquote 
re tremendously successful that other people want to do them, and so on, they flourish in different places. They\rquote re less institutionalised in Britain, I think, than they are in almost any oth
er place. Most other places have a Department of Cultural Studies, we hardly do. We have a few, some more recent, I suppose, in the last decade or two. Before that, Cultural Studies people were hidden out in the existing disciplines. They were like Femini
sts - hidden in sociology, hidden in history, hidden in literature - doing this kind of work but within another kind of institutional framework. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Now, you hinted about Richard Hoggart\rquote s going, and you also said something about the kind of difference 
between you which arose. I\rquote m not sure what you were referring to. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
