\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, I refer to his g
oing because Hoggart was an established professor, he was on, the ExeCurtive Committee of Senate for the University. He was in charge of this Centre of radicals and experimentalists in the Centre for Cultural Studies. They became very involved in the occu
pation. Indeed, the Centre published an issue of the Birmingham University magazine, addressed to the Vice-Chancellor, called, \'93To Sir, With Love\'94, which was about that times are changing, you know \endash  it\rquote 
s a very undemocratic place, do you know that more collective work is being done rather than individual \endash  reflecting the sixties, the moment of the sixties. So by the time people actually took occupation in the University\rquote 
s Central Hall and offices, we were seen as deeply implicated in it. \'93Well, why don\rquote t you get your students in line, Richard?\'94 So he was in a very exposed position. Very exposed position. And I think he thought, at the end of that \endash 
 I don\rquote t know this \endash  but my assumption was that he thought this was not a tenable position to be in. \'93I should side-step, I should find a way of getting out for a time, of the limelight, the headlights\'94. He had very few \endash 
 he had a few \endash  but he had very few supporters at that level in the University, all the others thought it was a bunch of radical students and teachers, quasi-Marxists, quasi-revolutionaries, over-politicised, etc.. So he decided to go. I don
\rquote t know this, I don\rquote t know when the offer from UNESCO came, in relation to this, but I imagine it was in the aftermath of the sit-in, because in that year that he said, \'93I\rquote m going to take this job in UNESCO. That\rquote 
s quite a senior job relating to cultural policy. It\rquote s very influential, I should take it. So I\rquote ll be away on sabbatical for three or four years\'94. Then there was the question of what should happen to the C
entre, and many people wanted to close it down. That\rquote s the first attempt to close the Centre down. There have been many, and only a few people, like Halloran at Leicester, and Raymond and others wrote in and said, \'93You can\rquote 
t possibly do this. There\rquote s a very creative thing going on there. It\rquote s becoming influential way beyond its numbers. You can\rquote t just bring it to a halt\'94. \'93Okay\'94, they said, \'93Well, who\rquote 
s going to run it? I suppose Stuart Hall\'94. \'93Yes, okay, for a time while Richard is away\'94. \'93Would you make him professor?\'94 \'93No. Certainly not!\'94 A very very friendly Dean of the Faculty of Arts said to me, \'93
If you want a professorship, don\rquote t stay here, because this University will never give you one. Never. You\rquote re regarded as a cuckoo in the nest. A sport. An outsider\'94
. Well, of course, since I already felt, on other grounds, I was an outsider, this was just the clinching moment! (LAUGHS) Anyhow, I wasn\rquote t interested in that, but I just tell you this more in relation to the University\rquote 
s attitude to the institution, yes? \'93Well, we can\rquote t close it because important people outside think it\rquote s worth doing, but we\rquote 
re not going to bump it up, perhaps somebody with not a lot of status in the University takes it on, they will see it dwindle, and when Hoggart comes back it\rquote ll be a different thing, or he\rquote 
ll have the opportunity to to drag it back to his greater interests\'94. So I think that\rquote s the sort of assumption around the place when he went. So when I took it on, I was Acting Director, and I remained Acting Director for four y
ears. Then there was another such crisis four years later, when Richard said, \'93I\rquote m not coming back\'94. \'93Ah, well, I think we\rquote d better close the Centre, then. It\rquote s a Hoggart Centre\'94. No. People wrote in and said, \'93It
\rquote s now publishing all over the place. There are book series, and other people are doing this kind of work. You can\rquote t possibly close it down\'94. \'93Oh, all right. Well, we\rquote ll confirm him as the Director\'94
. So I was then Director, not Acting Director, from 1974 till I left in \rquote 79. Incidentally \endash  and this doesn\rquote t really follow - but it\rquote s just a thought that\rquote 
s come into my head, which you need to bear in mind. I talked about what theoretical work we were reading early in the Centre \endash  Weber, Durkheim, Simmel, classics of European social thought, but I haven\rquote t talked about Marx. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
