\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes. Okay.
 Marxism was a point of reference in early cultural studies because it was also concerned with the relationship between culture and other practices, but he had a particular economistic base superstructure, dependent dependency way of understanding that, w
hich we didn\rquote t agree with. So our involvement with Marx was to be tremendously inspired, to use concepts, borrow all the time, etc., and yet to quarrel with certain aspects of his work. So we were - I don\rquote 
t know what you call the term - people often say, \'93Are you a Marxist?\'94 Well, in the sense that my world view is framed by, you know, a basic understanding of Marx\rquote s position with which I agree, it is, but I\rquote 
m not what most people think of as a Marxist. I\rquote m a Revisionist from the beginning. I was only interested in working with and revising some of Marx\rquote 
s ideas. So the relationship to Marx is very much misunderstood outside, because they imagine he was the secret inspirer of cultural studies, whereas he was one on the points of contention! We defined ourselve
s in part with, and in part against a sort of Marxist approach. But it was a very important continuing thread right through. And Gramsci is important because first of all he made more tangible and more constitutively, in its own right, the political quest
ions \endash  questions of power \endash 
 and questions of power were usually ruled out of culture. Culture had nothing to do with those earthy problems of power, except that it did. It was all about social meaning, and it did have a lot to do with questions of power. Th
e Marxist notion of ideology did cover some aspects of that, although Marx thought ideology was dependent on the base, and reflective of it, whereas we didn\rquote t. So he\rquote s a point of debate, discussion, focus. And that\rquote 
s why Gramsci is so important, because Gramsci worked in exactly the same way as I did. He accepts a broad framework, he\rquote 
s not so explicit about his Revisionism, but he is revising all the time. By the time you get to the end of Gramsci, the relationship between politics, economics, and culture does not look the same as it does at the end of The German Ideology. It doesn
\rquote t. Okay, that\rquote s just to correct an emphasis. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
