\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Yes, of course. Yes. There was an English and American Studies Department at the University of Naples, led by Professor Ferrara, who was an old Shakespearian scholar, but also a Marxist. He was very very interested in Hoggart and Raymond\rquote 
s work, and in cultural studies as it developed. And he sent one of his young women lecturers \endash  Lidia Curti \endash  to have a year at the Centre, in about - the Centre opened in \rquote 64, must be \rquote 
65, very early on. Technically, she was attached to the Italian Department, teaching language, but she came to all our seminars and participated very heavily. Okay, in one of those more theory-oriented early groups that I described, she said, \'93Well
, have you ever read Gramsci or Croce?\'94 Well, I\rquote 
d read Gramsci. I remember, as Editor of New Left Review, a tiny book published by Lawrence and Wishart, which had extracts from The Modern Prince, was published. So I read Gramsci a bit, and I knew the role that he had played in Italian politics \endash 
 a bit. I knew about the Turin occupations and so on, but not really. So we began to ask, \'93Well, what is it about Gramsci? What does Gramsci say?\'94 So she was the person who really introduced Gramsci, in a more system
atic way, into Centre thinking. So when she went back, they started a huge cultural studies strand within the Department of Language and Literature, and in the ten or twenty years which followed that, we were hardly without some member of that group of st
aff coming to Birmingham for six months or a year, or whatever it was \endash 
 a whole procession of them, one after another. They came, learnt something about cultural studies, took it back, created a strand of cultural studies within the Italian English Studies 
Confederation, etc. - they gave it its first international presence really. Another influence was Larry Grossberg, who was one of the first people, first American students. We had a lot of American visitors \endash  because I haven\rquote 
t told you about the visitors yet, but let\rquote s leave that \endash  but he was one of the first American students, very involved in the sit-in in \rquote 
68, who went back to do his Ph.D. at the Annenberg School of Communications with James Cary, and James Cary was very knowledgeable about [and] sympath
etic to Raymond, and so after took the message of cultural studies to the US. But Italy was, you know, Italy was our first contact. And Lidia Curti was really the first independent friend that Catherine and I made after we were married. Before that, they 
were either Catherine\rquote s friends, or my friends. But at Birmingham we got to know Lidia as somebody that we both got to know. She was an early friend of both of us together after \rquote 
64, when we got married. Andwe communicated with her practically every weekend
. She came back to the Centre many times. Ferrara came to the Centre, on and on and on, Marina Vitali, two people who were at my birthday are from Italy. And she eventually married one of my graduate students \endash  Ian Chambers \endash 
 who is one of the people she met on her return visits, and he went the other way! He went to teach in Italy, and took his interest in cultural studies there. So that\rquote 
s the first international interchange. That and the US were the first ones. Interestingly, neither France nor Germany we
re, at that stage, at all interested. France, because the French think they know all about cultural theory already, thank you very much! And they\rquote 
re certainly not going to learn anything about that from the British! (LAUGHS) And the Germans because, well, it wasn\rquote 
t sufficiently philosophical for them. Not Hegelian enough, not trained in European philosophy, and they had Adorno, who was also a kind of cultural critic, but from the Hegelian/Marxist Frankfurt School tradition, rather than from other sources. S
o they didn\rquote t take it on either, although afterwards, in \rquote 68 and afterwards, since then it\rquote s become a very important strand in Germany. It hasn\rquote t become in France. You wouldn\rquote 
t find Departments of Culture Studies in France, French universities \endash  they all think they\rquote re already doing it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 In their own way. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
And in their own way. And that, to some extent, is based on the fact that cultural studies, at a certain point, you know, drew enormously on French cultural theory, so it drew from that \endash  and on German too. It\rquote 
s a very important moment in cultural studies when it undergoes the \'93theoretical turn\'94 \endash  as it\rquote s called. First of all, cultural studies discovers language, and takes a \'93linguistic turn\'94
, very influenced by Saussure who is one of the founding thinkers of French structural linguistics of Saussure. Then we looked at linguistics in cultural anthropology. In the States, they\rquote 
re very interested in Indian terms and Weltenschaung, you know, etc.. We were not directly influenced so much by Adorno. I don\rquote t know why. People find it hard to understand why we just didn\rquote 
t take on the Frankfurt School as our model. We didn\rquote t. The grouping, the organisation of the Centre was rather like, I understand, the Frankfurt School, in its wider meaning too. But we didn\rquote 
t follow that model. But there is another turn, and that is the turn into theory, which is happening during the period when I\rquote m there, and there\rquote s a huge debate between what was defined as the \'93humanistic approach\'94
 to cultural studies, of which Hog
gart, Williams, Thompson, and so on, were felt to belong, and structuralism, which was the rival view of how you would study and analyse culture - much more influenced by Levi-Strauss, therefore more anthropological in orientation. Then by Roland , and so
 on. Later by Foucault, then by Derrida and so on. So there are these shifts within cultural studies, some of which occur, of course, after me. The theoretical turn sort of occurs within that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
