\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 So I think we\rquote ve got a good idea now about the Centre and what you managed to do there. Why did you decide to leave? }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
I decided to leave for two reasons. One was that every year the same pattern would recur. We would start - I was teaching the theory course. We would start. Then, in the spirit of 1968, at a certain point, they would say, \'93Hey, hold on! Why aren
\rquote t we studying that?\'94 Or, \'93Why aren\rquote t we studying this?\'94 And they\rquote d want to \endash  in the spirit of \rquote 68 \endash  re-write the curriculum. Well, was I ready for that? I wasn\rquote 
t sure. But it was such a predictable moment, I thought to myself, at one point, \'93I cannot go through another confrontation with the students about, \lquote Why isn\rquote t more Feminist text being studied?\rquote  or, \lquote 
Why are we studying that?\rquote  \lquote Why are we going back to Hoggart?\rquote \'94 - that kind of question. \'93I can\rquote t do it. I can\rquote t change this 
orientation of my own interest, overnight, to suit each random group of students who walk into the Planning Meeting\'94. So I thought, \'93
Time for you to go. Time for you to go and give it independence. Let it go on. Find another niche for yourself. Another place for yourself\'94. My experience in the Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament, and the New Left, had always been that you mustn\rquote 
t confuse personal trajectories with institutional ones. Institutions persist, and you aren\rquote t the right person for it any longer, tough luck. Get out. But don\rquote t think that because you\rquote ve gone, the project has stopped. And it hadn
\rquote t. It\rquote ll go on \endash  as it did. It\rquote ll develop a new emphasis \endash  as it did. But you may not be happy any longer, doing that. The second thing was a sort of version of
 that, which was we had worked so hard to try to run and organise the Centre collaboratively. I\rquote 
ll give you one instance. I talked about Gestetner machines, yes. The only way of copying things, in those days, was on the old Gestetner machine. We bought a s
econd Gestetner machine, so that the students had unmediated access to it, and could circulate anything they liked to any member of the Centre. So we were putting through, \'93Shall we do this?\'94 \'93Here\rquote s an agenda for the next series seminar
\'94. And they were putting out - (LAUGHS), well, this is extremely creative tension, but it is a tension, and, you know, well, I wasn\rquote t always up to it, is the answer. And that\rquote 
s because I had inherited, of course, older models, including gendered models, of leadership and so on. I was ultimately the Director, although I wasn\rquote t Director in any classical or accepted sense of the word, but I couldn\rquote 
t get rid of the idea that teachers had a duty to teach as well as participate in discussion, and students had something to learn as well as dialoguing. Do you understand me? And those are ingrained habits. And I thought, \'93I\rquote m not ready\'94
, as it were. \'93I won\rquote t be good at just saying, \lquote Well, you can define the Centre in whatever way you like\rquote \'94. But this is, you know, this sounds self-justificatory, I don\rquote t feel self-justificatory about it at all, I feel it
\rquote s a limitation on myself. It came, really, in relation to Feminism. The Centre had a thesis by Trevor Millum in the very early days, which was published as a book called, Women in Advert
ising, and this was his Ph.D. on the image and role of women in contemporary advertising. The Centre had a Group doing work on women\rquote 
s magazines, so the idea that there was no Feminist content to cultural studies was not quite right, although it didn\rquote t bul
k very large. But when Feminism, as a Movement, developed in the very late sixties and seventies, women wanted to get together as they did elsewhere, and have a caucus, a women\rquote 
s caucus, to which men were not men, including the Director, and the two male members of staff, were not necessarily admitted. They wanted to go off and bring back a roneo\rquote d critique of our position. And my feeling about it was, \'93
I thought we were making this collectively, as a project. Can you have a caucus, a gendered caucus, while maintaining a collective project?\'94 And the answer to that is, \'93Ideally, of course, you can. But practically it puts a lot of strain on people
\'94. Especially like me, formed in an earlier model, trying to un-learn that model, and trying to adapt to and learn another more collaborative one. And I wasn\rquote t good at it. Well, I felt I wouldn\rquote 
t be happy in doing so any longer. Well, as you can see, these two aspects come together, because one of the things that the students were criticising were exactly the absence of Feminist issues. \'93Why aren\rquote 
t we reading Juliet Mitchell as much as we\rquote re reading Edward Thompson?\'94 \'93Why aren\rquote t we looking at Christeva as well as Levi-Strauss?\'94 etc.. Well, the answer to that is, \'93There were no good reasons!\'94 (LAUGHS) And eventually we 
did, but, you know, I felt peculiar in that, well, I hadn\rquote 
t helped to push this. My feeling about Feminism was very complicated, because, in the early stages, because of my involvement through Catherine and people in Birmingham, in the early Feminism, earl
y renewal of second-wave Feminism, I wanted to push the Centre in this direction, so I encouraged Trevor Millum\rquote s Ph.D., supervised it. I encouraged the work on women\rquote 
s magazines, and I even tried to get one or two Feminist scholars to accept an attachment to the Centre for a year, because I thought, \'93Well, there are lots of young women coming to us. Why isn\rquote t the place more Feminist?\'94 So I thought, \'93
I am in the usual in advance of this move\'94. I didn\rquote t really like to be told by younger women, \'93I\rquote m afraid you should shut up\'94, \'93Why don\rquote t you take a back seat?\'94 \'93Dear Stuart, because it\rquote 
s not your time any longer\'94, in that unmediated way. They were quite right. Quite right. But it\rquote s an old habit that I couldn\rquote t learn at that stage. It taught me a very very impor
tant lesson about the distinction between change in theory, and in practice. Men can be as Feminist as they like in their orientation, beliefs, what they subscribe to, their ideology, their politics, but their actual practice remains stubbornly fixed in o
lder gendered modes. I didn\rquote 
t like being thought of as believing that theory was masculine, but well, I suppose I sort of did. Well, I must have, because I was much more familiar with that than I was familiar with Feminist writing. So maybe I did. So I began to look for a way out. 
\'93Well, what are you going to do? There\rquote s no other place like this. It\rquote s been an absolutely transformatory experience in your life\'94, you know, \'93you\rquote ll never be the same again \endash 
 what you work on, how you think, how you work, you know, etc., will be marked by this\'94. \'93What are you going to do? Are you going to go back, teach literature? Teach Henry James? What are you going to do?\'94 \'93Well, teach sociology\'94. \'93You
\rquote re not a sociologist. You\rquote ve never been to a sociology lesson in all your life! Nobody\rquote s going to hire you to teach sociology\'94. Well, so the question was where? And I did, in fact, get some approaches \endash  I won\rquote 
t say from where \endash  but then I was invited to come and give a talk, they didn\rquote t like what they heard. They did not like what they heard. That never went anywhere. Then, all of a sudden, a friend of mine said, \'93
You know, sociology at the Open University is looking for somebody, because they\rquote ve just lost their Head, and they\rquote re trying to find somebody, and they\rquote ve asked me to sound you out as to whether you\rquote 
d be interested in going there\'94. And I thought, \'93The Open University? Well, that\rquote s less structured than graduate studies in Kent or Essex or Oxford or Manchester. Much more open. Based not on disciplinary boundaries so much as 
groupings of disciplines\'94. Yes, in the OU, we don\rquote t have Departments. There\rquote s not a Geography Department. There\rquote s a grouping of staff called \'93The Geography Discipline\'94, but it\rquote 
s almost, by definition, that some courses in sociology will have a geographical
 element, and some people from the Geography Discipline will come and work for them. I wrote for the Geography Discipline on migration, and lots of people in Geography, John Allen, for instance, wrote for Sociology. So I thought, \'93
This is a looser structure\'94. Secondly I thought, \'93
This is a good test as to whether Cultural Studies can survive in another element, especially not among students who are professionally highly trained, but among a different sort of student, without a developed analytic vocabulary 
and conceptual framework. Ordinary folks. Can you make this stuff which you\rquote 
ve been pursuing with these highly specialised graduate students, many of them, getting grants to do their Ph.Ds.? Can you make the issues in Cultural Studies intelligible within a
 broader disciplinary framework and to a different audience, student audience?\'94 It\rquote s a kind of test as to whether this is really, in the end, an elite pursuit or not. So I said, \'93Yes, I would be interested\'94
. And I was offered the job. And I remember the Vice-Chancellor saying to me, \'93Well, but are you willing to profess to the discipline of Sociology?\'94 And I said, \'93Well, I\rquote m willing to profess to anything that will get me a job!\'94
 (LAUGHS) Because I couldn\rquote t really claim to be a professional sociologist, of 
course not! So anyhow, they gave me the job. And my role there, not my plan, but what eventually turned out, was that I took cultural studies questions and increasingly cultural studies people, into the courses we were writing and planning for other subje
cts. So in my time, the sociology courses we offered were of a very different kind from those which had been offered before or since. We wrote a course on \'93The State and Society\'94. \'93Well, isn\rquote t that politics?\'94 \'93Mmm, Yes. Yes\'94
. We hosted geographers and historians etc.. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Were you interested by the challenge of distance learning? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
