\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Yes. I was interested by the challenge of non-academically trained, or backgrounded, students. I was interested in the difference in the class background of Open Unive
rsity students. I was interested in their age and experience, rather than their formal educational achievement. All of this about the student body. And then I was interested in the challenge of distance learning, in itself, but even more because what that
 meant was that the staff were writing courses, writing them. That\rquote 
s the work I did for the OU. It was not to teach. I taught Summer School. I taught classes, but that was not my job. My job was, from the start, to produce courses - to write, to commission,
 to write, to revise course material. To make supporting television and radio programmes. To put together key texts which might be published by some outside person. Yes? A body of readings, [with] which you had an opportunity to sort of define a field. So
 that\rquote s what attracted me very much, not, strictly speaking, the distance learning aspect. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Did you miss having direct contact with students? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
