\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, I don\rquote t know. We did a course called \'93Beliefs and Ideologies\'94, I don\rquote t think there\rquote 
d ever been a sociology course called that! Then we did a course on the State, which really didn\rquote t seem to quite belong, but dealt with social relationships very profoundly, not just with political power. Then, very influential, was a ba
se course in sociology, which was on Modern Societies, and that had a really big impact, because the notion of modernity had just come in and was widely circulating, and it framed, you know, it very much framed the way in which that course was designed, b
u
t together, written and revised, and taught. Then we went on from that to do the Media and Cultural Studies course, which is the first course of that kind that the OU had ever taught. So several of them were influential. Several of them were important inn
ovations, and many of them, in different areas, were influential. There was a time when every undergraduate Department in a straightforward old style university, seemed to be using Modernity and Society. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
