\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 No, no, that\rquote s a different strand altogether! (LAUGHS) That\rquote s another kind of strand. I mean, you know, somebody said 
\endash  Bill Schwartz, I think - that by the time he came to the Centre, York
 graduate in history, taking on cultural studies work, working very much in the historical area with Richard, but the general Centre approach and concerns, well, by then, he said, \'93
I always thought that cultural studies was political, in the broad sense\'94. 
This is a much misunderstood view, because it was never lined up behind a political current or tendency, and was one of the things I insisted that the Centre was not recruitable to one or other of the Trotskyist Groups, or the Communist Party, or the Labo
u
r Party. Nothing. Every student was free to proselytise, to interpret, to spread the word, in the Centre, but the Centre could not be subordinated to one political tendency, not only because that would be divisive, but also because Gramsci has two injunct
ions \endash 
 one is that intellectuals have tried to, if possible, locate themselves in the place of not just what exists, but what is emergent, was coming into being. And secondly, that they have a responsibility to be rigorous. They have to, Gramsci said, \'93to u
nderstand better than anybody else does, the social phenomenon they are explaining\'94. So they can\rquote t just polemically recruit some political theory that suits your group or your tendency and impose that, you can\rquote 
t do it. You really have to try to say, \'93I know better than traditional intellectuals, how this stuff works\'94. So that\rquote 
s one of the reasons for having a political conception of cultural studies but keeping sort of group politics out. And that was kind of broadly agreed by other members of the Centre. B
ut the second thing is that our definition of culture represented a critique of a more traditional conception of culture, which \endash  as I think I said in a sentence or two earlier \endash 
 was without a conception of power. Culture was the sphere where a power did not operate. It has been the greatest things that have been thought and said by mankind. It wasn\rquote 
t recruitable to the ruling class, or the ruling bloc, or the working-class, etc., it was an empirian sphere of values and judgements floating up above there in the Matthew Arnoldian sense. Well, we dirtied that conception. We said, \'93
It is not just that, but ideas are always connected with social groups, and thus connected with social interests. The interests don\rquote t explain entirely why people think that, but don\rquote t tell me that there isn\rquote 
t a connection. There is a connection\'94. In that sense the political was always part of cultural studies, part of culture. So these are two senses in which political was kept out of the Centre, or marginalised, and on the other hand
, which were central to the definition of what we were doing. Well, what that meant was that I, personally, pursued a kind of political path which overlapped with, and was influential, on my own approach, but which never tried to recruit people to it in t
he Centre, and which was often pursued outside the Centre. So the time when I was in the Centre, I was also active in anti-racist work, then active with Marxism Today \endash  where the critique of Thatcherism was made \endash  and so on. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
