\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Well, eventually. David Edgar, the dramatist, and I, became the only two members of the editorial group who had never been in the Communist Party. But that was because of what Marxism Today was. Marxis
m Today was the theoretical journal of the Communist Party, one of the places of the strictest Stalinist and Leninist lines. But when, you know, with the 20th Party Congress, and Khrushchev and the Hungarian Revolution, when the old bloc began to disinteg
rate, Marxism Today began to reflect these changes. So under Martin Jacques\rquote 
 editorship, it was still formally within the Communist Party, still being supported financially by the Communist Party, but following a very independent political path. One of the 
ways in which that was, was to recruit people to write for it, and to play a central role in it, who were not Communists subject to the Party line, thinking within Party grooves, etc., and I was one of those people. I started to write about it. Some thing
s
 which are of interest here. Why? Well, I started to write about it, because of Policing the Crisis, because as I say in Policing the Crisis, we understood that Policing the Crisis was written and conceived at the moment between two conjunctures. On the o
ne hand, the social democratic Keynesian Welfare State, more egalitarian redistributive moment, which comes apart in the seventies, the coming apart is the crisis in the title of the book, and more or less is ushered out in \rquote 
79. Mrs. Thatcher comes in, and Thatcherism begins, and a quite new conjuncture \endash  the newer liberal free market forces, privatisation, marketisation, restitution of the power of private capital, all of that comes in \endash 
 another conjuncture. We published in \rquote 78. Mrs. Thatcher had already em
erged, but was not elected until 1979, but anybody who read Policing the Crisis, or who understood what Policing the Crisis was about, and how its analysis was developed, knew that what was happening was not a mere twist in the electoral pendulum, but was
 a new conjuncture, a new phase altogether. And since we were looking at the impact of Conservatism and the anti-Welfare State consensus position, at a popular level, we said, \'93
If you find a populist Tory, who is able to put these new interests and concerns into a popular language, they will be elected\'94. They will be elected, because the old system has been coming apart at the seams. It can\rquote 
t hold any longer. Wilson was struggling to hold it together. By the time you get to Callaghan and industrial disputes and three-day working, it\rquote s finished. It\rquote 
s come apart at the seams. So this is a new area, and we would not be at all surprise if someone, as apparently marginalist, and apparently populist, as Mrs. Thatcher from Finchley \endash  for God\rquote s sake, where is that in the Conservative Party? 
\endash  wasn\rquote t the person who resonated with public opinion more effectively than Douglas-Home or members of the old more aristocratic based leadership. And we were right. So in an article I wrote for Marxism Today I said, \'93That\rquote s what
\rquote s going to happen\'94. That something of this kind is going to happen. And I\rquote m very proud of that. I\rquote 
m proud of it because not all sociological research is accurately predictive. But loose and confused and making itself up as it went along, out of the methodol
ogy applied in Policing the Crisis, it was accurate about what was to come. It was predictively correct. So then I got involved in analysing Thatcherism and its moment, and what it was about \endash 
 its theories and ideologies; its political programmes, etc.. A lot of that was published in Marxism Today, or under Marxism Today\rquote 
s auspices, including the book which you cited. The Hard Road to Renewal. That is really a selection, expansion of essays that I wrote in Marxism Today. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
