 so the people in my Department, like Ken Thompson, and Graham Salaman, and then Paul du Gay. And then, of course, course teams are mixed, because they\rquote re not just in one area, so John Cl
arke, Mike Fitzgerald from Social Policy and Criminology, and Doreen Massie from Geography, and John Allen from Geography, so from really all around the spectrum of the Faculty of Social Science I got to know quite a lot of people. And when I say \'93
got to know\'94
, worked with them. So for instance, David Hill was Professor in Politics there. I think, actually, David Hill was attached to the Sociology Department while I was there, though he went on to politics. I worked quite closely with him. So on different c
ourses over the years, it\rquote s a very intense experience. A course team lasts two to three years, you begin from nothing, talking, conversations, planning, outline, short outlines, drafts, first drafts, second drafts, third drafts, while you\rquote 
re doing that you\rquote re planning radio programmes and perhaps doing them, television programmes, doing them, publishing a book of course essays, course work, which is the draft, but also extracts from other books which you\rquote 
re going to get students to read. So the focus is on teaching, huge teaching operation. You have a Course Manager, who has to manage all that. Academics couldn\rquote t, weren\rquote 
t able to do that. You had many of the ideas, but the Course Manager played an absolutely crucial role \endash  holding the schedules together, making sure the television programmes are being completed; if they\rquote 
re with outside people, radio interviews with X and Y, setting them up; at the same time, keeping everybody up to time with the next draft, draft 2\rquote s, commenting, each time, in detail, on those drafts. If you\rquote 
re a Course Chair - I was of several courses - well, you really do very substantial editing between draft 1 and draft 2, draft 3 is a bit easier because you\rquote ve established the lines of comment and criticism by then. So it\rquote s quite a long ti
me. You\rquote 
ll probably, when the course is about to go out - which is, of course, when it faces the public and the undergraduates, and when it faces the part-time tutors, because you involve them also in the course at a late stage, because they tell you what 
they see as the problems of teaching to come, so they\rquote re involved. But, I mean, then it passes over to them \endash  they teach it, and pass back a lot of information about, \'93That Unit is not working very well\'94, \'93
We need some extra material on that\'94. \'93I wouldn\rquote t set a question on that because, really, the chapter doesn\rquote t handle it properly\'94, and so on. So it\rquote 
s a five or six year process. And then the courses last for three or four years. So it\rquote s quite a long time. They overlap. At the end of one course team, you\rquote r
e probably doing a Unit for a geography course while you still have another course in production, and people are teaching the course you\rquote ve just completed. So one\rquote s forced into very close contact with one\rquote 
s academic colleagues, certainly in the Faculty. And I think I mentioned to you before, they are called \'93disciplines\'94, because they\rquote re arranged \endash  Sociology, Politics, Geography, Economics, but they\rquote 
re not Departments, everything is within the Faculty. So people join other course teams other than their own,
 and you work with people from elsewhere. So I probably worked with Doreen Massie on four or five courses. I worked with John Allen on two or three. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
