\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, complicated, isn\rquote t it! (LAUGHS) Really, there are two elements to it. One is Gramsci. It\rquote 
s not well known, but the Althusserian Group \endash  Derrida, Poulantzas, all of them, read Gramsci. There was a Gramsci Reading Group, and a lot of Althusser is, in my view, Gramscian concepts translated into a structuralist idiom, Marxis
t structuralist idiom. So unless you have Gramsci, you really don\rquote 
t understand my take on Althusser. Gramsci is the person who talked a lot about conjuncture, about hegemonic forms of power, about historical blocks rather than the ruling class, on and on, 
Gramsci was proliferating new concepts for discussing the political, what is distinctively belongs to the political. Althusser brings a kind of structuralist mode of thinking about that, to bear on that, so that you\rquote 
d find important sections on articulation in Althusser, which is about the joining up of different processes or different sites, but then you have to go back to Gramsci who says, \'93
Hegemonic power is precisely something which is not defined just in one place\'94. For instance, you can\rquote t get it by ju
st commanding the State, because you have to command popular assent, you have to lead in intellectual work, you have to lead in the media, you have to lead in moral debate, so hegemonic power is precisely things coming together across a series of sites. S
o when Althusser says that in more specialised language, or closer to a kind of revision of Marxist text, you\rquote ve got to appreciate \endash  at least where I\rquote m coming from, you know, this is not an account of Althusserian scholarship, it
\rquote s my take on it, okay? \endash  an
d when Althusser discusses the vexed problem of determination in the last instance by the economic, which is where cultural studies begins in a resistance to that formulation taken in a simplistic way. Well, Althusser is the person who eventually frames t
he idea of over-determination, that things are determined at the same time \endash  ideologically and politically and economically \endash  so they\rquote re like symptoms really, they\rquote 
re the effect of several processes which crystallise, they conjoin, and that\rquote s exactly a conjuncture. So Althusser, for me, clarifies a lot that is in Gramsci, but he tends, because he occupies a structuralist position, which is to say \endash  I
\rquote m going to it in detail \endash  but he is reading Marx in a more structuralist way, in a more French way than a Heg
elian way. Very critical of Hegel, the Hegelian Marx. His line is that Marx goes away really, and Marx becomes more strictly an analyst of the capitalist mode of production, in its broader framework, so he would make a distinction between the Hegelian and
 the post-Hegelian, and that is what he would call \'93The structuralist Marx\'94. We were, of course, interested in structures \endash  and I think I\rquote ve said this to you \endash  I was interested in non-Marxist structuralism for a very long time 
\endash  Levi-Strauss, Roland - the q
uestion of structure in anthropology, semiotics, all of that strand of thought which is really, in critical theory, influenced by Saussure, stemming from Saussure. Saussure on language provided what somebody like me felt was a more rigorous form of cultur
al analysis than the analysis I had been taught in literary departments, which was sort of splurgy - do you feel, you see that metaphor? (LAUGHS) I think it works this way, you know. Semiotics always said, \'93
Yes, of course it works in that way, but it only works because the words work in a particular way, the language works in a particular kind of way\'94, and therefore language became not what the people imagine \endash 
 some notion that everything is really determined by language \endash  but language provides a sort of mod
el of culture. So people who are influenced by that strand of thinking, which goes right along Derrida and difference, and on and on and on in French critical thought, but Saussure is very much a kind of founding figure, though he was a linguist, he wasn
\rquote t a semanticist, he wasn\rquote t interested necessarily in broader social or political questions. I wrote this essay on two strands in culture studies, one which you call the \'93humanistic\'94
, to which Edward Thompson and Raymond Williams and so on belonged, and one called the \'93structuralist\'94, which was our first impact with French critical theory. And it\rquote 
s interesting for the Centre that it went that way, influenced by Althusser \endash  which is what you asked me in the first place \endash  rather than going in the Hegelian route
 to the Frankfurt school, which also had an elaborated theory of culture. But we didn\rquote t go that way. We went the French way rather than the German way. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
