\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, Althusser - first of all I accept that you can\rquote 
t really think about Marxism without thinking about the notion of structures. But structuralism is a different thing! (LAUGHS) Yes? It\rquote s a sort of methodology, it\rquote s a principle of analysis, and Althusser
 took structuralism right to the very end - to the extreme is really what I mean \endash 
 so that each of the practices that Althusser discusses are not only relatively autonomous of each other, they sort of become autonomous. At one point, Althusser, in reading Kapital, talks about a \'93theoretical practice\'94 as if it doesn\rquote 
t really matter whether the theory explains anything or not, or has any practical purchase on the world. Well, that was to leave, that\rquote s to apply structuralism, you know, much too far, as is the case in a lot of French critical theory \endash 
 for me. There are wonderful insights, you can work with them, you\rquote ve got to rob them, steal them away, and go on thinking in another way, because they will exaggerate it, to the sort of point of ridiculous. So when Althusser says, \'93
theoretical practice can\rquote t be measured by its practical or concrete relevance\'94, I thought, \'93This is rubbish\'94. \'93And is Hegel really so absent from the later Marx?\'94
 So there were key questions, for somebody who was very influential in my thinking, which I just thought, \'93It\rquote s too much. You\rquote re pushing the point. This is a good point, too far\'94. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
