\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 At a certain point. I don\rquote t know that I\rquote m so keen on it now (LAUGHS), but there\rquote s a point when it\rquote 
s in the atmosphere and I think it\rquote s important. I suppose what modernity means is it\rquote s the modern age, it\rquote s post-modernism, it\rquote s post-revolution in knowledge, which is cons
tituted by modern thought, from relativity all the way through all those incredible breaks with the past which happen roundabout the end of the 19th/beginning of the first two decades of the 20th century. And after that, it seems to me, modern life in the
 developed world is really significantly different, and \'93modernity\'94
 is just a way of summing up those differences. Yes? They constitute a new epoch, a new era. There is nothing dramatic about saying that, but one of the reasons for emphasising it is this: t
hat there is a strong preference for people who resist the modern - at least going back to tradition, going back to your roots and so on, and, of course, I respect all that \endash  I\rquote m very respectful of the past \endash 
 I mean, in some ways you wouldn\rquote t believe it, but I was a kind of historian manqu\'e9. I think historically all the time. I think in terms of \'93What are the conditions of existence of something which is happening now?\'94 So it\rquote 
s not that I\rquote m anti-historical in any way, but I felt that I didn\rquote t see why somebody like me, born in Kingston, should not aspire to live a modern life. I didn\rquote 
t see why I should go on being a native, primitive, and consigned to the margins of the intellectual and philosophical and literary world \endash  this is how I felt as a boy growing up
. I wanted to know about modernism. I wanted to know about modern music. I wanted to know who the hell Paul Klee was, and who was James Joyce? And, you know, why did Eliot write what he did? And who was Ezra Pound? And, you know, I wanted to know all thos
e things. Well, Kingston, of course, felt very provincial in relation to [all that]. I understood that, that\rquote s one of the reasons why I wanted to study abroad. \'93Go on\'94, you know, \'93
find out what is at the leading edge of the world, and claim it\'94. I think loads of West Indian writers and thinkers, at that point, without having it as a particular project, did just that. All the novelists came to London \endash 
 all of them. Why? Well, English literature was how they learnt their language, the finest writers were being
 published in New York and London, you go there and you are as good as they are, and you re-write The Tempest, and you re-write The Odyssey, you appropriate it for Caribbean. That is a modern impulse. Do you understand what I\rquote m trying to say? }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 It\rquote s, \'93I will not be shut out of future history because of what has happened in the past\'94
. So the debates about modernity slightly have these two edges to it. One is more analytic. What is it that\rquote s changed about the economy? What is it that is d
ifferent when the US is the leading instance rather than industrialising Britain? What is it about culture when high bourgeois culture gives way to mass culture and popular culture? What is it about society when there\rquote 
s a more cohesive sense of class, and 
now more individualist, more specialised groups, higher division of labour, social division of labour, etc.? What is it like when some of the primordial social divisions like wealth and property and so on, are compounded by new issues around sexuality, or
 
around Feminism, or around race, which is, after all, more primordial than class, but had never been given serious attention. So modernity is simply a phrase for summoning up these big distinctions between somewhere towards the end of the 19th century, an
d somewhere into the 20th century. Don\rquote t ask me where it starts and where it stops. I would have said, myself \endash  but for reasons we won\rquote t go into \endash  that it starts in the 1880s. I think that\rquote 
s the break with the older form. I think Hobsbawm was right, that is
 the age of capital, high bourgeois values. After that, something different is on. Something different is on. And for very good reasons. Something different is on because the first phase of industrial capitalism was based on extracting as much surplus val
ue as you could, provided you kept them alive, you didn\rquote t care how they survived \endash  that\rquote s the Marx/Engels story, that\rquote s the story of social reformers. You know, that was the condition then \endash  what Marx called \'93
extracting absolute surplus value\'94. After that you suddenly see, \'93Well, if they don\rquote t earn anything, who are you going to sell your products to? You\rquote ve got to sell them as items for conspicuous consumption\'94
. And the moment you begin giving them the vote, worrying about how much you can pay them and not raise your costs, the moment you say, \'93Well, I read Tolstoy but they look at \lquote Coronation Street\rquote \'94
, the moment you encounter those transition points \endash  which happens very much in the 18th, happens before \endash  then modernism, all this begins to accumulate in the
 intellectual realms, and then Joyce and Eliot and Picasso in the artistic world. So that\rquote s the kind of shift of conjuncture, a real shift in conjuncture. It doesn\rquote 
t coincide with the end of the century: you might say the First World War is the culmination
 of a huge arc that comes to its fruition in its disaster, in the First World War, and after that, all sorts of things which were germinating before that, take for instance, the phrase, \'93the masses\'94 \endash 
 mass politics, mass democracy, mass culture, mass production \endash  they\rquote re all 1880, 1890, they all follow the big depression, the Great Depression, they wave out of it. That\rquote 
s the moment when American mass production and consumerism and \'93a chicken in every pot\'94 takes over from \'93grinding the faces of the poor\'94, so it\rquote s another world. Another world. It\rquote 
s a very imprecise term, but that shift is the shift into modernity. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
