\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 No, I wouldn\rquote t put it quite like that. I am interested in 
photography, and more interested in photography than many people who are interested in visual arts, who regard the other visual arts as more central. Photography is a different sort of category from high art. But I would have said that it goes back to an 
i
nterest in the image, which is modernity! (LAUGHS) The moment when the visual overtakes the written and spoken word as the principal carrier of influences on the patterns of thought and common sense ideas of the masses of population. The impact of the ima
ge, and anything it has to do with it \endash  so I\rquote m interested in television, I\rquote m interested in photography, I\rquote m interested in advertising, I\rquote m interested in the cinema, yes? These are all particular interests of mine. I don
\rquote t think they\rquote re greater than Impressionist painting, it\rquote s not that, they are a different thing. They are a different thing. And I belong to the moment after these things emerge. Okay. So that\rquote 
s one set of interests. Later on, when we come to the period when I worked with visual arts organisat
ions, and was building Rivington Place, I did pay as much attention to photography as to other visual arts. One of the reasons is because I was interested, then, of course, in the work being done by black and Asian diaspora artists, and they didn\rquote 
t start with painting, they started with manipulating photography. Their aim was, as Joy Gregory says, the paintings are there for herself: self-portraits, \'93putting yourself in the frame\'94. [Black people] have been the excluded subject \endash 
 18th century, there we are with a dog attending to Mr. and Mrs.- whatever their names are! (LAUGHS) You know, we are always in the margins, in the subordinate role, etc.. What would happen if we put ourselves dead in the centre of the frame? Well, it
\rquote s a metaphor. And so in the sense that a frame doesn\rquote t exclude painting by any means, but it just says that\rquote 
s not the only way. Putting yourself is getting an image of yourself, seeing yourself, as a subject rather than as an object of somebody else\rquote s gaze or vision, etc., so I\rquote m interest
ed in the visual, in visual languages as the languages of modernity \endash  and that includes spectacle, and it includes the design of shops, you know, it includes Benjamin\rquote 
s work on the shopping malls etc., all of that is the huge concentration of the visual element in modern life. That\rquote s one time interest. Secondly, I\rquote 
m interested in representation. Now, the debate about representation really happens first of all in relation to film and film aesthetics, because the critics of this position argue very strongly a
gainst a mimetic conception of representation. That is to say that the aim of representation is to imitate real objects in the world \endash  a position which you might just have with Cezanne, but which you are unlikely to have with Picasso \endash 
 so the break I was talking about earlier comes into this. After that, and probably at all times, representation is not just an imitation of the world, it\rquote 
s not an imitation of nature, because that would make it of secondary importance, that would make it dependent on nature itself. Nature is the kind of ideal it is working towards, and what you don\rquote t understand is, \'93
Well, why draw or paint a landscape?\'94 or \'93Why paint a still life?\'94 \endash  go out and get some fruit and put it in a bowl? That\rquote s the real thing. It\rquote s because something 
else is going on. What happens in representation is that all sorts of ideas and feelings and subjective relationship to the object \endash  whatever it is \endash 
 is expressed in the sheer imitation of nature. Which is why no painters, even people who believe in the mi
metic formation of representation, that the painting of human beings is always different, they see them differently, and something about how they are seen goes into the way they are represented. So I have a much stronger interpretation of representation. 
Yes? Representation is another transformation. Representations are another level of reality, they are not just a copy of \'93the real\'94
. So you can put these two things together, the general theoretical interest in representation, and the particular interest in
 that break from verisimilitude, naturalism, into formalism and abstraction etc., and you put that together with the claim among diaspora people to equal rights of representation. I suppose there\rquote s a third element, and that is to say, \'93
If you think that I do - \'94 that - it\rquote s always, of course, been culture, but culture becomes a sphere of increasing importance \endash 
 exactly with the coming of modernity, because it becomes technologised, you know? So photography begins, it begins earlier than that, but the real e
ra of photography begins when people began to invest in the means of representation, not just in having your tame artists, in your palace, but in machines that will reproduce the world. This presents real problems for representation, because if the image 
you\rquote 
re pointing the camera towards, records it on film, what do you have to do with it? Well, the funny thing is, when you look at, no two photographers taking the same subject, will produce the same image. So other things are always going on. So if you
\rquote re interested in the cultural ideological dimension of the social, you\rquote d better address this form \endash  the visual \endash 
 which encapsulates it in a very important way, and this practice of representation, which transforms: it means that there\rquote s a real, and then there\rquote s how the real is represented. Somebody as very traditional as G.H. Mead said, \'93
Those things which men and women believe to be true are real in their effects\'94, so you\rquote d better take the question of culture and feeling and subjectivity and ideas and ideologies seriously. It\rquote 
s not a secondary mirror image of the real economic relations, or the real class relations. Indeed, it had a retrospective effect on that, because class relations would not be what they were without precisely some conception of class in people\rquote 
s heads. Where did that come from? Well, all over the place \endash  people like me, people they talk to, things they see, thing\rquote s they\rquote re watching and observing \endash  so the representation works back on the thing represented. There
\rquote s no real and the represented. So this creates an interest in this world, I would say. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 When did you first get interested in photography? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
