\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 No. I don\rquote t. Then I become very interested in film, which is the medium of modernity. Again, it arises in that period
, comes into its fruition: colour, the big, wonderful cinemas of the post-War period, France, Italian neo-realism, American cinema, and so on, so my visual interest is transferred to film. Then in the period I think you\rquote 
re talking about, it becomes focused on the visual arts, in particular the visual arts of black artists and Asian artists working in Britain, or showing their work in Britain. And they are second generation diasporic subjects. They\rquote 
ve been through the very difficult period of settlement when the post-War migrants first arrived. The second generation has gone to school here, they\rquote 
re becoming educated, but they simultaneously feel distanced from the place which is their potential new home. They feel they have what\rquote s called \'93double consciousness\'94 \endash  they belong to Jamaica, but they\rquote 
ve never been there. They have been to London, but people in London don\rquote t think they\rquote re really Londoners, so they\rquote re betwixt and between. This is the second generation, which is the audience for reggae, it is Rastas, it
 is rude boys, it is anti-racism, that whole thing. One of the things that comes out of it is a few of them who get, for the first time, to Art School, and they start to paint, or take photographs of themselves \endash  putting themselves in the frame 
\endash  and of other things, \'93this is how we see it, not how you see it. This is how we see it\'94
, and indeed, as a weapon of protest, the first big wave, Eddie Chambers and so on, you know, are very close to the kind of collage protest art of the Black Power and of Civil Rights. So it hasn\rquote 
t sort of explicit politics, but it carries forward a sort of political critique, even when it\rquote s not so directly engaged politically. Now, this produces enormous work, interesting work. In the eighties there\rquote s a huge explosion of this kind
 of work - everybody\rquote s making something, doing something, putting together an installation, taking photographs, doing some painting, writing, etc. \endash 
 huge creative explosion. And they have nowhere, nobody who represents them, nobody who attends to their work very carefully, they can\rquote t get spaces for exhibitions, galleries are not interested in their work, Art Schools don\rquote 
t teach their work, they don\rquote t encourage them to produce it. Okay. So, you know, there is a question about their accessibility. There is a question about, \'93What is their impact \endash 
 not in relation just to the black community and black consciousness elsewhere, in the Caribbean and black America, and South Africa and elsewhere, but in Britain?\'94 In Britain. And some of my friends have spent their 
youth organising little exhibitions in back-street shops in Brixton, the Black Arts Centre which, you know, closes tomorrow, and then opens somewhere else. But fine work is done in that period. So I became involved with two Organisations that come out of 
that eighties work, or are inspired by it. One is in the visual arts more narrowly defined, and it\rquote s called the Institute for International Visual Arts \endash  INVA, and the other is a similar movement, parallel movement, in photography \endash 
 the Association of Black Photographers, Autograph. And these two organisations are what emerged from that earlier period \endash  the eighties into the nineties. Something else comes out of that, and that\rquote 
s the black film makers, Isaac Julian, John Akomfrah, Steve MacQueen and so on, that\rquote s also going, and they\rquote re all similar problems \endash 
 who will give them money to make films? Where will their work be shown? They get subventions to start a series of workshops \endash  they\rquote re all beginners \endash  film workshops, and these other people are all beginne
rs, small organisations, picking the artists and championing the broader cause \endash  cultural cause of what Fanon calls \'93The fact of blackness\'94 as a strong element in the arts, because a strong element in social life, and it\rquote 
s going to be a strong element in Britain \endash  whether they like it or not. So I became involved with this work, introduced to it very much by someone who was responsible for putting on many of those exhibitions \endash 
 his name is David Bailey. He was a young photographer, he doesn\rquote t produce very m
uch but he was a very early putter together of exhibitions, and selective, and he tracked their futures, etc.. He was a kind of early curator of this work, he and many other people. But that just happens to be my route into it, and I met people through hi
m. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
