\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes. Yes. We\rquote re not telling them what to paint, or what to do at all. We\rquote 
re partly responsible for generating a debate about those things. What is black art? What does that mean? So there is a debate going on about it, and black art isn\rquote t impacted by Feminism, so what are black women\rquote 
s interests visually different from black men\rquote s interests, etc.? So there\rquote s a series of debates like that. We would feel we had a responsibility to those debates - for providing a venue for them, for inviting people to them \endash  
but we are not trying to lead the field. And when artists move from black and white naturalism \endash  so-called \endash  to colour, to paint, and then to abstraction or semi-abstraction, we go with them, because now they\rquote 
re in Art Schools and they\rquote re coming into contact with modern art in a wider sense \endash  they\rquote re learning about abstraction, they\rquote re learning about installations \endash  so that\rquote 
s what they want to show, in some ways their consciousness, what they\rquote re on about, goes into that kind of work, and we\rquote ll follow them if that\rquote s what they want to exhibit. We won\rquote 
t not exhibit the earlier work, and in a sense, photography has its feet in that earlier tradition, but so does film, so does painting, so does drawing. It\rquote s not a commitment to naturalism. You\rquote re not talking abou
t my personal tastes, because that doesn\rquote t help you either, because, you know, I like all the stuff! I like photography, I like painting, I like abstraction, I like non-abstraction. I\rquote 
m interested that, on the whole, the black arts have not gone wildly into abstraction, they\rquote 
re still more figural, they use the face and the body much more than the broad generality of global modern art does, and that interests me, because I think you can see its roots in putting yourself in the frame, still operating within a
 tradition where even the forms have become more abstract... But you\rquote ll notice that, perhaps in the work that I have in the house, most of which was given me by artists of that generation, there\rquote 
s a lot more photography than there would normally be. You\rquote re looking at two paintings by Chris Ofili, who\rquote 
s a painter, wonderful painter. But in the room in there, there are lots of photographs. A lot of them are art photography, that is to say, they use the camera, not literally to record what\rquote s going on, which is
 the documentary element, but as they construct the scenes. But still they photograph them. Just at the head of the stairs down there is a young black man, with his hands in his pockets, standing in a public urinal, and you can see reflected in the mirror
 above his head, a graffiti, which is called \'93White Knights\'94. Well, what\rquote 
s the point of setting up an apparatus and staging an actor to film a man in a public urinal? Well, it has a lot to say about the period of black masculinity, a lot to say about the period of the posse, about involvement, there\rquote 
s a kind of hard look on his face, the involvement in crime or drugs, or small hustling or whatever it might be, but he\rquote s well-dressed, black suit, there\rquote s the style of black street fashion involved in it. It\rquote s a
 kind of combination. I don\rquote t mind something which says, \'93This is how it really looked in the seventies in Hackney\'94
, and something else which says, like a great black abstractionist, still going, but now must be nearly 90, to one of the very earliest called Frank Bowling, who in a debate about black art, said, \'93Well, if you ask me, black art \endash 
 whatever that is \endash  begins in abstraction\'94. So you can\rquote t argue with that as a wide spectrum! I\rquote ve just written a piece about somebody called Dennis Morris, who was a photographer in Hackney in the seventies. And there\rquote 
s an incredible portrait of growing up black in one of those London black settlements. Incredible images. He took marriages and weddings and birthdays, but he also shot the neighbourhood. There\rquote s a tremend
ous amount of documentary element in it. If I showed them to you, you would say, \'93These are documents, but they\rquote re not just recording - we\rquote re not just building an archive of what really was there - he\rquote s on a theme\'94
. Well, I like that work very much, and it\rquote s got huge publicity, it was in the Guardian, it\rquote 
s in the Telegraph colour supplement, it really attracted a lot of attention. Because this guy, Dennis Morris, then went on - at 19 he went to a Bob Marley concert, and Marley said, \'93What are you doing?\'94 He said, \'93I\rquote 
m trying to become a photographer\'94, and [Marley] said, \'93Do you want to come on tour with us?\'94 And many of the record covers that you and I think of as Bob Marley records, are done by Dennis Morris, who has a foot in the creative music camp, and a
 foot in the documentary tradition. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Interesting. One of the last things you published to do with visual artists was Different [2001] wasn\rquote t it, and that\rquote 
s to do with how photos can show black identity. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes. But I would say it\rquote s a slight d
eparture from that because there is an exploration of black identity, but it is not some essentialist notion of blackness. Yes? So there\rquote s not one blackness, and there\rquote 
s not one way of representing it. And the image, itself, explores that. It is one of the
 modes of exploring the complexity of blackness. So it seems a kind of interrogation of blackness, rather than just a representation of it, or a reflection of it. The question of identity, as you can imagine, is absolutely essential because, who are these
 
people? Brought to the Caribbean from West Africa, driven into slavery in the plantation; 400 years of Colonialism; the terrible vicissitudes of their existence; coming to England looking for a different life; making settlements which are part English and
 part not, themselves and the white working-class in the same areas, getting on with them, and hating them or not getting on with them \endash  very complicated thing. Where is the essential blackness in that? There isn\rquote t one. It\rquote 
s a series of positions which calls itself \'93blackness\'94
, and each one of them is not complete, and each one of them, as it were, has an openness to what is it about to become, not just what it is. I could show you a portrait, a picture, taken by the same Dennis Morris, of a boy running acro
ss one of those bare patches of the city, in the seventies \endash  waste ground really - and he\rquote s hurrying across, and he looks at the camera, sees the camera is looking at him, and says - Dennis Morris calls it, \'93Brother, can you spare a dime?
\'94 If you look at the boy\rquote s face, he isn\rquote t a beggar at all! He\rquote s going somewhere else, boy. He\rquote s off! You know, he\rquote s off! Scooting across this ground, off somewhere to some gig or some scenario, or some party! He
\rquote s not hanging around to be pitied and abused and marginalised. He\rquote s off somewhere else, boy! He\rquote 
s going places. I can show you another image of a man and a woman, living in one room, this is in the sixties. Their bed is there, their sofa is there, and their washing is hanging up there, and he is sitting, with his daughter, on the sofa. But he
\rquote s in a pork-pie hat, he\rquote s in smart cleanly pressed trousers, you know, he\rquote s in a white shirt, with tie, he\rquote s not going to be knocked down by this experience. He\rquote s not its victim. He won\rquote t be it\rquote 
s victim. And all of that is carried \endash  just an ordinary man with his daughter, sitting in a one-room house, which is the most squalid living conditions in multi-occupation London that you can think of. But out of this comes what I\rquote 
m always interested in, which is something that is emergent, a new interpretation of blackness is emergent. Forces that you don\rquote t expect are already at work wherever you are, in these terrible political times, people say, \'93
Well, where are the forces of change?\'94 \'93Well, we don\rquote t know. We\rquote re not good enough to see. But the one thing you can bet is that the next decade will not be just a repetition of this one\'94
. And it will come from somewhere. And those contradictions are already busy at work emerging. Emerging. So it treats blackness \endash  that kind of work \endash  as an emergent quality, not of the fixed, stabilised. Yes? And I was interested in \endash 
 put it another way, routes \endash  R O U T E S \endash  travelling, yes? Taking blackness somewhere else, building new diasporas, as it is in the past, conquest, movement, transportation, etc., as I am in roots \endash  R O O T S. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 This idea of there not being a sort of single image, that\rquote 
s very typical of your way of thinking, I think. I remember, also, Pictures of Everyday Life [1987], in a way that\rquote s trying to suggest the variety of [images]. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
