\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 You\rquote 
ve been reading my work too assiduously, Paul! (LAUGHS) You know the Commonwealth exhibition, competition, for pictures from around the world, by non-British people, and I was asked to be one of the judges, and so the person who organised it, and I, decid
ed that it would be nice to produce a book, which was of the people who did well, who were shown in this exhibition \endash 
 wherever they came from. Which, therefore, was one of the many occasions that influenced me to think that there were multiple ways of being
 marginalised, not one way, and that depending on different cultures, this fact would be seen in different ways. And what Difference is about, why it\rquote s called Difference, is because the assumption is, \'93
Oh well, these differences are really just the surface effect of some essence which is fixed and steady\'94, and I think it\rquote 
s not. That may be there at a certain point, qualities of blackness may get fixed, but the qualities of blackness gets fixed in slavery \endash  a very distinct, horrendous image of blackness ther
e. So there are many points at which routes, - which is what we\rquote 
re talking about - is this Africa? Is this a plantation? Is this slavery? Is this colonised blacks? Is it free blacks? Which blackness are we talking about? So the argument is that it isn\rquote t ju
st the same being myriadly represented, each representation is an active transformation of something which you posit as being there, but which isn\rquote t essential. What matters are the differences. What matters are the differences. Don\rquote 
t try and leave the differences and find the total essence, leave the essence out because it\rquote s a kind of positive starting point. You\rquote ve got to start somewhere! But that\rquote s not what\rquote s important. What\rquote 
s important is that each one transforms and reaches, complexifies, opens new dimensions on whatever is the subject that you\rquote re dealing with. And that, you know, does have something to do with the impact on me of \endash  which you haven\rquote 
t asked \endash  post-structuralism. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 I hardly dare to ask! But since you\rquote ve volunteered about this, perhaps you could say something about that? }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, I don\rquote t want to be - I\rquote 
m not going to give you a long disquisition, if you were attracted by structuralism but thought it was too scientistic, too structuralist \endash  which is my quarrel with Althusser \endash  yo
u are influenced by the post-structuralists who take questions of structure seriously, but are interested in pulling it out, framing it. So the critique of essentialism, which I\rquote 
ve just given you in relation to blackness, is that post-structuralists take on blackness - you know, it doesn\rquote 
t believe in essentialism. It questions any essentialism. Is composed of more than one thing. Ends and beginnings are resting points, not teleological things built into the real world. When you write history, it has a begin
ning, middle and an end, because books have a beginning, middle and end, but history, well, when does history actually start and finish? And what will its finish look like? It doesn\rquote t. So the critique of essentialism, Derrida says, \'93
Difference used to be thought of as binaries\'94 \endash  black and white; red and green - and you can build up a language from that, red means stop, green means go. When you have green, everybody goes, when you have the red, everybody stops. It\rquote 
s a language. Language of traffic signs. And it exploits the binary. But what Derrida and others say is that, actually, \'93
Difference is not like that. Difference is a set of positions along a very long spectrum in which there is no origin and no final end, except as abstract\'94 - and it\rquote s hard to think of a spectrum that doesn\rquote 
t have a beginning and an end, so you have to have one. But that\rquote s not what\rquote s important. It\rquote s the passage from one differential position to another which really is the thing to go for. It has a long history, and it has a complica
ted and ambiguous history in Marx\rquote s work, because in one sense you would say, \'93Marx was absolutely the opposite of that\'94, which is what a lot of Marxist critics would say. Marx was interested in the totality. But, you know, Marx says, when he
\rquote s talking about language, \'93The differentiae, specifici, what is different about one language from another is more important than the fact there is language\'94
. Of course there is language, it is a constituent of the human, but what really interests us is why Assyrian Babylonian is different from contemporary French, and what is carried in that difference. So it\rquote 
s part of my long reorientation from an attempt to get a total explanation, everything in the world, to the acceptance of difference. Once you open yourself to the
 acceptance of difference, look exactly what happens. What happens is, you can see, now, why race matters, because it is a matter of difference. You can see, now, why sexuality contains a deep ambiguity, because it is founded on a principle of male hegemo
ny, of a certain kind of sexuality. Once you open that up, all hell breaks loose! So it\rquote s a kind of mode of thinking. Yes? To respect difference. I believe, you know, as a sort of wedge, what Gramsci calls a \'93hope\'94, and Bloch calls a \'93
wager\'94, as a sort of b
et, that at one period, some point in the future, one of these speculative points, everybody will come together and love everybody else. But between here and there is just differences. Some of them can be appropriated dangerously, they can become the basi
s of genocide, of race hatred, of sex hatred, of class hatred, etc., but you can\rquote t do without the concept of difference. You couldn\rquote t understand any of them without the concept of difference. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 So which of your works could you cite which is particularly post-structuralist? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 I think most of my work after the big essay, which was called, \'93Coming to terms with Althusser\'94, but it then went on to be, \'93
A Reading of Marx\rquote s 1858 Preface to the Grundrisse\'94, which is his most methodological text, and which I have been very influenced by. That\rquote 
s the moment when I begin to think against the orthodoxy of the totality and total explanations and so on. I accept a lower level of explanatory reach, as it were! Everything after that begins to be influenced by this kind of thinking \endash 
 Foucault, Modern Critical Thought, Benjamin Bahktin, and then Levi-Strauss, Roland , Derrida. I\rquote m not sycophantic about any of them, and I\rquote m not really their scholar either. I\rquote m not really interested in making a critique of Derrida, 
half of it I don\rquote t understand, and a lot of it, I think, is probably nonsense. But when Derrida talks about \'93difference\'94, I think he has given me an idea which I will worry at, worry at, worry at, I\rquote 
ll try to apply it to racial difference, I\rquote ll try to apply it to sexual difference. Yes. That\rquote s the curse of having a magpie mind, and being rather brutal about it. I don\rquote t give a damn whether - well, that\rquote 
s really very excessive, and will go down, forever against me! (LAUGHS) But in a way, I don\rquote t give a damn what the paradigm is out of which it comes. I\rquote m not inattentive to that, because you can\rquote 
t just pluck the idea, so it has to be an idea that has been worked on with some systematic rigour and application by whoever\rquote s working on it. But I want to appropriate 
it for uses that he or she did not think of. I want to go on thinking this. That\rquote s what theory is about. There is what Foucault called \'93a tool to go on thinking with\'94. It\rquote 
s not a thing in itself. Cultural theory is not a kind of status to become. Cultural 
theory is certainly not what cultural studies is about! Cultural studies is the application of some of those concepts about culture to the concrete historical world. So the reason why I think you\rquote re puzzled, \'93
Well, where did this appear in different work?\'94 is because I\rquote ve never tried to state it in the abstract, and that is my weakness. You find it, therefore, buried, you find a passage on difference in my essay on multiculturalism, for instance. }{
