\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, you might say all of the influence of post-structuralist work on difference is in that paragraph, but I\rquote 
m not going to tell you a theoretical thing about it. I don\rquote t work at that level of distraction. I work at the interface between the concept and the concrete. And that\rquote s because Marx said \endash  and I\rquote m following the 1858 \endash  
\'93Well, you can start thinking with a chaotic abstraction, but you can only refine it by adding more and more concrete levels of determination. And what that does is to produce the concrete in thought\'94. That\rquote s a wonderful phrase! \'93
To produce the concrete in thought\'94, and that\rquote s what my work has been trying to be about. I\rquote m not anti-theoretical - I mean, quite the opposite. I don\rquote t think you can get anywhere without concepts, but it\rquote 
s not my job to produce concepts one after another. Books on concepts - not mine. It\rquote s not a critique, other people have other jobs to do! But one has to think as one can think, up to a certain point. I was very late - I thought, \'93You can
\rquote t go on thinking this\'94: relentlessly eclectic, popping this idea with that idea, trying that out, etc., and then you feel, \'93Well, I might as well give up\'94. You have to think along the grain you can think with, it isn\rquote 
t anything else. You can\rquote t make yourself Hegel. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
