\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Yes, Sartre was very important, but not for long. Sartre is a good example of somebody who gave you some good ideas, but when you look at it further, they\rquote re not the ones that stuck with me. But I was interested in, particularly, in Sartre\rquote 
s work - I wasn\rquote t tremendously interested in existentialism, but I was interested in the more social application of Sartre\rquote s work, and especially in the little book he published, c
alled, The Question of Method. And in The Question of Method the thing that I remember most is when he says, both Verlaine and Baudelaire were \'93 bourgeois poets\'94. So what? So what does that tell you about their poetry? You know! Nothing! It\rquote 
s lazy Marxism. It\rquote s Marxism of recognising what you already knew. You knew they\rquote re bourgeois, so they produce bourgeois poetry. Why don\rquote t they look the same? It doesn\rquote t. So that\rquote s not what\rquote 
s interesting about them. You accept that. They think within those patterns of thought, they live within those frames of existence. But that\rquote s not what\rquote s interesting about them, what\rquote 
s interesting is what do they add that makes them nevertheless produce a statement about that world which is so different from one to the other? And that 
is what Marxism is about. It must produce new knowledge, not the knowledge of recognising what you already knew. It\rquote s not to secure your sleep, in, \'93Oh well, it\rquote s true what I always believed, and look, here\rquote s another good example!
\'94 I always knew that the bourgeois produced that kind of work \endash  and there it is. That\rquote s not what it\rquote s about. That\rquote s what a lot of Marxism is about, reassuring us, \'93I really got hold of the truth there\'94, \'93
I can really analyse the world\'94, \'93It\rquote s going to go in a direction I would like it to go\'94, etc.. It\rquote s reassurance, it doesn\rquote t produce a new insight that you didn\rquote 
t have before you started the work. And Sartre insists on that. I took that idea from The End of Lazy Marxism, repetition of formuli, borrowed from Marx, borrowed from all o
ver Marx. When you look at Marx, of course, the early Marx is very different from the middle Marx, very different from the end. So there\rquote 
s no essential Marx. Marx of the early Economic and Philosophical Manuscripts, Marx of The Class Struggle in France, Ma
rx of Kapital. Well, of course, there are a lot of continuities, there are a tremendous amount of differences, which is what Saussure said about meaning \endash  if you want to mean something, you have to maintain some continuities and some differences. }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Now, I just want to ask you something about method - I hope you don\rquote t dislike this question, but obviously you\rquote 
re a qualitative researcher and you\rquote ve got this sort of literary critical basis originally, but did you ever feel you wanted to have anything to do with measuring and counting like a lot of social researchers do? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes, I did. No, I\rquote m not against that, I think it produces a certain kind of evidence. I don\rquote t think it\rquote 
s as hard an evidence as many people imagine it does, I think it depends a lot more on interpretation. People quote the figures, \'93that the figures prove\'94, and they don\rquote t prove - they may give greater weight to it. Some of the things they don
\rquote t take into consideration are that people don\rquote t know, when they answer questionnaires, they don\rquote t know. \'93Why do you think that?\'94 \'93Why do you think homosexuality is wrong?\'94 \'93Mmm, well, because the Bible says so\'94
, or, \'93It\rquote s against nature\'94. You can\rquote t say it\rquote s [against] nature, it doesn\rquote t appear in nature, because it appears all over the bloody place, and dogs are at it, and the cats are at it, so it\rquote 
s there, you know. They don\rquote t really know where the moral distinction falls. What can they tell you? They can tell you what they believe. \'93Do you believe that it\rquote s wrong?\'94 \'93Tick \lquote no\rquote \'94. But how they cam
e to that, and what follows from that, and what frames of interpretation are being drawn on to support that belief, that they can\rquote t tell you. It doesn\rquote t mean it\rquote s not worth counting how many people believe it, but don\rquote 
t think that you\rquote re at the end of the game when you\rquote ve done that, you\rquote re just at the beginning of the game. Now we know it\rquote s an important cultural formation \endash  this belief \endash  which affects practice, of course. So it
\rquote s pretty important to know whether it\rquote s very widespread, but how is it spread? W
hy does it take root in certain people, at certain times? Why does it become a public issue? Why is it just a question of morality and private belief? These are to take the numbers further. So it\rquote 
s not just that there are phases when I thought that was good, I thought that that was a very important kind of method, in the same way I think ethnography is a very important. More so, because there\rquote s more investment in the concrete, there\rquote 
s more an instance, it instantiates processes, you don\rquote t have to guess that it\rquote s happening, you can say, \'93Look at this life, it is happening here. This is how it happens. This is how they talk about it\'94
, and so on, so ethnography is very very rich. But an ethnography which is not related to wider social principles that you wouldn\rquote t capture in a questionnaire, what\rquote s the use of that? It doesn\rquote 
t really tell you anything. When I first read Durkheim, social facts are \'93things\'94, treats social facts as things, Durkheim was not stupid, he knew that there are mental processes, but he says it all happens in a black box, and we can\rquote 
t enter the black box. So if you\rquote re asking about morality, you should ask about the changing statistics of crime and deviance, that will tell you what the public morals and social morality is, and why, how it came about. Well, that\rquote 
s fine. A lot of Suicide didn\rquote t attempt to do that. But a funny American sociologist, not a very distinguished man, called Jack Douglas, wrote a book called, The Social Meanings of Suicide, and what he shows is the amount of actual substa
ntive material which is ad hoc into place by Durkheim. Why do Jews commit suicide more often? Well, the whole history of Judaism, the position of the Jews, anti-Semitism, all that is is implied by it, it\rquote 
s in the interpretative background to it, but what he produces is, \'93Well, don\rquote t worry about that, treat social factors as things\'94. Well, social factors are not just things, there are things and meanings and practices, and beliefs \endash 
 some of them wrong, many of them wrong. Still, what we believe to be true is true in its effects, including idiotic beliefs. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 I\rquote m afraid so! Well, I think I\rquote 
ve run out of questions about your work, I was wondering whether we could move on to life outside work, the sort of things you like to do when you\rquote re not working. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
