\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
What do I like to do? Well, when I was younger I liked playing sport. I played tennis well. I played squash. I like racquet games. I mean, I like to play racquet games, I was reasonably good at them \endash 
 so I like squash, I like badminton, I like tennis. I played cricket and football, but I wasn\rquote 
t wonderful at either of them. I took up squash quite late, and had a wonderful time playing squash, and I really realised what my age was when - I had a very close friend, a member of Policing the Crisis team \endash  T
ony Jefferson, we were very close, but he systematically beat me, and I thought, \'93I can\rquote t go on with this! He is just younger, fitter, faster than I am. I\rquote ve come to the end of squash!\'94 So I like sport. I\rquote 
m not one of these - I support Arsenal, but I\rquote m not going to lose my heart over it. In fact, I think they\rquote re a load of what my grandson calls, \'93a load of old rubbish\'94
 at the moment! (LAUGHS) But I like sport, and I watch sport on television sometimes \endash  not the big matches. I love watching the acrobatics. Beautiful stuff. I like swimming. So I have a general interest in the body, competitive body etc., but I
\rquote m not a sports person like that, I don\rquote t think, and when I could do it, I enjoyed doing that. What do I enjoy doing that is not related to things that I\rquote ve talked about? Well, I\rquote 
m not sure that I do. I love going to the cinema. Work. Play. Yes, I go to play, to the cinema, or a play, because I would go to things that most people think are not serious, because then things I think are not serious are very serious indeed! I can
\rquote t make the distinction. I watch more television than I ought to. I watch genre television because I like genre. I love the thriller, I love melodrama. I also like the great single works of exploration, of course. But I think that Tolst
oy was a great novelist, so is Raymond Chandler \endash  in a different mode. I\rquote ll never get from Chandler what I can get from Tolstoy, but likewise I\rquote 
ll never get that sharp precision language that you find in Chandler, from Tolstoy. The sentences are too expansive, the view of the world is enormous, the range of emotions, complexities, there\rquote 
s a difference in complexity, I agree with that, but I don\rquote t agree with ordering all artistic expressions according to some category of high and low, and excluding low, because I\rquote m not interested, principally, in the aesthetic value. I
\rquote m interested in their social value, and the popular, has massive social value, and has full of meanings, though they\rquote re very repetitive, and they can be compromised, and they\rquote re open to manipulation, and they\rquote 
re invaded by the profit motive. That\rquote s absolutely true. I do not hold with the notion that popular culture is an area of the authentic expression of working people. Sorry. Not that. It\rquote s a controversial area, it\rquote 
s a contradictory space \endash  the popular \endash  always. Always been. People always manipulated it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 So how did you keep in touch with your Jamaican culture? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
