\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Yes. Oh, sure. Yes. But I knew many more Jamaicans - not from my kind of social milieu and class background - in my middle years when I was at Birmingham, a lot more. But I knew, then, a much much wider range of peo
ple of all kinds and colours. As you get older, you know your closer friends, the circle draws in, there\rquote s more and more people with similar tastes, similar beliefs, similar styles of life, etc., it\rquote s a narrowing \endash 
 that is the narrowing of age. But in the 
middle, well I went to a political meeting and demonstration every other weekend. There were people that I organised things with who were different from people who were at the Centre, who were different from people who I played sport with, etc.. So I supp
o
se the honest answer is, I have always found it extremely difficult to make that distinction. Because work was not clearly defined in a set of routines, or associated with a particular location, or, indeed, connected to a particular definition of myself, 
then it just splurges all over everything, and work all the time, in a way. I\rquote m not at work a lot of the time when I\rquote m working! I don\rquote t think that\rquote s a way of evading your question, it really is how I feel it. And when I say it
\rquote s not even attached to a particular conception of myself, I\rquote ve never thought of myself, I\rquote ve never called myself an \'93academic\'94, never. It\rquote s where I made my living, it\rquote s where I loved to teach, it\rquote 
s where I worked with other people, wonderful things, but my ambition was not to be an academic. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 So what was your ambition? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
