\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 To be an intellectual \endash  the category doesn\rquote 
t exist! (LAUGHS) Yes, because, you know, unlike some other kinds of people whom I value very greatly, I couldn\rquote t let go of ideas. So if you\rquote re following an ideas vocation, you ought to be a certain kind of intellectual \endash  you\rquote 
re committed to ideas, you\rquote re committed to teasing them out, you\rquote re committed to critical thought, you\rquote re committed to unravelling problems, etc.. So I wanted to be an intellectual, always wanted to be an intellectual, but I wasn
\rquote t interested \'85 wasn\rquote t what I defined as my profession. I didn\rquote t particularly care whether I was a sociologist, or a cultural - while I\rquote d got a job I\rquote d stay alive materially, but then I tried to as much to do, under w
hatever heading, the work that I wanted to do. I think I told you that the Vice-Chancellor of the Open University said, \'93Well, you\rquote re coming from the Centre for Cultural Studies, you\rquote 
ve never had a sociology degree, are you willing to profess sociology?\'94 I said, \'93I\rquote m willing to profess anything that\rquote s likely to give me a job just now!\'94
 (LAUGHS) I was only half-joking, because I wanted to move from the Centre, I thought my time at the Centre at finished \endash  I should get out and allow the Centre to develop along its own pathway. So I had to find a job, and there weren\rquote 
t any Cultural Studies Departments, so I was going to wear somebody else\rquote s hat anyway, but I wasn\rquote t going to pretend that I was a sociologist of a mainstream kind. I didn\rquote t want to be, but then again, that couldn\rquote t be, I
\rquote d never been taught to be. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
