\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 
Well, very few of my friends at school do I now see very often, but some of them have been very important. A lot of them [were] not actually people I was with at school, but younger people whom I met when I went back, who were involved in the political fe
rment in the seventies. Yes? At the University, the period when Jamaica became a black society in its own consciousness, when civil rights and Black Power ideas and reggae and all of those things \endash  that\rquote 
s the seventies generation. My friend David Scott belongs to that. My friend, Hugh Small, was a lawyer, and Richard \endash  his brother \endash 
 lawyers, still in Jamaica. Both were very close to Manley for a time. That generation of people I still know, although I don\rquote t see them very much, because I don\rquote t go to Jamaica very much now, and they haven\rquote t been here. That\rquote 
s why I asked you about when is the cut-off point. Well, as you can imagine, then there are people like Mike Rustin. I met Mike Rustin very shortly after I came to England in the fifties, and I married his sister-in-law! He\rquote 
s been involved in the New Left, so I\rquote ve known Mike ever since he walked into a New Left Club meeting. I think I\rquote ve described it to you, yes? We\rquote ve shared many projects, although we\rquote re not the same kind of people really. But we
\rquote ve shared many common interests in projects, both personal and political, artistic, and all of that \endash  so that\rquote s somebody I\rquote 
ve known for a long time. When I was in Oxford, in my second and third and fourth and fifth years, I left College and went to live in a student house \endash  I think I\rquote 
ve described that to you too. Well, I knew a lot of West Indians then, who lived in the house \endash  I\rquote ve described them to you. They are people who went back to work in the first phase of Independence \endash 
 Scotty Lewis, Dodd Jermaine, Willy Demas, [Ridge Alleyne], etc., all these lived in the house. But they can\rquote t be friends in quite the way in which you mean, because I don\rquote 
t see them. They went back to Trinidad, I stayed here, so the decision to stay makes a break, a fundamental break in a lot of 
continuing friendships, so my continuities are not easy to record. I can tell you people who meant a lot to me at a particular moment, some of whom I\rquote ve continued through. All of them have continued in my head, they\rquote 
re my interlocutors, but that\rquote s not because I see them all the time. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
