\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, yes, somebody I met at Oxford very early on, and I\rquote 
m not going to remember his name, who was a little bit older than me [Grae
me Martin]. Literary critic, a really important interesting literary critic, who then went on to teach at the Open University. Anyhow, he taught at the Open University, and he and his wife \endash  he married his landlady \endash 
 and I used to go and see them a lot. And he died quite recently. She died. Both Catherine and I, when we got married, we used to go and see them, and I saw him right until he died a few years ago. So that\rquote s another long trail. I\rquote 
ll tell you about the house in Oxford. I met three or four English people there, whom I\rquote ve continued to know \endash  two women, one called Tessa, who I still keep in touch with, phone all the time, she sends me tracts. She\rquote 
s a very interesting, lovely woman, and she was very influenced by the milieu, and so she married an Ital
ian, who had been in the War, got a GI grant and came here to do art, and went to Ruskin College, and she married him. But her two children, one child has married a black woman, and she then adopted two black girls for her daughters. So I got to know her,
 and she got to know us. She has been to see some of the people who lived in that house \endash  in the Caribbean \endash  more recently than I have. So that\rquote s a long continuity, that\rquote s from about 1952 onwards. Then there\rquote 
s the political people from the sixties onwards, 
and then there are students from the seventies, who are my close friends, and most of them live in England, and so I see them much more often. So, for instance, I mentioned Tony Jefferson, John Clarke, and Charles Critcher I don\rquote 
t see so much because he\rquote s 
not in London very much. But those people whom I worked with, I see a lot. So I could pick out people from each of those groups. There would be a sequence of moments, but if they were nearby, or we kept contact, they would continue to be close friends. Bu
t I don\rquote t think they\rquote re what you mean. What you mean is, have I had a lifelong friend throughout my life? And the answer to that is no. I haven\rquote t. The break with the past and Jamaica was, in that sense, radical and profound. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 So you\rquote ve been really getting new friends in each stage. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
