\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Yes. Yep. And, of course, I got married in \rquote 64, quite early on! (LAUGHS) I suppose, in that sense, it\rquote 
s as if I were on my own for a very long period of time. I more or less gave up my family, not formally but I broke with them [and for] a long time I didn\rquote t go back. When I went back, I already could see them, what they were. I wasn\rquote 
t going to have a confrontation with them, but I could see them for what they were, and I had a way of understanding how they\rquote d have to form me, which I hated. So that was a radical break. And since then, I\rquote ve been in England, I don\rquote 
t have close relatives in England to begin with. I\rquote ve made friends, had to do my work, and live, and form a social world, and get involved in politics, and enjoy the arts and culture and so on, all on my own. I\rquote 
m not boasting about it, , I just mean I am, in that sense, a more solitary person. I regret not having a lifelong friend who goes back to my childhood. I have one or two still in Jamaica. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
