\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Interesting. Yes, you\rquote ve mentioned Catherine again. What about the children, could you just briefly say what\rquote 
s happened to them? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
\par 
\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Well, Catherine and I got married in \rquote 64. She finished her undergraduate work, began to do post-graduate work, and then Be
cky was born. Becky was born in \rquote 68 \endash 
 a testing time! We were in occupation in Birmingham, Catherine was on the floor in the Great Hall, (LAUGHS) raised up off the floor, and by Boxing Day in the Maternity Home, having Becky. And Jess was born two years later. And we didn\rquote 
t decide not to have any more, but as it turned out, we didn\rquote t have any more. I was fortunate in having one of each, which I really wanted. I say \'93I really wanted\'94, but I was pretty convinced, when I got through my early twenties and came 
into my later twenties, and people were not - you know, I had not formed a serious attachment, other than a friendship one with lots of people. For instance, there\rquote s a woman called Suzie Benghiat, who was around early New Left, lives in Paris, I
\rquote ve known her all my life. I went to Jamaica with her. Her brother worked in Jamaica as a builder. So Suzie is a lifelong, but lifelong in England friend. She doesn\rquote t live in England any more. She\rquote 
s quite old, quite ill, living in Paris. I think of Suzie as part of the furnishing of my mind. So it\rquote s been an odd route like that. Well, the kids were born, and I had never expected to have children, because I thought, \'93Well, you\rquote 
re not seriously attached to anybody, and you\rquote re 26, 27, 28\'94. I was 32 when I was married \endash  qu
ite late. So I thought I would never have any children really, probably. So they came - first of all Catherine, then I did have a serious relationship \endash  which lasted the rest of my life \endash 
 and then the two kids. So that was both of them, fulfilment of something. There was no question that I thought my daughter, when she was born, was the most beautiful and sensational thing in the world! Catherine and I completely backgrounded, you\rquote 
re in love with this baby, you know! (LAUGHS) Have lost you! I was completely besotted with her, and she was a very very beautiful baby \endash  straight black hair, huge black eyes, wonderful child! And then two years later, Jess came \endash 
 quite different. In those days - though he\rquote s now as thin as a rake \endash  a rather plump baby. We had a Bab
ygro which had rings, different colours, and he looked exactly like the Michelin man, running along the sand where we used to go for holidays in Cornwall, with his grandmother \endash  Catherine\rquote s mum \endash 
 kicking a football, age one and a half, or two or something!
 (LAUGHS) Quite different. And the two of them are different. I very much enjoyed their childhood. I cannot tell you that I enjoyed without some reservations their adolescence! Actually, Becky was not a big problem, but Jess was in a rage with me, as adol
escents often are, so that was not easy. But, what should I say? They\rquote re the people I think about all the time, they\rquote re amongst my most closest familiars. Catherine, Catherine\rquote s sister Margaret, these are people very close to me 
\endash  the inner core. But, on the other hand, as I\rquote ve said, there are these groups of other people. In the nineties, late eighties and nineties, when we moved to London, I got to know all those Feminists, you know, whom I really didn\rquote 
t know before that \endash  Sally Alexander, Barbara Taylor - on and on and on. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
