\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Margaret \endash  my sister-in-law \endash 
 ran the psychotherapy training at the Tavistock, and Becky went to Sussex, got a very good degree, started her Ph.D., and taking a quick look at both parents, she didn\rquote 
t want to be an academic (LAUGHS), and left, and went to the Tavi and trained as an analytic child psychotherapist. She works in the Child and Family Centre in Willesden. She\rquote s now training as an adult analyst. Jess got through \lquote A\rquote 
 Level quite well \endash  complete mystery to everybody! Complete mystery! I mean, his set book was Middlemarch, I don\rquote 
t know that Jess ever read it, or how much of it he ever read. Anyhow he wrote quite well. So he did that. Then he went to Sussex to do anthropology. At the end of the second term he said, \'93I can\rquote 
t stand this. I wanted to learn about the modern world, about Africa and all that\'94 \endash  he was in his African phase, locks down to his knees, etc. - \'93And all they\rquote re telling me about is the Nuer!\'94 Poo
r old Evans-Pritchard, and these dead colonials! \'93So what are you going to do?\'94 \'93Leave. Or either you\rquote re going to take my exams for me, or I\rquote m going to leave!\'94 Well, that was Hobson\rquote s choice there. So he left. I said, \'93
What are you going to do?\'94 \'93I\rquote m going to go to Art School. I\rquote m going to complete my portfolio, and try to get into a foundation course in Art\'94. Which he did, in Camberwell. And from there he went to St. Martin\rquote 
s, where he did film and photography I wasn\rquote t sure whether he was ever going to make a living at this, and it was kind of a wild course at St. Martin\rquote s, a course very influenced by high theory screen at the time. I remember Jess saying, \'93
They tell me my images are too seductive\'94, and, \'93you like narrative too much\'94, and, \'93your tastes are too broad. There are really only two and a half really good films\'94
. It was very very mandarin approach, and not his approach at all, though he\rquote s very very refined, aesthetically, in his judgement, but he\rquote s not at all precious about it. Anyhow, in his secon
d year, they arranged for students to go for a whole summer to a New York - NYU \endash 
 to a summer course which they ran for professionals who had never had an academic training, in the film industry. When he came back, he was completely professionalized, he\rquote d produced five short films. It was just a transformation. And he\rquote 
s never looked back since then. He\rquote s very professional about his work, he and a friend made a commercial when they were still at the end of being students, which Nike bought \endash  a film made in N
otting Hill, with black kids, but they bought it for Eastern Europe! And he\rquote s had work ever since then. He worked mainly in commercials, because that\rquote s how you make the money, but it\rquote 
s always been the intention to get further and further into feature film, which he\rquote s done. He\rquote s shot now, several films. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
