\par Stuart:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3228552\charrsid3228552 Oh, my God, Paul! What a question! Well, undoubtedly the worst thing for 
me was coming to understand what was the source of my profound alienation from my family, and that was not just a familial or emotional question, it was about being a colonial, and the way in which they had adapted to it, and I could not adapt to it, hate
d the person they wanted me to be \endash  who would adapt \endash  and being the person that I was, who wouldn\rquote t adapt, but found it difficult to be something else. That\rquote s the big chasm in my life. That\rquote 
s resulted in the fact that I not only chose to study abroad, but decided not to go back. So that\rquote s a life-changing decision. And you can hear in almost everything I say that there\rquote s before and after structure, and that\rquote 
s because [of] leaving Jamaica, coming to terms with all of that. A very difficult life, and by far the worst thing. I\rquote ve had many other very bad experiences, but not in the existential sense in which I think you mean it. What\rquote 
s the best thing? Well, I will tell you two. One is what I said at my 80th birthday. I don\rquote t think my work and me are very important. I really don\rquote t. But I have been alive in interesting times. I really have been \endash 
 end of colonialism; Welfare State; Thatcherism; the Centre for Cultural Studies; anti-racism; Feminism; the social movements; black arts. An incredible gift to have had all 
those, and in each one I have been able to work creatively with a group of people involved in those things. That\rquote s the great boon of my life \endash 
 work-wise. Personally, the great boon of my life is having married Catherine which was - you know, I\rquote m not saying that just because that\rquote 
s the right thing to say. You know, from what I said, I was a pretty lost soul by the time of my thirties. I\rquote d chosen to stay, I was going to stay. I didn\rquote t feel at one with England, I didn\rquote t feel English, so I wasn\rquote 
t going anywhere. I wasn\rquote t in a long-term relationship, hadn\rquote t had any children. I was in a bad way really, and she absolutely saved my life. Fourteen years younger than me, not yet gone to university, I imagine she can\rquote 
t possibly have known what she was doing. What would an 18, 19-year old girl, just done wonderful \lquote A\rquote  Levels, going to Sussex, pick up with a 32-year old Jamaican man from the Left, why would you do it? But she did. She rescued me \endash 
 which is a funny way round, you know, but she rescued me. Then there was a long period - which I think I\rquote ve talked about, so if I have, just stop me \endash 
 when she suffered, nevertheless, from the fact that I was the older one, I was partly established, people knew about me, they thought, \'93Who is this flipperty-jibbet that he\rquote s gotten involved with?\'94 \'93
What is he doing with robbing the cradle?\'94 and so on. And my work was important, not only to me, to us, but because of how other people saw me, and she was - I couldn\rquote t remember what she was, etc.. Then we passed through the trough. With
 Feminism and onwards, she has asserted herself, won her own independence, got her space. A different person. Acknowledged the differences between us, lived those differences, become a historian, she shared a great deal of interest, began in Feminism, pub
lished work, moved to [research in] Jamaica. She knows \endash  I think I\rquote ve said \endash 
 more about Jamaica now than I ever knew. But, nevertheless, she made that happen for herself, not because of me. So the relationship between us has not only equalised, but has been reversed. So now, you know, I am 80, and getting old, and she\rquote 
s 66, with her creative life still opening up ahead of her. A tragedy, of course, we\rquote ll never be on holiday, we\rquote ll never be that idyllic picture of two people who have been in love all their li
ves, who then have a retirement together and do all sorts of things together, we\rquote ll never have it. So that\rquote s a matter for regret, but I can\rquote 
t regret the fact that, as I would put it, nevertheless, I stole her life. I stole her youth from her. So I can\rquote t forget that. But that is what - I don\rquote t know about the best, it\rquote 
s just the most important transforming thing that ever happened to me. Of course. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7739222\charrsid7739222 
